{"title_page": "Shakib Al Hasan", "text_new": "{{Fanpov|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2013}} \n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2013}}\n{{short description|Bangladeshi cricketer}}\n{{Infobox cricketer\n| name = \u09b8\u09be\u0995\u09bf\u09ac\u09c7\u09b0 \u09ac\u0989 \u09aa\u09b0\u09cd\u09a6\u09be \u0995\u09b0\u09c7 \u09a8\u09be\n| image = Shakib Al Hasan (4) (cropped).jpg\n| caption = Shakib in 2018\n| fullname = Shakib Al Hasan\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1987|3|24|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Magura District]], [[Bangladesh]]\n| heightm = 1.75\n| batting = Left-handed\n| bowling = [[Slow left-arm orthodox]]\n| role = [[All-rounder]]\n| country = Bangladesh\n| international = true\n| internationalspan = 2006\u2013present\n| testdebutdate = 18 May\n| testdebutyear = 2007\n| testdebutagainst = India\n| testcap = 46\n| lasttestdate = 5 September\n| lasttestyear = 2019\n| lasttestagainst = Afghanistan\n| odidebutdate = 6 August\n| odidebutyear = 2006\n| odidebutagainst = Zimbabwe\n| odicap = 82\n| lastodidate = 5 July\n| lastodiyear = 2019\n| lastodiagainst = Pakistan\n| odishirt = 75\n| T20Idebutdate = 28 November\n| T20Idebutyear = 2006\n| T20Idebutagainst = Zimbabwe\n| T20Icap = 11\n| lastT20Ifor = Bangladesh\n| lastT20Iagainst = Afghanistan\n| lastT20Idate = 21 September\n| lastT20Iyear = 2019\n| club1 = [[Khulna Division cricket team|Khulna Division]]\n| year1 = 2004\u20132019\n| club2 = [[Worcestershire County Cricket Club|Worcestershire]]\n| year2 = 2010\u20132011\n| club3 = [[Kolkata Knight Riders]]\n| year3 = 2011\u20132017\n| clubnumber3 = 75\n| club4 = [[Khulna Royal Bengals]]\n| year4 = 2012\n| club5 = [[Uthura Rudras]]\n| year5 = 2012\n| club6 = [[Dhaka Gladiators]]\n| year6 = 2013\n| club7 = [[Leicestershire County Cricket Club|Leicestershire]]\n| year7 = 2013\n| club8 = [[Barbados Tridents]]\n| year8 = 2013, 2018\u20132019\n| clubnumber8 = 75\n| club9 = [[Adelaide Strikers]]\n| year9 = 2014\n| clubnumber9 = 75\n| club10 = [[Melbourne Renegades]]\n| year10 = 2015\n| clubnumber10 = 75\n| club11 = [[Rangpur Riders]]\n| year11 = 2015\n| club12 = [[Karachi Kings]]\n| year12 = 2016\n| clubnumber12 = 75\n| club13 = [[Jamaica Tallawahs]]\n| year13 = 2016\u20132017\n| clubnumber13 = 75\n| club14 = [[Dhaka Dynamites]]\n| year14 = 2016\u20132019\n| clubnumber14 = 75\n| club15 = [[Peshawar Zalmi]]\n| year15 = 2017\u20132018\n| clubnumber15 = 77\n| club16 = [[Sunrisers Hyderabad]]\n| year16 = 2018\u20132019\n| clubnumber16 = 75\n| columns = 4\n| column1 = [[Test cricket|Test]]\n| column2 = [[One Day International|ODI]]\n| column3 = [[Twenty20 International cricket|T20I]]\n| column4 = [[First-class cricket|FC]]\n| matches1 = 56\n| matches2 = 206\n| matches3 = 76\n| matches4 = 92\n| runs1 = 3,862\n| runs2 = 6,323\n| runs3 = 1,567\n| runs4 = 5,777\n| bat avg1 = 39.40\n| bat avg2 = 37.86\n| bat avg3 = 23.74\n| bat avg4 = 37.27\n| 100s/50s1 = 5/24\n| 100s/50s2 = 9/47\n| 100s/50s3 = 0/9\n| 100s/50s4 = 8/34\n| top score1 = 217\n| top score2 = 134[[not out|*]]\n| top score3 = 84\n| top score4 = 217\n| deliveries1 = 13,020\n| deliveries2 = 10,517\n| deliveries3 = 1,667\n| deliveries4 = 19,170\n| wickets1 = 210\n| wickets2 = 260\n| wickets3 = 92\n| wickets4 = 310\n| bowl avg1 = 31.12\n| bowl avg2 = 30.21\n| bowl avg3 = 20.58\n| bowl avg4 = 30.03\n| fivefor1 = 18\n| fivefor2 = 2\n| fivefor3 = 1\n| fivefor4 = 23\n| tenfor1 = 2\n| tenfor2 = 0\n| tenfor3 = 0\n| tenfor4 = 2\n| best bowling1 = 7/36\n| best bowling2 = 5/29\n| best bowling3 = 5/20\n| best bowling4 = 7/32\n| catches/stumpings1 = 24/\u2013\n| catches/stumpings2 = 50/\u2013\n| catches/stumpings3 = 19/\u2013\n| catches/stumpings4 = 47/\u2013\n| source = http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh/content/player/56143.html ESPNcricinfo\n| date = 21 September \n| year = 2019\n}}\n'''Shakib Al Hasan''' ({{lang-bn|\u09b8\u09be\u0995\u09bf\u09ac \u0986\u09b2 \u09b9\u09be\u09b8\u09be\u09a8}}; born 24 March 1987) is a Bangladeshi international [[cricket]]er who has played all three formats of the game. Internationally, Shakib has been recognised as one of the greatest all-rounders of all time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://iccrankings.cricket.com.pk/allrounder/|title=All Rounder Rankings|publisher=|accessdate=27 October 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricket.com.au/news/feature/shakib-al-hasan-bangaldesh-worlds-number-one-allrounder/2015-01-17|title=Bangladesh's finest pursues greatness|publisher=|accessdate=27 October 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/education/story/bangladeshi-player-shakib-al-hasan-named-best-all-rounder-in-all-formats-by-international-cricket-council/1/447455.html|title=Bangladeshi Player Shakib Al Hasan named best all-rounder in all formats by ICC: Some interesting facts about the cricketer : Sports Arena|publisher=|accessdate=27 October 2016}}</ref> He was ranked as one of the world's most famous athletes by [[ESPN.com|ESPN]] WORLD FAME 100 in 2019.<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.espn.com/espn/feature/story/_/id/26113613/espn-world-fame-100-2019#shakib-al-hasan |title=Shakib in the list of ESPN WORLD FAME 100 in 2019 |publisher=ESPN|accessdate=13 March 2019}}</ref>\nHis aggressive left-handed batting style in the [[batting order (cricket)|middle order]], controlled [[Left-arm orthodox spin|slow left-arm orthodox]] bowling, and athletic fielding has helped him win trophies in top leagues across the world.<ref>{{cricinfo|id=56143|accessdate=25 September 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/18515383/curious-case-shakib-al-hasan|title=The curious case of Shakib Al Hasan|work=ESPNcricinfo|access-date=2018-07-13}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, Shakib became the first and only cricketer in history to be ranked the 'No.1 all-rounder' by [[International Cricket Council|ICC]] in its [[ICC Player Rankings|Player Rankings]] in all three formats of the game (Test, Twenty20 and One Day Internationals).<ref>{{citation|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/sports/cricket/story/shakib-al-hasan-ranked-best-testodi-and-t20-all-rounder-in-icc-player-rankings-259782-2015-06-26|title=Shakib ranked number one all-rounder in all three formats  |publisher=India Today |accessdate=26 June 2019}}</ref> He is currently ranked no.1 in odis and no.2 in tests and t-20s. On 13 January 2017, he registered the highest individual score (217) by a Bangladeshi batsman in Tests.<ref>{{Cite web |first=Alagappan |last=Muthu|date=12 January 2017|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/new-zealand-v-bangladesh-2016-17/content/story/1077214.html |title=Mominul, Tamim sparkle on rain-hit day |website=ESPNcricinfo |access-date=25 September 2017}}</ref> In November 2018, he became the first bowler for Bangladesh to [[List of Bangladesh Test cricket records#Most Wickets|take 200 wickets in Tests]].<ref name=\"SAH200\">{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/25359369/shakib-al-hasan-becomes-quickest-3000-runs-200-wickets-double |title=Shakib becomes the quickest to 3000 runs-200 wickets double |work=ESPN Cricinfo |accessdate=24 November 2018}}</ref> In June 2019, Shakib became the fastest player to score 6,000 runs and take 250 wickets in ODIs in just 199 matches.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bdcrictime.com/shakib-al-hasan-fastest-to-reach-6000-runs-and-250-wickets-in-odis/ |title=Shakib Al Hasan fastest to reach 6000 runs and 250 wickets in ODIs |work=BDCricTime |accessdate=28 June 2019}}</ref> He is the highest run scorer as well as the highest wicket taker for Bangladesh in ICC ODI World Cups. He is also the only cricketer to score 1000 runs and to take 30 wickets in World Cup. At the [[2019 Cricket World Cup]], Shakib became the first cricketer to score 600{{nbsp}}runs and take 10{{nbsp}}wickets in a single World Cup.\n\nOn 29 October 2019, the [[International Cricket Council]] (ICC) banned Shakib from all cricket for two years, with one year suspended, after breaching the ICC's Anti-Corruption Code.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.icc-cricket.com/media-releases/1473892 |title=Shakib Al Hasan banned after accepting three charges under ICC Anti-Corruption Code |work=International Cricket Council |accessdate=29 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Early years and youth cricket==\nBorn in [[Magura District|Magura]], [[Khulna Division|Khulna]], Shakib started playing cricket at an early age. According to ''[[Prothom Alo]]'' sports editor Utpal Shuvro, Shakib \"was fairly proficient at cricket and was often hired to play for different villages and teams\".<ref name=\"From Magura to No. 1\">{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/magazine/content/story/389383.html |title=From Magura to No. 1 |first=Utpal |last=Shuvro |work=ESPNcricinfo |date=6 February 2009 |accessdate=31 October 2010}}</ref> In one of those matches, Shakib impressed an umpire who arranged for him to practice with the Islampur Para Club, a team in the Magura Cricket League. During the practice session, Shakib batted aggressively and bowled fast, as he usually did, but also chose to experiment with spin bowling which proved to be not so effective. He was picked to play for Islampur and took a wicket with his first ball; it was his first delivery with a proper cricket ball, having previously played with a [[tape ball|taped tennis ball]].{{Citation needed|date=August 2019}} He spent six months training at [[Bangladesh Krira Shiksha Pratisthan]],<ref name=\"From Magura to No. 1\"/> a government-run sports institute.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.bkspbd.org/why_bksp.html |title=About BKSP |publisher=Bangladesh Krira Shikkha Protishtan |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100130201357/http://www.bkspbd.org/why_bksp.html |archive-date=30 January 2010 |accessdate=23 February 2011}}</ref> and in 2004, at the age of 17, was drafted by [[Khulna Division cricket team|Khulna]] to play in the National Domestic League.\n\nShakib first represented Bangladesh at the U-19 level, debuting in August 2006 against [[Zimbabwe national cricket team|Zimbabwe]] at [[Harare Sports Club]]. He played an important part in Bangladesh's victory, where he scored 30 runs and bowled out [[Elton Chigumbura]] to get his first ODI wicket.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/249207.html|work=ESPNcricinfo|title=Scorecard: Bangladesh tour of Zimbabwe, 5th ODI: Zimbabwe v Bangladesh at Harare, 6 August 2006}}</ref> In 2005, during the final of a tri-nation tournament involving England and Sri Lanka's Under-19 teams, Shakib scored an 86-ball century and took three wickets to lead his team to victory.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh/content/story/229488.html |title=Saqibul Hasan blasts Bangladesh to victory|work=[[ESPNcricinfo]] |date=13 December 2005 |accessdate=7 November 2009}}</ref> Between 2005 and 2006, Shakib played 18&nbsp;youth One Day Internationals; he scored 563&nbsp;runs at an [[Batting average (cricket)|average]] of 35.18, and took 22&nbsp;wickets at an [[bowling average|average]] of 20.18.<ref>{{citation |url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/73/73152/73152.html |title=Shakib Al Hasan |work=CricketArchive|url-access=subscription |accessdate=7 November 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Domestic and T20 franchise cricket==\nDomestically Shakib has represented Khulna since 2004, and in 2010 spent several months playing for [[Worcestershire County Cricket Club|Worcestershire]] in England, becoming the first Bangladeshi player to represent an [[County cricket|English county cricket]] team. For the [[2011 Indian Premier League]], Shakib was contracted by [[Kolkata Knight Riders]]. Shakib was released by KKR and was picked up by [[Sunrisers Hyderabad]] in the [[List of 2018 Indian Premier League personnel changes|2018 IPL personnel changes]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thedailystar.net/sports/bangladesh-cricket/shakib-al-hasan-gaining-confidence-each-sunrisers-hyderabad-session-1558471|title=Shakib al hasan gaining confidence each sunrisershyderabad session|website=dailystar.net}}</ref> In the [[2012 Bangladesh Premier League|first season of Bangladesh Premier League]], he captained [[Khulna Royal Bengals]], and in the [[2013 Bangladesh Premier League|second season]] he led [[Dhaka Gladiators]] to the tournament title. In the [[2015 Bangladesh Premier League|2015 season]] he played for [[Rangpur Riders]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thedailystar.net/sports/icons-find-teams-bpl-161047|title=BPL: Shakib to lead Rangpur, Mushfiq Sylhet, Tamim Ctg|work=The Daily Star}}</ref> and from [[2016 Bangladesh Premier League|2016 season]] he is playing for [[Dhaka Dynamites]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://m.bdnews24.com/en/detail/cricket/1248843|title=Dhaka Dynamites' Shakib wants to win BPL 2016|website=bdnews24.com}}</ref> Shakib represented [[Uthura Rudras]] in the [[2012 Sri Lanka Premier League]]. Shakib also played for [[Barbados Tridents]] in the [[2013 Caribbean Premier League]]. He played for [[Jamaica Tallawahs]] in both the [[2016 Caribbean Premier League|2016]] and [[2017 Caribbean Premier League|2017 season]] before returning to [[Barbados Tridents|Barbados]] for [[2018 Caribbean Premier League]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thedailystar.net/sports/cricket/shakibs-jamaica-conquer-cpl-1266748|title=Shakib's Jamaica conquer CPL|work=The Daily Star}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thedailystar.net/sports/bangladesh-cricket/shakib-al-hasan-replaced-steve-smith-barbados-tridents-1610815?amp|title=Shakib Al Hasan replaced by Steve Smith|work=The Daily Star}}</ref> He played for [[Adelaide Strikers]] in [[2014\u201315 Big Bash League season|2014]] replacing the injured [[Johan Botha (cricketer)|Johan Botha]], thus becoming the first Bangladeshi to play in the [[Big Bash League]].<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/big-bash-league-2013/content/story/706569.html |title=Shakib joins Adelaide Strikers|work=ESPNcricinfo |date=3 January 2014 |accessdate=3 January 2014}}</ref> For [[2015\u201316 Big Bash League|2015 season]] he was picked up by [[Melbourne Renegades]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thedailystar.net/shakib-to-play-for-melbourne-renegades-56888|title=Shakib to play for Melbourne Renegades}}</ref> For [[2016 Pakistan Super League]] he was picked up by [[Karachi Kings]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.banglanews24.com/sports/article/48146/Shakib-to-play-with-Karachi-Kings|title=Shakib to play with Karachi|website=banglanews24.com}}</ref> and in [[2017 Pakistan Super League|2017 season]] and  he played for [[Peshawar Zalmi]]<ref name=zalmi>{{cite web|url=https://www.dhakatribune.com/sport/cricket/2017/10/07/peshawar-retain-shakib-release-tamim-quetta-keep-mahmudullah|title=Peshawar retain Shakib, release Tamim as Quetta keep Mahmudullah|work=Dhaka Tribune}}</ref> He was supposed to play for the [[2018 Pakistan Super League|2018 season]] also but was injured at that time<ref name=zalmi /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thedailystar.net/sports/bangladesh-cricket/shakib-out-psl-1538398|title=Shakib Out of PSL|work=The Daily Star}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2019, he was selected to play for the Brampton Wolves franchise team in the [[2019 Global T20 Canada]] tournament.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.canadacricket.com/?p=12755 |title=Global T20 draft streamed live |work=Canada Cricket Online |accessdate=20 June 2019}}</ref> Shakib again played for Barbados in the [[2019 Caribbean Premier League|2019]] season.<ref>{{cite news\n| author =\n| title =Litton Das and Shakib Al Hasan fly to Caribbean to join in CPL\n| quote =\n| newspaper =bdcrictime.com\n| date =\n| pages =\n| url =https://www.bdcrictime.com/litton-das-and-shakib-al-hasan-fly-to-caribbean-to-join-in-cpl/amp/\n| accessdate =  \n}}</ref> He was released by the Sunrisers Hyderabad ahead of the [[List of 2020 Indian Premier League personnel changes|2020 IPL auction]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/28087425/where-do-eight-franchises-stand-2020-auction |title=Where do the eight franchises stand before the 2020 auction? |work=ESPN Cricinfo |accessdate=15 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\n===Debut years===\nShakib made his [[One Day International]] (ODI) debut against [[Zimbabwe cricket team|Zimbabwe]] on 6 August 2006, where he scored 30 runs and bowled out [[Elton Chigumbura]] to get his first ODI wicket.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/249207.html|work=ESPNcricinfo|title=Scorecard: Bangladesh tour of Zimbabwe, 5th ODI: Zimbabwe v Bangladesh at Harare, 6 August 2006}}</ref> He made his Test debut the following 6 May against [[India national cricket team|India]]. From January 2009 to April 2011 and again from March 2012, Shakib was ranked first amongst ODI all-rounders by the [[International Cricket Council|ICC]]. In December 2011, he became the world's top-ranked Test all-rounder. In December 2014 Shakib became the world's top ranked Twenty 20 all-rounder. He is currently the only all-rounder to be ranked in the top 3 of [[ICC Player Rankings]] across every format of international cricket.<ref name=\"Reliance ICC\">{{cite web | url=http://www.relianceiccrankings.com/| title=Reliance ICC Rankings | publisher=Reliance ICC | accessdate=25 October 2013}}</ref> In 2008, Shakib took at that time the best bowling figures by a Bangladesh player in Tests, 7&nbsp;wickets for 36&nbsp;runs, against [[New Zealand national cricket team|New Zealand]]. To date he is [[Bangladesh]]'s highest wicket taker in Test Matches.\n\nShakib was appointed Bangladesh's [[Captain (cricket)|vice-captain]] in June 2009. During Bangladesh's tour of the West Indies the following month, the captain [[Mashrafe Mortaza]] was injured and Shakib took over the captaincy. He was 22&nbsp;years old at the time. Initially a temporary position, Shakib's success against the [[West Indies]], securing his side's first overseas series win, ensured his retention of captaincy even after Mort recovered. Shakib was named ''[[The Wisden Cricketer]]'s'' \"Test Player of the Year\" in November 2009. In July 2010, he stepped down from the ODI captaincy to concentrate on his personal performance. Mortaza took over until he became injured again and Shakib was asked to resume leadership. This lasted until he was relieved of captaincy in September 2011 due to a poor World Cup campaign.\n\nIn 2015 after batting in the first match at [[2015 Cricket World Cup]], Hasan had a total of 4,040 runs in ODI matches and became the first Bangladeshi cricketer to score 4,000 runs in ODIs.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://bdnews24.com/cricket/2015/02/18/shakib-al-hasan-first-bangladesh-player-to-score-4000-odi-runs | title=Shakib Al Hasan first Bangladesh player to score 4,000 ODI runs | work=[[Bdnews24.com]] | date=18 February 2015 | accessdate=18 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Breakthrough (2006\u20132008)===\nShakib was included in Bangladesh's senior squad to tour Zimbabwe in February 2006. Along with [[Farhad Reza]] and [[Mushfiqur Rahim]], Shakib was one of the three uncapped players to be included in the squad.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/zimvbdesh/content/story/253971.html |title=Whatmore: 'Bangladesh are favourites'|work=ESPNcricinfo |date=20 July 2006 |accessdate=7 November 2009}}</ref> Shakib and Reza were described as \"very good cricketers in all departments of the game\", and Faruq Ahmed&nbsp;\u2013 the chief selector&nbsp;\u2013 said that Bangladesh had \"high hopes from them and it's time for them to perform at the international level\".<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/kenyavbdesh/content/story/252258.html |title=Bangladesh name young allrounders |work=ESPNcricinfo |date=3 July 2006 |accessdate=7 November 2009}}</ref> Shakib made his ODI debut on the tour on 6 August; his maiden wicket was that of all-rounder [[Elton Chigumbura]], and he finished with bowling figures of 1/39. He also scored 30&nbsp;not&nbsp;out while [[Shahriar Nafees]] scored his maiden ODI century to help Bangladesh win by eight&nbsp;wickets. It was the final match in the series, which Zimbabwe won 3\u20132.<ref>{{citation |url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/98/98929.html |title=o2398 a17537: Zimbabwe v Bangladesh, Bangladesh in Kenya and Zimbabwe 2006 (5th ODI) |work=CricketArchive|url-access=subscription|accessdate=9 November 2010}}</ref> In September 2006, Shakib was one of three players to be granted a rookie contract with the [[Bangladesh Cricket Board]] (BCB), along with Farhad Reza and [[Mehrab Hossain, Jr.|Mehrab Hossain Jr]]. This increased the number of players with central contracts and under the control of the BCB from 20 to 23.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh/content/story/260387.html |title=Mahmud named Bangladesh team manager|work=ESPNcricinfo |date=23 September 2006 |accessdate=7 November 2009}}</ref>\n\nThe [[West Indies]] hosted the [[2007 Cricket World Cup]] in March and April; Shakib was included in the 15-man squad led by [[Habibul Bashar]].<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh/content/story/280197.html |title=Mashud left out of Bangladesh squad |work=ESPNcricinfo|date=13 February 2007 |accessdate=9 November 2010}}</ref> Bangladesh made it to the second stage of the competition and finished seventh.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wc2007/engine/series/125929.html?view=pointstable |title=ICC World Cup 2006/07 / Points table |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=9 November 2010}}</ref> Along the way the team caused an upset by beating [[India national cricket team|India]] to help knock them out of the tournament. With [[Tamim Iqbal]] in just his fifth ODI and Mushfiqur Rahim, Shakib was one of three Bangladesh batsmen in the match to score a half century to help the team reach its target of 192 to win.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wc2007/content/story/285701.html |title=Brilliant Bangladesh stun India |first=Siddhartha |last=Vaidyanathan |work=ESPNcricinfo |date=17 March 2007 |accessdate=9 November 2010}}</ref> Later in the tournament, Shakib scored another half-century although Bangladesh were defeated by England on that very occasion.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wc2007/content/story/290076.html |title=Saqibul stands tall but can't stop the fall |first=Dileep |last=Premachandran |work=ESPNcricinfo |date=11 April 2008 |accessdate=9 November 2010}}</ref> With 202&nbsp;runs from nine&nbsp;matches at an average of 28.85<ref>{{cite web |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/wc2007/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=2403;type=tournament |title=ICC World Cup, 2006/07 / Records / Most wickets |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=9 November 2010}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Shakib fielding, 23 January, 2009, Dhaka SBNS.jpg|thumb|right|220px|Shakib in the 3rd and the final ODI against Zimbabwe in January 2009 in [[Sher-e-Bangla National Stadium]], which Bangladesh won with Shakib's individual unbeaten 33 runs off 60 balls<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bdeshvzim/engine/match/378759.html|title=3rd ODI: Bangladesh v Zimbabwe at Dhaka, Jan 23, 2009 \u2013 Cricket Scorecard \u2013 ESPN Cricinfo|publisher=|accessdate=27 October 2016}}</ref>]]\nLater that year, in May, India [[Indian cricket team in Bangladesh in 2007|toured Bangladesh]] for two Tests and three ODIs. On 18 May, Shakib made his Test debut against India. He batted once, scoring 27&nbsp;runs, and bowled 13&nbsp;overs without taking a wicket as the match ended in a draw.<ref>{{citation |url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/116/116634.html |title=f50076 t1832: Bangladesh v India India in Bangladesh 2007 (1st Test) |work=CricketArchive|url-access=subscription|accessdate=9 November 2010}}</ref> India won the Test series 1\u20130 and the ODI series 3\u20130. After the tour, [[Dav Whatmore]] resigned from his position as Bangladesh coach,<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/story/291550.html |title=Whatmore quits as Bangladesh coach|work=ESPNcricinfo |date=20 April 2007 |accessdate=9 November 2010}}</ref> and batsman [[Mohammad Ashraful]] replaced Habibul Bashar as captain.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh/content/story/296705.html |title=Ashraful named Bangladesh captain |work=ESPNcricinfo|date=2 June 2007 |accessdate=9 November 2010}}</ref> In September 2007, South Africa hosted the [[2007 ICC World Twenty20|ICC World Twenty20]]. Victory against West Indies in the first round was enough to ensure Bangladesh's progression to the second round, although it was the only one of their five matches they won. In the match against West Indies, Shakib took 4/34; it was the first time a Bangladesh player had taken more than three wickets in an International Twenty20 match (T20I).<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/twenty20wc/content/story/310815.html |title=Ashraful slams his way to fastest fifty in Bangladesh win |work=ESPNcricinfo |first1=HR |last1=Gopalakrishna |first2=Mathew |last2=Varghese |date=13 September 2007 |accessdate=9 November 2010}}</ref> Shakib was part of another piece of T20I history when in a match against Australia in the tournament he became one of three victims of the first T20I hat-trick. [[Brett Lee]] took Shakib's wicket, followed by those of Mortaza's and [[Alok Kapali]] to help Australia to a nine-wicket win.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/twenty20wc/content/story/311208.html |title=Hayden and Lee power Australian win |first=Sriram |last=Veera |work=ESPNcricinfo |date=16 September 2007 |accessdate=26 December 2010}}</ref> In October that year, it was announced that [[Jamie Siddons]]&nbsp;\u2013 Australia's assistant coach&nbsp;\u2013 would take over the role of Bangladesh coach;<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh/content/story/317465.html |title=Siddons accepts Bangladesh job |work=ESPNcricinfo|date=28 October 2007 |accessdate=9 November 2010}}</ref> Siddons asserted that the previous set-up had focused on short-term goals and that he was planning to improve Bangladesh over the long term and keep together a core squad of talented players to gain experience at international level.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/nzvbdesh/content/story/331087.html |title='My vision is long-term' \u2013 Siddons |work=ESPNcricinfo|date=15 January 2008 |accessdate=9 November 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Bangladeshi cricket team in New Zealand in 2007\u201308|December 2007 and January 2008]], Bangladesh toured New Zealand for two Tests and three ODIs. Although he did not play the first Test, Shakib was selected over [[Enamul Haque Jr]] for the second due to his better batting ability.<ref name=\"NZ January 2008\">{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/nzvbdesh/content/story/330795.html |title=New Zealand coast to innings victory |last=Binoy |first=George |work=ESPNcricinfo |date=14 January 2008 |accessdate=9 November 2010}}</ref> It was Shakib's fourth Test, and until that point he had gone wicketless. His first wicket was that of New Zealand's [[Craig Cumming]].<ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/player/56143.html?class=1;template=results;type=bowling;view=match |title=Statistics / Statsguru / Shakib Al Hasan / Test matches |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=9 November 2010}}</ref><ref>{{citation |url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/124/124203.html |title=f50566 t1861: New Zealand v Bangladesh, Bangladesh in New Zealand 2007/08 (2nd Test) |work=CricketArchive|url-access=subscription|accessdate=9 November 2010}}</ref> New Zealand won by an innings and 137&nbsp;runs and took the series 2\u20130.<ref name=\"NZ January 2008\"/> New Zealand also completed a clean sweep in the ODIs which preceded the Tests, winning 3\u20130.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/nzvbdesh/content/story/328292.html |title=Vettori and McCullum thrash Bangladesh |work=ESPNcricinfo |first=Jamie |last=Alter |date=30 December 2007 |accessdate=9 November 2010}}</ref> Shakib played in all three ODIs scoring 31&nbsp;runs at an average of 10.33,<ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/batting/most_runs_career.html?id=3308;type=series |title=Records / Bangladesh in New Zealand ODI Series, 2007/08 / Most runs |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=9 November 2010}}</ref> and taking 3&nbsp;wickets at an average of 42.33.<ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=3308;type=series |title=Records / Bangladesh in New Zealand ODI Series, 2007/08 / Most wickets |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=9 November 2010}}</ref> Over [[South African cricket team in Bangladesh in 2007\u201308|February and March 2008 South Africa toured Bangladesh]], playing two Tests and three ODIs. South Africa won both Tests.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bdeshvrsa/engine/match/323948.html |title=South Africa in Bangladesh Test Series \u2013 2nd Test Bangladesh v South Africa: Test no. 1865 |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=9 November 2010}}</ref> Shakib played in both Bangladesh's defeats, taking just one wicket while conceding 122&nbsp;runs,<ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=3677;type=series |title=Records / South Africa in Bangladesh Test Series, 2007/08 / Most wickets |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=9 November 2010}}</ref> and scoring 75&nbsp;runs.<ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/batting/most_runs_career.html?id=3677;type=series |title=Records / South Africa in Bangladesh Test Series, 2007/08 / Most runs |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=9 November 2010}}</ref> South Africa won the subsequent ODI series 3\u20130.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bdeshvrsa/content/story/342381.html |title=South Africa No.1 after clean sweep |first=Kanishkaa |last=Balachandran |work=ESPNcricinfo |date=14 March 2008 |accessdate=9 November 2010}}</ref> Shakib passed 1,000 ODI runs in the series; he passed the landmark in his 39th ODI with a batting average of 35.37.<ref name=\"ODI cumulative batting average\">{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/player/56143.html?class=2;template=results;type=batting;view=cumulative |title=Statistics / Statsguru / Shakib Al Hasan / ODI matches cumulative batting average |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=9 November 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Bangladesh's leading all-rounder (2008\u20132019)===\nBefore [[New Zealand cricket team in Bangladesh in 2008\u201309|New Zealand's tour of Bangladesh in October 2008]], Shakib was considered more of a batsman than a bowler, despite being an all-rounder. Though he usually batted down the order at number seven in Tests, he had mostly batted in the top five in ODIs. In a departure from Shakib's usual role Jamie Siddons, the coach, stated that Shakib would play the Test series against New Zealand as a specialist bowler. The move immediately paid off, and he took 7/37 in New Zealand's first innings in the opening Test. They were the best bowling figures by a Bangladesh player in Tests.<ref name=\"From Magura to No. 1\"/> Bangladesh lost the series 2\u20130, but Shakib finished as Bangladesh's leading wicket-taker in the series with 10&nbsp;wickets at 17.80.<ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=4494;type=series |title=Records / New Zealand in Bangladesh Test Series, 2008/09 / Most wickets |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=9 November 2010}}</ref> His spell was nominated to be the Best Test Bowling Performance of 2008 by ESPNCricinfo.<ref>http://www.espncricinfo.com/awards2008/content/story/385017.html</ref>\nBangladesh won the opening match of the ODI series against New Zealand&nbsp;\u2013 securing their first ever ODI win over them<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bdeshvnz/content/story/373126.html |title=Bangladesh maul sorry New Zealand|work=ESPNcricinfo |date=9 October 2008 |accessdate=11 November 2010}}</ref>&nbsp;\u2013 although they eventually lost the series 2\u20131.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bdeshvnz/engine/series/361750.html |title=New Zealand tour of Bangladesh 2008/09 / Results |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=11 November 2010}}</ref> Shakib finished with five&nbsp;wickets from three matches, making him Bangladesh's second-highest wicket-taker for the series behind Mashrafe Mortaza (7);<ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=4493;type=series |title=Records / New Zealand in Bangladesh ODI Series, 2008/09 / Most wickets |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=11 November 2010}}</ref> however Shakib scored just 16&nbsp;runs in the series.<ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/batting/most_runs_career.html?id=4493;type=series |title=Records / New Zealand in Bangladesh ODI Series, 2008/09 / Most runs |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=11 November 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe following month, Bangladesh toured [[Bangladeshi cricket team in South Africa in 2008\u201309|South Africa]] for two Tests, three ODIs, and a T20I. While Bangladesh lost all their matches against South Africa except for an abandoned ODI,<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/rsavbdesh/engine/series/350336.html |title=Bangladesh tour of South Africa 2008/09 / Results |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=11 November 2010}}</ref> Shakib continued to build on the good bowling form he had found against New Zealand. On the first day of the opening Test, Shakib went wicketless; on the advice of Mohammad Salauddin, Bangladesh's assistant coach, he gave the ball [[Flight (cricket)|flight]] on the second day and went on to take five wickets. He took another five-wicket haul in the second Test, again as Bangladesh lost to South Africa.<ref name=\"From Magura to No. 1\"/> Along with South Africa's [[Makhaya Ntini]], Shakib was the series' leading wicket-taker with 11 at an average of 20.81.<ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=4291;type=series |title=Records / Bangladesh in South Africa Test Series, 2008/09 / Most wickets |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=11 November 2010}}</ref> Shakib's performance against South Africa in a losing cause prompted former Australian [[Leg spin|leg spin bowler]] [[Kerry O'Keeffe]] to describe him as the \"world's best finger spinner at the moment\".<ref name=\"From Magura to No. 1\"/> Sri Lanka [[Sri Lankan cricket team in Bangladesh in 2008\u201309|toured Bangladesh in December 2008 and January 2009]] for two Tests and a Tri-nation tournament including Zimbabwe. Sri Lanka won both Tests and the tournament final,<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bdeshvsl/engine/series/378736.html |title=Sri Lanka tour of Bangladesh 2008/09 / Results |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=11 November 2010}}</ref> although Shakib turned in a man of the match performance, scoring 92&nbsp;not&nbsp;out, in the second ODI against Sri Lanka helped Bangladesh to their only victory against them on the tour.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/tri-bdesh/content/story/386385.html |title=Shakib powers Bangladesh to final|work=ESPNcricinfo |date=14 January 2009 |accessdate=11 November 2010}}</ref> In the first match of the Test series, Shakib took another five-wicket haul as his team again was defeated.<ref name=\"From Magura to No. 1\"/>\n\nOn 22 January 2009 Shakib was ranked first amongst ODI all-rounders by the ICC.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci-icc/content/story/387457.html |title=Shakib takes top spot among ODI allrounders |work=ESPNcricinfo|date=22 January 2010 |accessdate=9 November 2010}}</ref> Although he was part of the auction of players held the following month for the [[2009 Indian Premier League]], Shakib was not chosen by any of the eight teams and no bids were made for him. This was despite being rated as the world's highest ranked ODI all-rounder at the time. His teammate Mashrafe Mortaza, who was bought in the auction, said \"I would have been a lot happier if Shakib had got a team because he truly deserved it for his sensational form with the bat and ball\".<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ipl2009/content/story/389524.html |title=Proud Mortaza credits hard work|date=6 February 2009 |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=7 February 2009}}</ref>\n\n===Captaincy and Vice-captaincy (2009\u20132011)===\n[[File:Shakib al hasan 3.jpg|thumb|left|Shakib was appointed Bangladesh's vice-captain in June 2009.]]\nAt the beginning of 2009, there was speculation over Mohammad Ashraful's position as captain after a succession of defeats for Bangladesh and continuous poor form for Ashraful. Shakib was considered a possible successor by the [[Bangladesh Cricket Board]] (BCB). However, the BCB was cautious of over-burdening the all-rounder and decided against the move. Other candidates were discounted, and Ashraful remained as captain.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh/content/story/389739.html |title=Ashraful to continue as Bangladesh captain|work=ESPNcricinfo |date=8 February 2009 |accessdate=6 March 2009}}</ref> Later in 2009, Ashraful's captaincy was again under scrutiny after Bangladesh exited the [[2009 ICC World Twenty20]] in the first round following losses to Ireland and India. When [[Mashrafe Mortaza]] replaced Mohammad Ashraful in June 2009, Shakib was appointed vice-captain, filling the position vacated by Mortaza.<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wivbdesh2009/content/current/story/410237.html|title=Mashrafe named Bangladesh captain|date=23 June 2009|work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=8 July 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn July\u2013August 2009, [[Bangladeshi cricket team in West Indies in 2009|Bangladesh toured the West Indies]]. When Mortaza injured his knee in the first Test, he was unable to take to the field on the final day and Shakib took over as captain. He and [[Mahmudullah]] led Bangladesh's bowling attack, sharing 13&nbsp;wickets in the match and securing a historic win for Bangladesh.\nIt was Bangladesh's first against the West [[Indies]], their first overseas Test victory, and only their second Test win.<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wivbdesh2009/content/story/414146.html|title=Shakib, Mahmudullah make up for Mortaza's absence|date=13 July 2009|work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=18 July 2009}}</ref><ref>{{citation|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/247/247186.html|title=f51408 t1923 West Indies v Bangladesh: Bangladesh in West Indies 2009 (1st Test)|work=CricketArchive|url-access=subscription|accessdate=18 July 2009}}</ref> The West Indies side was very inexperienced due to the fallout of a dispute between the [[West Indies Cricket Board]] and the West Indies Players' Association over pay. The first XI had made themselves unavailable for selection and a new squad had to be chosen. Seven West Indies players made their Test debut in the match and the side was captained by [[Floyd Reifer]] who had played the last of his four Tests ten years earlier.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wivbdesh2009/content/story/413237.html |title=West Indies name replacement squad |work=ESPNcricinfo|date=8 July 2009 |accessdate=18 July 2009}}</ref> Shakib was fined 10% of his match fee for excessive appealing; bowler [[Shahadat Hossain]] was also fined and batsman [[Imrul Kayes]] was reprimanded for the same reason.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wivbdesh2009/content/story/414425.html |title=Shakib and Shahadat fined for excessive appealing |work=ESPNcricinfo |date=14 July 2009 |accessdate=19 June 2009}}</ref>\n\n====West Indies====\nIn Mortaza's absence through injury, Shakib led Bangladesh for the remainder of the tour.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wivbdesh2009/content/current/story/414664.html |title=History beckons for Bangladesh |work=ESPNcricinfo |first=Jamie|last=Alter |date=16 July 2009 |accessdate=18 July 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"step aside\">{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wivbdesh2009/content/story/416880.html |title=Mortaza happy to step aside for Shakib |work=ESPNcricinfo|date=30 July 2009 |accessdate=1 August 2009}}.</ref> Aged 22&nbsp;years and 115&nbsp;days at the start of the second Test, Shakib became Bangladesh's youngest captain and fifth youngest in the history of Test cricket.<ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/records/283416.html |title=Records / Test matches / Individual records (captains, players, umpires) / Youngest captains |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=23 November 2010}}</ref> Under Shakib's leadership Bangladesh went on to win the second Test, and in the process secured their first overseas series win.<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wivbdesh2009/content/current/story/415358.html |title=Raqibul and Shakib inspire first overseas series win |last=Veera |first=Sriram |work=ESPNcricinfo |date=20 July 2009 |accessdate=21 July 2009}}</ref> Individually Shakib performed well, earning both the player-of-the-match and player-of-the-series awards, scoring 16 and 96&nbsp;not&nbsp;out with the bat and taking 3/59 and 5/70 with the ball.<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wivbdesh2009/engine/current/match/401072.html|title=Scorecard: West Indies v Bangladesh, 2nd Test, 17\u201320 July 2009|work=ESPNcricinfo|accessdate=21 July 2009}}</ref> He scored 159&nbsp;runs in the series at an average of 53.00 and was Bangladesh's second highest run-scorer for the series;<ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/batting/most_runs_career.html?id=5037;type=series |title=Records / Bangladesh in West Indies Test Series, 2009 /  Most runs |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=1 August 2009}}</ref> his haul of 13&nbsp;wickets at an average of 18.76 from both matches meant Shakib was the equal highest wicket-taker for the series along with West Indies fast bowler [[Kemar Roach]].<ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=5037;type=series |title=Records / Bangladesh in West Indies Test Series, 2009 /  Most wickets |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=1 August 2009}}</ref> After winning the Test series 2\u20130, Bangladesh proceeded to whitewash the ODI series, winning 3\u20130. The West Indies' dispute remained unsolved for the whole of Bangladesh's tour and the West Indies continued to field an inexperienced side.<ref name=\"step aside\"/> Shakib collected two half centuries in the ODI series, averaging 45.00, and was the third highest run-scorer in the series;<ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/batting/most_runs_career.html?id=5036;type=series |title=Records / Bangladesh in West Indies ODI Series, 2009 /  Most runs |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=1 August 2009}}</ref> he also took 2&nbsp;wickets at an average of 48.00.<ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=5036;type=series |title=Records / Bangladesh in West Indies ODI Series, 2009 /  Most wickets |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=1 August 2009}}</ref> For his performance in the ODIs, Shakib was named the man of the series.<ref>{{citation |url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Seasons/WI/2009_WI_Bangladesh_in_West_Indies_2009.html |title=Bangladesh in West Indies 2009 |work=CricketArchive |url-access=subscription |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121026120022/http://www.cricketarchive.com/Archive/Seasons/WI/2009_WI_Bangladesh_in_West_Indies_2009.html |archive-date=26 October 2012 |accessdate=1 August 2009}}</ref>\n\n====Zimbabwe====\nShakib was appointed captain for Bangladesh's [[Bangladeshi cricket team in Zimbabwe in 2009|tour of Zimbabwe in August 2009]] as Mortaza was still injured.<ref name=\"step aside\"/> In the second ODI of the five match series in Zimbabwe in August 2009, Shakib scored 104 off only 64 balls before being run-out&nbsp;\u2013 his third ODI century&nbsp;\u2013 to help his team to their highest score in ODIs and lead Bangladesh to a 2\u20130 lead in the series.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/zimvbdesh2009/content/story/418910.html |title=Shakib scripts convincing win |author=Sriram Veera |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=11 August 2009}}</ref> He finished the series with 170&nbsp;runs from five&nbsp;matches at an average of 42.50&nbsp;\u2013 fifth highest run-scorer<ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/batting/most_runs_career.html?id=5129;type=series |title=Records / Bangladesh in Zimbabwe ODI Series, 2009 / Most runs |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=3 September 2009}}</ref>&nbsp;\u2013 and 6&nbsp;wickets an average of 39.66, fourth highest wicket-taker in the series.<ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=5129;type=series |title=Records / Bangladesh in Zimbabwe ODI Series, 2009 / Most wickets |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=3 September 2009}}</ref> Following his team's 4\u20131 victory in the ODI series against Zimbabwe, Shakib travelled to Australia to undergo medical treatment for acute groin pain. He had been experiencing pain since the end of the West Indies tour, but he had decided to play through the pain and lead Bangladesh in Zimbabwe.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh/content/story/422343.html |title=Shakib to undergo treatment in Australia|work=ESPNcricinfo |date=27 August 2009 |accessdate=3 September 2009}}</ref> Although he did not win, Shakib was nominated Cricketer of the Year and Test Player of the Year in the 2009 [[ICC Awards]]; he was the only Bangladesh player to be nominated in either category that year.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci-icc/content/current/story/422973.html |title=Dhoni, Dilshan pick up maximum nominations|work=ESPNcricinfo |date=2 September 2009 |accessdate=3 September 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite media release|url=http://icc-cricket.yahoo.net/events_and_awards/lg_icc_awards/newsdetails.php?newsId=1310_1254417540 |title=Mitchell Johnson takes top honours at glittering ICC Awards night |date=2 October 2009 |publisher=International Cricket Council |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110807055221/http://icc-cricket.yahoo.net/events_and_awards/lg_icc_awards/newsdetails.php?newsId=1310_1254417540 |archive-date=7 August 2011 |accessdate=9 November 2010}}</ref>\n\nShakib's success meant that it was not a given that Mortaza would replace him as captain once fit,<ref name=\"step aside\"/> but it was announced in September 2009 that Mortaza would return as captain for Bangladesh's home [[Zimbabwe cricket team in Bangladesh in 2009|ODI series against Zimbabwe the following month]] and Shakib would return to the role of vice-captain.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bdeshvzim09/content/current/story/424272.html |title=Mortaza appointed captain for Zimbabwe series |work=ESPNcricinfo|date=9 September 2009 |accessdate=9 September 2009}}</ref> However, Mortaza failed to return from arthroscopic surgery on both knees in time for the series, and Shakib was again named captain.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bdeshvzim09/content/story/430712.html |title=Injured Mortaza out of Zimbabwe ODIs |work=ESPNcricinfo|date=22 October 2009 |accessdate=1 November 2009}}</ref> After losing the opening match&nbsp;\u2013 in which Shakib criticised the performance of Bangladesh's batsmen including himself<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bdeshvzim09/content/story/431572.html |title=We can still win this 4\u20131&nbsp;\u2013 Shakib |work=ESPNcricinfo|date=27 October 2009 |accessdate=1 November 2009}}</ref>&nbsp;\u2013 Bangladesh went on to win the series 4\u20131.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bdeshvzim09/engine/series/422622.html |title=Zimbabwe tour of Bangladesh 2009/10 / Results |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=11 November 2010}}</ref> In the second match of the series, Shakib passed 2,000&nbsp;runs in ODIs.<ref name=\"ODI cumulative batting average\"/> In November 2009, Shakib was named ''[[The Wisden Cricketer]]'s'' \"Test Player of the Year\".<ref name=\"Test player of the year\">{{citation |url=http://wisdencricketer.com/item.php?parent_id=3&child_id=0&item_id=599 |title=Remember The Name |work=The Wisden Cricketer online |author=Rabeed Imam |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091012075533/http://wisdencricketer.com/item.php?parent_id=3&child_id=0&item_id=599 |archive-date=12 October 2009 |accessdate=11 October 2009}}</ref>\n\n====England and the Asia Cup====\n[[File:Shakib al hasan 4.jpg|thumb|upright|Shakib in the field against England during the second ODI, shortly after relinquishing the captaincy]]\nOver February and March 2010 [[English cricket team in Bangladesh in 2009\u201310|England toured Bangladesh]] for two Tests and three ODIs. England won all of their matches against Bangladesh.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bdeshveng2010/engine/series/426373.html |title=England tour of Bangladesh 2009/10 / Results |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=11 November 2010}}</ref> Shakib was Bangladesh's leading wicket-taker in both the Test and ODI series (9 wickets in Tests and 5 in ODIs).<ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=5510;type=series |title=Records / England in Bangladesh Test Series, 2009/10 / Most wickets |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=11 November 2010}}</ref><ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=5509;type=series |title=Records / England in Bangladesh ODI Series, 2009/10 / Most wickets |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=11 November 2010}}</ref> In the second Test, Shakib scored 49 and 96, and took 4/124 from 66&nbsp;overs. Both Tests went to the final day and Shakib expressed the opinion that the experience had exhausted his side.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bdeshveng2010/content/story/453368.html |title=Bangladesh ran out of steam&nbsp;\u2013 Shakib |last=Miller |first=Andrew |work=ESPNcricinfo |date=24 March 2010 |accessdate=11 November 2010}}</ref> The match was also a source of controversy after incorrect umpiring decisions on the third day went against Bangladesh, prompting Shakib to blame the lack of a [[Umpire Decision Review System|referral system]] for some of the team's misfortune.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bdeshveng2010/content/story/453049.html |title=Shakib blames board for lack of review system |last=Miller |first=Andrew |work=ESPNcricinfo |date=22 March 2010 |accessdate=11 November 2010}}</ref> In turn, Bangladesh [[Bangladeshi cricket team in England in 2010|toured England in May and July]] the same year. They again lost the Test series 2\u20130.<ref name=\"England 2010 results\">{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england-v-bangladesh-2010/engine/series/426339.html |title=Bangladesh tour of England, Ireland and Scotland 2010 / Results |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=11 November 2010}}</ref> Shakib finished as his team's leading wicket-taker with eight wickets,<ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/england-v-bangladesh-2010/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=5504;type=series |title=Bangladesh in England Test Series, 2010 / Records / Most wickets |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=11 November 2010}}</ref> although he only scored 52&nbsp;runs.<ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/england-v-bangladesh-2010/engine/records/batting/most_runs_career.html?id=5504;type=series |title=Bangladesh in England Test Series, 2010 / Records / Most runs |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=11 November 2010}}</ref> Before the ODI series, Bangladesh left England for Sri Lanka, which was hosting the [[2010 Asia Cup]] in June. Bangladesh lost all three of their matches.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/asia2010/engine/series/424694.html |title=Asia Cup 2010 / Results |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=11 November 2010}}</ref> With five wickets, Shakib was Bangladesh's lead wicket-taker with [[Shafiul Islam]] (5 each).<ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/asia2010/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=5477;type=tournament |title=Asia Cup, 2010 / Records / Most wickets |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=11 November 2010}}</ref>\n\nAs he was struggling to cope with the captaincy and his role as an all-rounder, Shakib gave up the captaincy in July 2010 to focus on his own performance. Mashrafe Mortaza returned to take charge in ODIs. Coach Jamie Siddons explained that \"Shakib was the main person behind the decision, he decided it was a bit much for him. His form was down with the bat and he needed a rest.\"<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england-v-bangladesh-2010/content/current/story/466199.html |title=Shakib is an ideal captain&nbsp;\u2013 Siddons |work=ESPNcricinfo |last=McGlashan |first=Andrew |date=5 July 2010 |accessdate=9 November 2010}}</ref> Bangladesh returned to England for the ODI half of their tour. Bangladesh lost the series 2\u20131,<ref name=\"England 2010 results\"/> but their victory in the second match was the first time Bangladesh had beaten England in international cricket.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england-v-bangladesh-2010/content/story/466798.html |title=Bangladesh seal historic victory |last=McGlashan |first=Andrew |work=ESPNcricinfo |date=10 July 2010 |accessdate=11 November 2010}}</ref> While in Europe, Bangladesh were scheduled to play two ODIs against Ireland, and one each against Scotland and Netherlands. The match against Scotland was abandoned and Bangladesh lost one match to each of Ireland and the Netherlands.<ref name=\"England 2010 results\"/>\n\nHaving signed a contract in November 2009,<ref name=\"Shakib for Worcestershire\">{{citation |url=http://www.worcesternews.co.uk/sport/wccc/4744603.Worcestershire_in_swoop_for_Shakib_as_overseas_player/ |title=Worcestershire in swoop for Shakib as overseas player |work=Worcester News |publisher=[[Newsquest|Newsquest Media Group]] |last=Reeves |first=Michael |date=18 November 2009 |accessdate=11 November 2010}}</ref> Shakib joined up with [[Worcestershire County Cricket Club]], playing the second division of the [[County Championship]], in July 2010. He was the first Bangladeshi to represent a county side.<ref name=\"Shakib for Worcestershire\"/> While playing for Worcestershire he took his best first-class bowling figures of 7/32 against [[Middlesex County Cricket Club|Middlesex]]. In eight first-class matches he scored 358&nbsp;runs at 25.57 (with one score over 50)<ref>{{citation |url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/73/73152/f_Batting_by_Team.html |title=First-class batting and fielding for each team by Shakib Al Hasan |work=CricketArchive|url-access=subscription|accessdate=11 November 2010}}</ref> and took 35&nbsp;wickets at 22.37,<ref>{{citation |url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/73/73152/f_Bowling_by_Team.html |title=First-class bowling for each team by Shakib Al Hasan |work=CricketArchive|url-access=subscription|accessdate=11 November 2010}}</ref> as Worcestershire secured promotion to the first division at the end of the season.<ref>{{citation |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/counties/9006380.stm |title=Worcestershire win promotion with victory over Sussex |publisher=[[BBC Sport]] |date=16 September 2010 |accessdate=11 November 2010}}</ref> Shakib also played five one-day matches for Worcestershie, scoring 187 at an average of 37.40 (including two half-centuries)<ref>{{citation |url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/73/73152/a_Batting_by_Team.html |title=ListA batting and fielding for each team by Shakib Al Hasan |work=CricketArchive|url-access=subscription|accessdate=11 November 2010}}</ref> and taking 9&nbsp;wickets at 17.77.<ref>{{citation |url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/73/73152/a_Bowling_by_Team.html |title=ListA bowling for each team by Shakib Al Hasan |work=CricketArchive|url-access=subscription|accessdate=11 November 2010}}</ref>\n\nFor his performances in 2009, he was named in the World Test XI by the ICC<ref>http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci-icc/content/story/427665.html</ref>\n\n====New Zealand and Zimbabwe====\nIn October 2010, [[New Zealand cricket team in Bangladesh in 2010\u201311|New Zealand went to Bangladesh]] for five ODIs. In the first match of the series Mortaza injured his ankle and was forced to leave the field; Shakib took over, and under his leadership Bangladesh secured a nine-run victory, during which Shakib took four wickets and scored 58. Once it emerged that Mortaza would be unable to play in the rest of the series, Shakib was made captain for the remaining matches.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh-v-new-zealand-2010/content/story/480285.html |title=Mortaza ruled out due to injury |work=ESPNcricinfo|date=6 October 2010 |accessdate=11 November 2010}}</ref> In the fourth match, Shakib scored a century and took three wickets to help his team win by nine runs.<ref name=\"NZ 4th ODI 2010\">{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh-v-new-zealand-2010/content/story/481617.html |title=All-round Shakib inspires Bangladesh to historic win |work=ESPNcricinfo |first=Andrew |last=Fernando |date=14 October 2010 |accessdate=11 November 2010}}</ref> Bangladesh went on to win the series 4\u20130,<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh-v-new-zealand-2010/content/story/482305.html |title=Bangladesh reap rewards of hard work |first=Mohammad |last=Isam |work=ESPNcricinfo |date=18 October 2010 |accessdate=11 November 2010}}</ref> their first series victory against a full strength ICC Full Member nation.<ref name=\"NZ 4th ODI 2010\"/> Shakib finished the series as the player with most runs and wickets on either side: 213&nbsp;runs<ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/batting/most_runs_career.html?id=6168;type=series |title=Records / New Zealand in Bangladesh ODI Series, 2010/11 / Most runs |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=11 November 2010}}</ref> and 11&nbsp;wickets.<ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=6168;type=series |title=Records / New Zealand in Bangladesh ODI Series, 2010/11 / Most wickets |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=11 November 2010}}</ref>\n\nAlthough Mortaza returned from injury in time for Zimbabwe's tour of Bangladesh in December, Shakib was retained as captain for the five-match ODI series.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh-v-zimbabwe-2010/content/current/story/489535.html |title=Shakib retained as captain for Zimbabwe series |work=ESPNcricinfo|date=28 November 2010 |accessdate=29 November 2010}}</ref> Following his side's defeat in the opening ODI, Shakib stated that he \"was not prepared to take the job and I am also not satisfied with my role as a captain\".<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh-v-zimbabwe-2010/content/story/490108.html |title='I was not prepared for captaincy'&nbsp;\u2013 Shakib Al Hasan|work=ESPNcricinfo |date=2 December 2010 |accessdate=2 December 2010}}</ref> Bangladesh went on to win the next three complete matches, with one called off due to rain, to beat Zimbabwe 3\u20131.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh-v-zimbabwe-2010/content/current/story/491571.html |title=Shakib praises Bangladesh recovery|work=ESPNcricinfo |date=12 December 2010 |accessdate=12 December 2010}}</ref> Shakib was Bangladesh's second-highest run-scorer and wicket taker for the series with 156&nbsp;runs, including two half centuries, and nine&nbsp;wickets.<ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/batting/most_runs_career.html?id=6321;type=series |title=Records / Zimbabwe in Bangladesh ODI Series, 2010/11 / Most runs |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=12 December 2010}}</ref><ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=6321;type=series |title=Records / Zimbabwe in Bangladesh ODI Series, 2010/11 / Most wickets |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=12 December 2010}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"float: right; margin-left: 1em; width: 40%; font-size: 90%;\" cellspacing=\"5\"\n|-\n!colspan=\"6\"|'''Shakib's record as captain'''\n|-\n!Format \u2193 || Matches || Won || Lost || Drawn/NR\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| Test <ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh/engine/records/individual/list_captains.html?class=1;id=25;type=team|work=ESPNcricinfo|title=List of Bangladesh test captains}}</ref>\n|| 13 || 3 {{efn|Mortaza began the first Test against the West Indies in 2009 as captain, the win is not counted as being part of Shakib's term in charge}} || 10 || 0\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ODI <ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh/engine/records/individual/most_matches_as_captain.html?class=2;id=25;type=team|title=Bangladesh captains' playing record in ODI matches|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> \n|| 50 || 23 || 26 || 1\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| T20I <ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh/engine/records/individual/most_matches_as_captain.html?class=3;id=25;type=team |title=Bangladesh captains' playing record in International Twenty20 matches |work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> \n|| 17 || 4 || 13 ||\n|-\n|colspan=5; align=center|Last updated on: 23 December 2018 \n|}\n\nIn February to March April 2011, Bangladesh co-hosted the [[2011 Cricket World Cup|World Cup]] with India and Sri Lanka. West Indies dismissed Bangladesh for 58&nbsp;runs, the team's lowest score in ODIs and a record low for a Full Member at the World Cup.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/icc_cricket_worldcup2011/content/story/504517.html |title='Team devastated by performance'&nbsp;\u2013 Siddons |work=ESPNcricinfo |first=Sidharth |last=Monga |date=6 March 2011 |accessdate=6 March 2011}}</ref> Shakib's house was stoned by angry fans in the aftermath,<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/icc_cricket_worldcup2011/content/story/504533.html |title=Shakib, Siddons hit back at criticism from former players |work=ESPNcricinfo |first=Sidharth |last=Monga |date=6 March 2011 |accessdate=6 March 2011}}</ref> as was the West Indies team bus as it left the ground.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/icc_cricket_worldcup2011/content/story/504279.html |title=West Indies team bus stoned in Dhaka |first=Sidharth |last=Monga |work=ESPNcricinfo |date=4 March 2011 |accessdate=6 March 2011}}</ref> Bangladesh registered wins against England, Ireland and the Netherlands, but defeats by West Indies, India and South Africa meant they did not progress beyond the first round of the tournament.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/icc_cricket_worldcup2011/content/story/506964.html |title=Abject Bangladesh surrender meekly |first=Abhishek |last=Purohit |work=ESPNcricinfo |date=19 March 2011 |accessdate=20 March 2011}}</ref> With 8&nbsp;wickets at an average of 27.87, Shakib was Bangladesh's lead wicket-taker in the tournament,<ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/icc_cricket_worldcup2011/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=4857;type=tournament |title=ICC Cricket World Cup, 2010/11 / Records / Most wickets |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=20 March 2011}}</ref> and his 142&nbsp;runs from 6&nbsp;innings made him the team's third highest run-scorer.<ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/icc_cricket_worldcup2011/engine/records/batting/most_runs_career.html?id=4857;type=tournament |title=ICC Cricket World Cup, 2010/11 / Records / Most runs |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=20 March 2011}}</ref>\n\n'''After World Cup'''\n\nShortly after the World Cup, [[Australian cricket team in Bangladesh in 2011|Australia toured Bangladesh]] for three ODIs. In the first match of the series, Shakib scored 51 to pass 3,000&nbsp;runs in ODIs.<ref name=\"ODI cumulative batting average\"/> Bangladesh lost the series 3\u20130,<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh-v-australia-2011/content/story/510859.html |title=Hussey hundred sets up Australia's clean-sweep |first=Brydon |last=Coverdale |work=ESPNcricinfo |date=13 April 2011 |accessdate=18 April 2011}}</ref> Shakib scored 69&nbsp;runs in three matches<ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/batting/most_runs_career.html?id=6486;type=series |title=Records / Australia in Bangladesh ODI Series, 2011 / Most runs |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=18 April 2011}}</ref> and took just one wicket whilst conceding 117&nbsp;runs.<ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=6486;type=series |title=Records / Australia in Bangladesh ODI Series, 2011 / Most wickets |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=18 April 2011}}</ref> [[Shane Watson]]'s performances in the series meant he was ranked first amongst ODI all-rounders, claiming the position from Shakib.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci-icc/content/story/511114.html |title=Watson rises to top spot in ICC rankings|work=ESPNcricinfo |date=15 April 2011 |accessdate=18 April 2011}}</ref> For the [[2011 Indian Premier League]], held in April and May, Shakib was contracted by [[Kolkata Knight Riders]] for US$425,000.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/indian-premier-league-2011/content/story/495911.html |title=Ryder, Kartik, Kaif go in re-bidding|work=ESPNcricinfo |date=6 January 2011 |accessdate=8 January 2011}}</ref> He made his debut in the tournament on 15 April in a match against [[Rajasthan Royals]]. He claimed two wickets in the match, first that of [[Amit Paunikar]] and then [[Shane Watson]], but did not get the chance to bat as his team only lost a wicket, winning by 9 wickets.<ref>{{citation |url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/333/333574.html |title=tt2137 ipl188 Rajasthan Royals v Kolkata Knight Riders: Indian Premier League 2011 |work=CricketArchive |url-access=subscription |accessdate=18 April 2011}}</ref> KKR were knocked out in the semi-finals of the competition;<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/indian-premier-league-2011/content/story/517231.html |title=A cut above the rest |first=Nitin |last=Sundar |work=ESPNcricinfo |date=30 May 2011 |accessdate=31 May 2011}}</ref> Shakib played in seven matches, taking 11&nbsp;wickets at an average of 15.90 and finished as KKR's third-highest wicket-taker.<ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/indian-premier-league-2011/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=5969;type=tournament |title=Indian Premier League, 2011 / Records / Most wickets |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=31 May 2011}}</ref> After the IPL, Shakib returned to Worcestershire for seven weeks. He played a single County Championship match as his time with the team coincided with the [[2011 Friends Life t20]],<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/county-cricket-2011/content/current/story/498143.html |title=Shakib rejoins Worcestershire for 2011|work=ESPNcricinfo |date=6 January 2011 |accessdate=8 January 2011}}</ref><ref>{{citation |url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/73/73152/First-Class_Matches.html |title=First-class matches played by Shakib Al Hasan |work=CricketArchive|url-access=subscription|accessdate=23 July 2011}}</ref> but in that match he took seven wickets and passed 3,000&nbsp;runs in first-class cricket.<ref>{{citation |url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/316/316169.html |title=f53262 Worcestershire v Hampshire: LV County Championship 2011 (Division 1) |work=CricketArchive|url-access=subscription|accessdate=23 July 2011}}</ref> Worcestershire finished fifth out of nine teams in their group for the t20 competition, failing to qualify for the quarter-finals.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/series/491208.html |title=Friends Life t20 2011 |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=23 July 2011}}</ref> From 12&nbsp;matches Shakib took 19&nbsp;wickets, finishing as the club's leading wicket-taker, equal with seam bowler [[Gareth Andrew]].<ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=6381;type=tournament |title=Records / Friends Life t20, 2011 / Most wickets |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=23 July 2011}}</ref>\n\nWhen Bangladesh toured Zimbabwe in [[Bangladeshi cricket team in Zimbabwe in 2011|August 2011]] they were expected to win the one-off Test, which was Zimbabwe's first in five years, and the five-match ODI series. As it transpired Bangladesh lost the ODI series 3\u20132 and the Test. Shakib and his vice-captain, Tamim Iqbal, were sacked with a BCB official citing unsatisfactory leadership.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh/content/current/story/531274.html |title=Shakib and Tamim stripped of leadership roles |work=ESPNcricinfo |date=5 September 2011 |accessdate=5 September 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Post-captaincy (2011\u20132017)===\nBangladesh's first series under new leadership was against the West Indies in [[West Indian cricket team in Bangladesh in 2011\u201312|October 2011]]. Relieved of the captaincy, Shakib was Bangladesh's leading wicket-taker in both the ODI and Test series,<ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=6863;type=series |title=Records / West Indies in Bangladesh ODI Series, 2011/12 / Most wickets |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=21 December 2011}}</ref><ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=6864;type=series |title=Records / West Indies in Bangladesh Test Series, 2011/12 / Most wickets |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=21 December 2011}}</ref> His bowling was backed up by 168&nbsp;runs in the two Tests (of the Bangladesh players, only Tamim Iqbal scored more),<ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/batting/most_runs_career.html?id=6864;type=series |title=Records / West Indies in Bangladesh Test Series, 2011/12 / Most runs |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=21 December 2011}}</ref> and 79 from two innings in the ODIs.<ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/batting/most_runs_career.html?id=6863;type=series |title=Records / West Indies in Bangladesh ODI Series, 2011/12 / Most runs |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=21 December 2011}}</ref> Bangladesh lost both series.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/series/531420.html |title=West Indies tour of Bangladesh 2011/12 / Results |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=21 December 2011}}</ref> Following this, Shakib was Bangladesh's top run-scorer and wicket-taker in the [[Pakistani cricket team in Bangladesh in 2011\u201312|home Test series]] against Pakistan in December 2011.<ref>{{citation|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=6957;type=series|title=Pakistan in Bangladesh Test Series, 2011/12: Most wickets|work=[[ESPNcricinfo]]|accessdate=21 December 2011}}</ref><ref>{{citation|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/batting/most_runs_career.html?id=6957;type=series|title=Pakistan in Bangladesh Test Series, 2011/12: Most runs|work=[[ESPNcricinfo]]|accessdate=21 December 2011}}</ref> In the second Test of the series, he became Bangladesh's first player to score a century (his highest score, 144) and take five wickets in an innings in the same Test.<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh-v-pakistan-2011/content/story/546223.html|title=Pakistan in charge despite Shakib's six-for|last=Ravindran|first=Siddarth|date=20 December 2011|work=ESPNcricinfo|accessdate=21 December 2011}}</ref> After the series he moved to first place in the ICC's ranking of Test all-rounders.<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh/content/current/story/546592.html|title=Shakib becomes No. 1 Test allrounder|date=22 December 2011|work=ESPNcricinfo|accessdate=27 December 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Bangladesh Cricket Board]] founded the six-team [[Bangladesh Premier League]] in 2012, a twenty20 tournament to be held in February that year. The BCB made Shakib the 'icon player' for [[Khulna Royal Bengals]].<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh/content/story/547222.html |title=Bangladesh Premier League to begin on February 9 |first=Tariq |last=Engineer |work=[[ESPNcricinfo]] |date=28 December 2011 |accessdate=5 March 2012}}</ref> Under his captaincy, Shakib's team progressed to the semi-finals of the competition where they were beaten by [[Dhaka Gladiators]].<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh-premier-league-2012/content/story/555618.html |title=Dhaka make final despite Shakib |work=[[ESPNcricinfo]] |date=28 February 2012 |accessdate=5 March 2012}}</ref> In ten matches he scored 280&nbsp;runs and took 15&nbsp;wickets, which make him KRB's leading wicket-taker, and was named Man of the Tournament.<ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh-premier-league-2012/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=7188;type=tournament |title=Bangladesh Premier League, 2011/12 / Records / Most wickets |work=[[ESPNcricinfo]] |accessdate=5 March 2012}}</ref><ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh-premier-league-2012/content/story/555925.html |title=The BPL XI |first=Mohammad |last=Isam |work=ESPNcricinfo |date=1 March 2012 |accessdate=5 March 2012}}</ref>\n\nSoon after the BPL finished, Bangladesh hosted the [[2012 Asia Cup]] featuring India, Pakistan, and Sri Lanka. In four matches Shakib scored 237&nbsp;runs including three half-centuries and took six wickets. Bangladesh progressed to the final of the tournament for the first time where they lost to Pakistan by two runs. Shakib's performance saw him named Player of the Tournament and reclaim the number&nbsp;1 ODI all-rounder ranking from Australia's Shane Watson.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/asia-cup-2012/content/story/558027.html |title=Team effort takes Bangladesh to historic final |first=Kanishkaa |last=Balachandran |work=ESPNcricinfo |date=20 March 2012 |accessdate=29 March 2012}}</ref><ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/asia-cup-2012/content/story/558267.html |title=Pakistan prevail over gutsy Bangladesh |first=Abhishek |last=Purohit |work=ESPNcricinfo |date=22 March 2012 |accessdate=29 March 2012}}</ref><ref>{{citation |url=http://icc-cricket.yahoo.net/newsdetails.php?newsId=19717_1332781920 |title=Shakib returns as No.1 ranked all-rounder in ODIs |date=26 March 2012 |publisher=International Cricket Council |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120618034148/http://icc-cricket.yahoo.net/newsdetails.php?newsId=19717_1332781920 |archive-date=18 June 2012 |accessdate=29 March 2012}}</ref> The [[2012 Indian Premier League]] was held in April and May; Shakib played in eight of KKR's 18 matches and won two-man of the match awards as the team won the competition for the first time.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh/content/story/566769.html |title=Shakib happy with IPL outcome |work=ESPNcricinfo |date=30 May 2012 |accessdate=7 July 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[West Indian cricket team in Bangladesh in 2012\u201313|home series against West Indies in late 2012]], he became the 2nd Bangladeshi to both take 100 Test wickets, making him the leading wicket-taker in Tests for Bangladesh, and to complete the 1000 run / 100 wicket double.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh-v-west-indies-2012/content/story/592795.html |title=A high and low for Shakib Al Hasan |first=Kanishkaa |last=Balachandran |work=ESPNcricinfo |date=24 November 2012 |accessdate=11 December 2012}}</ref> However, he got ruled out of the ODI and T20 series due to a shin injury.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh-v-west-indies-2012/content/story/594591.html |title=Shakib out of rest of West Indies ODIs |first=Mohammad |last=Isam |work=ESPNcricinfo |date=1 December 2012 |accessdate=11 December 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[2013 Bangladesh Premier League player auction|auction of the BPL 2]], Shakib was brought by defending champions [[Dhaka Gladiators]] for $365,000, the most expensive player in the tournament.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh/content/story/597888.html |title=Shakib the top pick at BPL auction |first=Mohammad |last=Isam |work=ESPNcricinfo |date=20 December 2012 |accessdate=27 February 2013}}</ref> He led his team to victory, getting 329 runs and 15 wickets in 12 matches, emerging as the Man of the Tournament for consecutive second time in the BPL.\n<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh-premier-league-2013/content/story/605655.html |title=The BPL XI |first=Mohammad |last=Isam |work=ESPNcricinfo |date=20 February 2013 |accessdate=27 February 2013}}</ref>\n\nShakib got ruled out of the [[Bangladeshi cricket team in Sri Lanka in 2012\u201313|Sri Lanka tour]] in March due to a calf muscle injury. He had a successful operation on the right leg at a private hospital in [[Sydney]], [[Australia]]. He would be on rest for one month since his operation<ref>{{citation |url=http://bdnews24.com/cricket/2013/02/26/shakibs-surgery-successful |title=Shakib's surgery successful |first=Mohammad |last=Isam |work=bdnews24.com |date=26 February 2013 |accessdate=27 February 2013}}</ref>\n\nShakib signed for [[Leicestershire County Cricket Club]] as their second overseas club, joining Australian [[Joe Burns (cricketer)|Joe Burns]] for their [[2013 Friends Life t20|Twenty 20]] campaign.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/cricket/21975899 | title=Shakib Al Hasan joins for FL t20 | date=29 March 2013 |work=BBC Sport|publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation| accessdate=28 September 2013}}</ref> Shakib played in all 10 of Leicestershire's games.\n\nIn the [[2013 Caribbean Premier League]], Shakib played for [[Barbados Tridents]]. On 3 August 2013 against [[Trinidad & Tobago Red Steel]] Shakib recorded the second best bowling figure in T20 cricket dismissing six batsmen to finish with figures of 6 for 6 from his four overs at Kensington Oval.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/caribbean-premier-league-2013/content/story/658685.html | title=Barbados Tridents v Trinidad & Tobago Red Steel, CPL 2013, Bridgetown Shakib's six overwhelms Trinidad in low-scorer |work=ESPNcricinfo| date=3 August 2013 | accessdate=17 August 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn his debut match at the [[2013\u201314 Big Bash League season]], Shakib scored 41 runs off 29 balls and took 2 wickets for 21 runs in his 4 overs for [[Adelaide Strikers]], although being unable to prevent his team from losing.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/big-bash-league-2013/engine/current/match/654061.html |work=ESPNcricinfo| title=Adelaide Strikers vs Sidney Sixers | date=5 January 2014 | accessdate=5 January 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[2014 Indian Premier League]], he was retained by Kolkata Knight Riders for a fee of INR 2.80 [[crore]]. In the competition he scored 227 runs in 11 innings at a strike rate of 149.34; his best being a 60 off 38 balls. He also achieved 11 wickets in 13 matches at an economy of 6.68 and an average of 30.36. His all-round performance was instrumental in Kolkata Knight Riders' title win. For his performances in 2014, he was named as 12th man in the [[2014 Indian Premier League#2014 Cricinfo IPL XI|Cricinfo IPL XI]] .\n\nIn 2nd Test match of [[Zimbabwean cricket team in Bangladesh in 2014\u201315|Zimbabwe tour of Bangladesh 2014]] Shakib became only the third player in Test history after [[Ian Botham]] (1980) and [[Imran Khan]] (1983) to score a hundred and take 10 wickets in the same match.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/story/797145.html | title=Shakib joins Imran, Botham | date=7 November 2014 | accessdate=7 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 December 2014, it was announced that Shakib would be joining the [[Melbourne Renegades]] for the final 4 games of the [[2014\u201315 Big Bash League season]], replacing [[Andre Russell]], who would be leaving to join the [[West Indies cricket team|West Indies]] in their [[West Indian cricket team in South Africa in 2014\u201315|tour of South Africa]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cricket.com.au/news/shakib-al-hasan-joins-melbourne-renegades-big-bash-league/2014-12-24|title=Bangladesh hero Shakib joins Renegades|work=cricket.com.au|accessdate=15 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bigbash.com.au/news-and-videos/2014/12/24/shakib-al-hasan-joins-melbourne-renegades|title=Shakib joins the Renegades|work=bigbash.com.au|accessdate=15 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.melbournerenegades.com.au/news/2014/12/24/renegades-sign-shakib|title=Renegades sign Shakib Al Hasan|work=melbournerenegades.com.au|accessdate=15 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, Shakib helped Bangladesh to their most successful year in cricket. Following their success in the [[2015 Cricket World Cup]], he also helped the team to a white wash of Pakistan and series win against India and South Africa. On 15 July, he took his 200th wicket of his ODI career by taking wicket of [[Hashim Amla]] in the final ODI of the series. He also became the 8th and youngest ODI cricketer to take 200 wickets and score 4000 runs.\n\n===New era of Test & T20I captaincy (2017\u20132019)===\nAfter the retirement of [[Mashrafe Mortaza]] in 2017, Shakib was appointed as the T20I captain of the team for the second time. Later [[Mushfiqur Rahim]] was also removed from Test captaincy and Hasan was again appointed as Test captain. However, during [[2017-18 Bangladesh Tri-Nation Series]] he injured his finger and was rested for few days and in his absence [[Mahmudullah]] captained the side in the [[Sri Lankan cricket team in Bangladesh in 2017-18|Home series against Sri Lanka]] and [[2018 Nidahas Trophy]]. His first tour was against Pakistan in July 2017.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cricketcountry.com/news/shakib-al-hasan-appointed-bangladeshs-t20i-captain-598395 |title=Shakib Al Hasan appointed Bangladesh's T20I captain |publisher=Cricket Country |accessdate=22 April 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thedailystar.net/sports/shakib-officially-t20-captain-1394791 |title=Shakib officially T20 captain |work=The Daily Star |accessdate=22 April 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 August 2017, Al Hasan became the 4th bowler in Test history to record a 5-wicket haul against all Test Playing nations (except Afghanistan and Ireland, who have only just granted Test status earlier that year.) when he grabbed 5 wickets against Australia in his first encounter with the team. He also scored a half-century in the first innings. In the second innings, he only scored 8 runs with the bat, but he grabbed another 5 wickets to secure his first 10-wicket haul and the win.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cricket.com.au/news/shakib-al-hasan-five-wicket-haul-bangladesh-australia-every-test-playing-nation-herath-murali-steyn/2017-08-28|title=Shakib joins legends with record five|work=cricket.com.au|access-date=28 August 2017|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://live.cricket.com.au/#/2032/41972|title=Live & Official Cricket Scores {{!}} cricket.com.au|website=live.cricket.com.au|access-date=30 August 2017}}</ref> However, after the series, Al Hasan opted to take a break from Test to focus on limited-overs games.\n\nIn April 2018, he was one of ten cricketers to be awarded a central contract by the [[Bangladesh Cricket Board]] (BCB) ahead of the 2018 season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/23229414/bcb-cuts-contracts-list-2018-ten |title=BCB cuts contracts list for 2018 to ten |work=ESPN Cricinfo |accessdate=18 April 2018}}</ref> Later the same month, he was named in the [[World XI (cricket)|Rest of the World XI]] squad for the [[West Indies v ICC World XI in England in 2018|one-off T20I]] against the [[West Indies national cricket team|West Indies]], played at [[Lord's]] on 31 May 2018,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.icc-cricket.com/media-releases/670194 |title=Rashid, Tamim and Shakib confirmed for ICC World XI team to play the Windies at Lord's |work=International Cricket Council |accessdate=23 April 2018}}</ref> but later withdrew from squad due to personal reason.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.icc-cricket.com/media-releases/691274|title=Sandeep Lamichhane added to the ICC World XI for 31 May T20I against the Windies at Lord's|accessdate=16 May 2018|work=International Cricket Council}}</ref> On 24 May, he became the second T20 player to take 300 wickets and score 4000 runs in the format.<ref>{{cite web|title=Super Shakib joins elite list of T20 greats|url=https://www.cricket.com.au/news/shakib-al-hasan-t20-allrounder-4000-runs-300-wickets-double/2018-04-25|website=cricket.com.au|publisher=Cricket Australia|accessdate=25 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2018, he was named in the squad for the [[Dhaka Dynamites]] team, following the draft for the [[2018\u201319 Bangladesh Premier League]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tigercricket.com.bd/2018/10/29/full-players-list-of-the-teams-following-players-draft-of-bpl-t20-2018-19/ |title=Full players list of the teams following Players Draft of BPL T20 2018\u201319 |work=Bangladesh Cricket Board |accessdate=29 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2018, in the series [[West Indian cricket team in Bangladesh in 2018\u201319|against the West Indies]], he became the first bowler for Bangladesh to [[List of Bangladesh Test cricket records#Most Wickets|take 200 wickets in Tests]].<ref name=\"SAH200\"/> In the same match, he also became the fastest cricketer, in terms of matches, to score 3,000 runs and take 200 wickets in Tests, doing so in his 54th match.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thedailystar.net/sports/bangladesh-cricket/news/shakib-becomes-fastest-200-wicket-3000-run-double-1664536 |title=Shakib becomes fastest to 200-wicket, 3,000-run double |work=The Daily Star (Bangladesh) |accessdate=24 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2019:Cricket World Cup and beyond===\nIn April 2019, he was named as the vice-captain of [[2019 Cricket World Cup squads#Bangladesh|Bangladesh's squad]] for the [[2019 Cricket World Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/26535028/bangladesh-pick-odi-newbie-abu-jayed-world-cup |title=Bangladesh pick ODI newbie Abu Jayed for World Cup |work=ESPN Cricinfo |accessdate=16 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.icc-cricket.com/news/1180213 |title=Shakib, Jayed, Hossain in Bangladesh squad for World Cup |work=International Cricket Council |accessdate=16 April 2019}}</ref> In the first innings of  Bangladesh's opening match in the World Cup, against [[South Africa national cricket team|South Africa]], he and [[Mushfiqur Rahim]] scored 142 runs for the third wicket, the highest partnership for any wicket for Bangladesh in a World Cup match.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.republicworld.com/sports-news/cricket-news/world-cup-2019-what-a-lovely-batting-tigers-rave-netizens-as-shakib-al-hasan-and-mushfiqur-rahims-record-breaking-partnership-sets-bangladesh-up-for-a-big-total-against-south-africa |title=World Cup 2019: \u2018What A Lovely Batting Tigers\u2019, Rave Netizens As Shakib Al Hasan And Mushfiqur Rahim\u2019s Record-breaking Partnership Sets Bangladesh Up For A Big Total Against South Africa |work=Republic World |accessdate=2 June 2019}}</ref> Bangladesh went on to score their [[List of Bangladesh One Day International cricket records#Highest Innings Totals|highest total in an ODI match]], finishing on 330/6 from their 50 overs.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://in.reuters.com/article/cricket-worldcup-zaf-bgd/cricket-record-partnership-spurs-bangladesh-to-score-their-highest-odi-total-idINL8N2390HF |title=Cricket-Record partnership spurs Bangladesh to score their highest ODI total |work=Reuters |accessdate=2 June 2019}}</ref> In the second innings, he took the wicket of [[Aiden Markram]] as  his 250th wicket in ODIs, to become the fastest cricketer to take 250 wickets and score 5,000 runs in ODIs, in terms of number of matches (199).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thedailystar.net/icc-cricket-world-cup-2019/news/shakib-fastest-5k-runs-250-wickets-double-1752502 |title=Shakib fastest to 5k runs, 250 wickets double |work=The Daily Star (Bangladesh) |accessdate=2 June 2019}}</ref> Bangladesh went on to win the match by 21 runs with Shakib named as player of the match. In that match he also became the first cricketer to score a fifty in the first match of Bangladesh in each World Cup since [[2007 Cricket World Cup|2007]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/8039/game/1144487/bangladesh-vs-south-africa-5th-match-icc-cricket-world-cup-2019 |title=5th match, ICC Cricket World Cup at London, Jun 2 2019 |work=ESPN Cricinfo |accessdate=2 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn Bangladesh's next match in the tournament, against [[New Zealand national cricket team|New Zealand]], Shakib played in his 200th ODI.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thedailystar.net/icc-cricket-world-cup-2019/bangladesh-vs-new-zealand-interesting-facts-1753495 |title=Interesting facts ahead of Tigers' game against New Zealand |work=The Daily Star (Bangladesh) |accessdate=5 June 2019}}</ref> On 17 June 2019, in the match against the [[West Indies cricket team|West Indies]], Shakib became the second batsman for Bangladesh to [[List of Bangladesh One Day International cricket records#Most Career Runs|score 6,000 runs in ODIs]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dhakatribune.com/sport/cricket/2019/06/17/shakib-gets-past-6-000-odi-runs |title=Shakib gets past 6,000 ODI runs |work=Dhaka Tribune |accessdate=17 June 2019}}</ref> For his unbeaten 124 he was awarded man of the match.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/sports/cricket-world-cup-2019/story/west-indies-vs-bangladesh-world-cup-2019-report-shakib-al-hasan-hundred-liton-das-1550840-2019-06-17|title= World Cup 2019: Shakib, Liton gun down 322 in record chase as Bangladesh crush West Indies|work= India Today |accessdate=17 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 June 2019, in the match against [[Afghanistan national cricket team|Afghanistan]], where he was again named man of the match, Shakib became the first batsman for Bangladesh to score 1,000 runs in the Cricket World Cup,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/cricket/icc-world-cup-2019-bangladesh-vs-afghanistan-shakib-al-hasan-scripts-unique-world-cup-history-for-bangladesh/story-7oR0TQYDSpW7We3JRIc8mN.html |title=ICC\u2009World Cup 2019, Bangladesh vs Afghanistan:\u2009Shakib Al Hasan scripts unique World Cup history for Bangladesh |work=Hindustan Times |accessdate=24 June 2019}}</ref> and the first bowler for Bangladesh to take a [[five-wicket haul]] in a World Cup match.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/sports/cricket-world-cup-2019/story/bangladesh-vs-afghanistan-world-cup-2019-match-report-shakib-al-hasan-mushfiqur-rahim-1555443-2019-06-24 |title=World Cup 2019: Bangladesh ride on all-round Shakib Al Hasan to inflict 7th-straight defeat on Afghanistan |work=India Today |accessdate=24 June 2019}}</ref> He also became the second cricketer, after [[Yuvraj Singh]], to score 50 runs and take five wickets in the same match at a World Cup.<ref name=\"Indian Express\">{{cite web|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/sports/cricket-world-cup/shakib-al-hasan-yuvraj-singhs-world-cup-record-5797784/ |title=Shakib al Hasan matches Yuvraj Singh\u2019s World Cup record for best all-round performance |work=Indian Express |accessdate=24 June 2019}}</ref> On 2 July 2019, in the match against [[India national cricket team|India]], Shakib became the first cricketer in the World Cup to score 500 runs and take 10 wickets in a single tournament.<ref name=\"The Hindu\">{{cite news |last1=Sportstar |first1=Team |title=Shakib Al Hasan first to 500 runs and 10 wickets in single World Cup |url=https://sportstar.thehindu.com/cricket/icc-cricket-world-cup/news/shakib-al-hasan-world-cup-2019-records-batting-bowling-allrounder-new-zealand-scott-styris/article28263851.ece |accessdate=2 July 2019 |work=[[Sportstar]] |publisher=[[The Hindu]] |date=2 July 2019}}</ref> He finished the tournament as the leading run-scorer for Bangladesh, with 606 runs in eight matches.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/averages/batting_bowling_by_team.html?id=12357;team=25;type=tournament |title=ICC Cricket World Cup, 2019 - Bangladesh: Batting and bowling averages |work=ESPN Cricinfo |accessdate=5 July 2019}}</ref> and surpassed [[Sachin Tendulkar]]'s record for the most runs in the group stage of a World Cup.<ref name=\"hasan\">{{cite web |title=Shakib Al Hasan breaks Sachin Tendulkar' World Cup record |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/sports/cricket-world-cup-2019/story/shakib-al-hasan-breaks-sachin-tendulkar-world-cup-record-1563193-2019-07-05 |first=Saurabh|last=Kumar|website=India Today |date=5 July 2019|accessdate=6 July 2019}}</ref> He was named in the 'Team of the Tournament' by the ICC and ESPNCricinfo.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.icc-cricket.com/news/1278701/featured|title=CWC19: Team of the Tournament |work=ICC |accessdate=25 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/27210608/starc-archer-ferguson-bumrah-espncricinfo-2019-world-cup-xi |title= Starc, Archer, Ferguson, Bumrah in ESPNcricinfo's 2019 World Cup XI|work=ESPNCricinfo |accessdate=25 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2019, during the [[2019\u201320 Bangladesh Tri-Nation Series]], Shakib took his 350th wicket in international cricket, in the final group match against [[Afghanistan national cricket team|Afghanistan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.icc-cricket.com/news/1353055 |title=All-round Shakib gives Bangladesh momentum heading into tri-series final |work=International Cricket Council |accessdate=21 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Disciplinary issues==\nIn October 2010, Shakib was on 92 in the fourth ODI against [[New Zealand cricket team|New Zealand]], when there was movement near the sightscreen, which the umpires failed to stop.<ref name=\"Discipline\">{{Cite news|title= A punishment that should have come earlier|url= http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh/content/story/721459.html|work= [[ESPNcricinfo]]|date= 22 February 2014|accessdate=23 February 2014}}</ref> After a few minutes Shakib, Bangladesh captain at the time, ran towards the sightscreen, hurled abuse and threatened to hit the offender with his bat.<ref name=\"Discipline\" /> He was later warned by the match referee.<ref name=\"Discipline\" />\n\nIn March 2011, during the world cup match against [[West Indies cricket team|West Indies]], several people in the [[Sher-e-Bangla National Cricket Stadium]] grandstand complained Shakib had reacted too strongly when he was booed.<ref name=\"Discipline\" /> The offending picture was spread over the internet and published in several newspapers. Within days of that incident, Shakib blasted former national cricketers in his ''[[Prothom Alo]]'' column.<ref name=\"Discipline\" />\n\nIn February 2014, Shakib was fined BDT 300,000 and was handed with a three-ODI ban, because he had made an indecent gesture towards his crotch in the dressing room live on broadcast, during the second ODI against [[Sri Lanka cricket team|Sri Lanka]].<ref>{{Cite news|title= Shakib suspended for three ODIs|url= http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh/content/story/721171.html|work= [[ESPNcricinfo]]|date= 21 February 2014|accessdate=23 February 2014}}</ref> Shakib later made a public apology statement through his official [[Facebook]] page.<ref>{{Cite news|title= Shakib offers an apology|url= http://bdnews24.com/cricket/2014/02/22/shakib-offers-an-apology|publisher= [[bdnews24.com]]|date= 22 February 2014|accessdate=23 February 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2014, Shakib was allegedly involved in a brawl between him and a spectator, who was allegedly harassing Shakib's wife in the grand stand of Sher-e-Bangla National Cricket Stadium, during the first ODI against [[India cricket team|India]].<ref>{{Cite news|title= BCB to investigate alleged altercation between Shakib, spectator|url= http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh-v-india-2014/content/story/752783.html|work= ESPNcricinfo|date= 15 June 2014|accessdate=8 July 2014}}</ref> Shakib violated rules by \"leaving the team dressing room during the course of an international match\".<ref>{{Cite news|title= Shakib attends BCB hearing over alleged altercation|url= http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh/content/story/754361.html|work= ESPNcricinfo|date= 21 June 2014|accessdate=8 July 2014}}</ref> Shakib later filed a case the following day regarding the incident.<ref>{{Cite news|title= Man held for \u2018harassing\u2019 Shakib's wife|url= http://bdnews24.com/bangladesh/2014/06/19/man-held-for-harassing-shakibs-wife|work= [[bdnews24.com]]|date= 19 June 2014|accessdate=8 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nDuring the 6th T20I match which was a controversial tense clash between Sri Lanka and Bangladesh as a part of the [[2018 Nidahas Trophy]], he argued the poor umpiring errors for not signalling a \"no ball\" delivery when [[Isuru Udana]] bowled 2 short pitched bouncer deliveries to [[Mustafizur Rahman]] in the last over of the match, where Bangladesh needed 12 runs to victory off the six balls.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/22803467/shakib-nurul-fined-breaching-code-conduct|title=Shakib, Nurul fined for breaching code of conduct|work=ESPNcricinfo|access-date=17 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cricbuzz.com/cricket-news/101036/shakib-al-hasan-nurul-hasan-nidahas-trophy-fined-25-percent-for-altercation|title=Shakib, Nurul fined for breaching ICC code of conduct|work=Cricbuzz|access-date=17 March 2018|language=en}}</ref> Fellow cricketer, [[Mahmudullah]] who was on the non-striker's end when Mustafizur Rahman was batting, demanded a no-ball delivery from the on-field umpires. Shakib later threatened to leave the field and recalled the batsmen from the field as a result of the umpiring errors. Reserve Bangladeshi cricketer, [[Nurul Hasan (cricketer)|Nurul Hasan]] was also suspected to have breached the code of conduct for exchanging war of words with Sri Lankan skipper, [[Thisara Perera]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thedailystar.net/sports/bangladesh-cricket/hot-rivalry-what-cost-1549450|title=A hot rivalry, but at what cost?|date=2018-03-17|work=The Daily Star|access-date=17 March 2018|language=en}}</ref> It was also revealed that Shakib exchanged arguments with Sri Lankan commentator [[Russell Arnold]]. The [[International Cricket Council]] later imposed a 25 percent fine and issued a demerit point to both Shakib and [[Nurul Hasan (cricketer)|Nurul Hasan]] for their unruly behaviour on the field by breaching the code of ethics.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/cricket/india-sri-lanka-bangladesh-tri-series/shakib-al-hasan-nurul-hasan-docked-25-percent-match-fee/articleshow/63344033.cms|title=Shakib Al Hasan, Nurul Hasan docked 25 percent match fee \u2013 Times of India|work=The Times of India|access-date=17 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.firstpost.com/firstcricket/sports-news/nidahas-trophy-2018-shakib-al-hasan-fined-handed-demerit-point-nurul-hasan-penalised-for-breaching-iccs-code-of-conduct-4394401.html|title=Nidahas Trophy 2018: Shakib Al Hasan fined, handed demerit point; Nurul Hasan penalised for breaching ICC's code of conduct- Firstcricket News, Firstpost|website=FirstCricket|language=en-US|access-date=17 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://zeenews.india.com/cricket/shakib-al-hasan-nurul-hasan-receive-punishment-for-breaching-icc-code-of-conduct-2090760.html|title=Shakib Al Hasan, Nurul Hasan receive punishment for breaching ICC Code of Conduct|date=2018-03-17|work=Zee News|access-date=2018-03-17|language=en}}</ref>\n\n===International ban===\nOn 7 July 2014, Shakib was banned for eight months from all forms of cricket for what the [[Bangladesh Cricket Board]] described as a \"severe attitude problem\".<ref name=\"Banned\">{{cite web | url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh/content/story/758155.html | title=Shakib Al Hasan suspended for six months by BCB | work=ESPNcricinfo| date=7 July 2014 | accessdate=8 July 2014}}</ref> Shakib missed Bangladesh's [[Bangladesh cricket team in West Indies in 2014|tour of the West Indies]]; he was also prohibited to participate in foreign tournaments until 31 December 2015.<ref name=\"Banned\"/> Controversy arose when Shakib left to play for the [[Barbados Tridents]] of the [[Caribbean Premier League]], allegedly without informing board officials and without obtaining a [[No Objection Certificate]] from the board, a claim he has denied.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh/content/story/757945.html | title='I never said I would quit' \u2013 Shakib| work=ESPNcricinfo| date=6 July 2014 | accessdate=8 July 2014}}</ref> Shakib found himself embroiled in further controversy after a dispute with coach [[Chandika Hathurusingha]] led to rumours of him threatening to retire from Test and One Day cricket.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh/content/story/757629.html | title=Shakib threatens to quit international cricket| work=ESPNcricinfo| date=5 July 2014 | accessdate=8 July 2014}}</ref> The BCB has ended the restriction on no-objection certificates being issued to Bangladesh all-rounder Shakib Al Hasan, leaving him free to participate in overseas tournaments. BCB reduced his ban by three a half months on 26 August 2014 letting him play for Bangladesh from 15 September 2014.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh/content/story/807379.html | title=Shakib's NOC restriction lifted| work=ESPNcricinfo| date=4 December 2014 | accessdate=4 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nShakib was initially selected to lead the team in the [[Bangladeshi cricket team in India in 2019\u201320|T20I and Test series against India]], but on 29 October 2019, Shakib was suspended for one year and banned from all forms of cricket for two years by the [[International Cricket Council]] for breaching the ICC-Anti Corruption Code. Shakib was supposedly contacted by bookmakers while playing in the [[2018 Bangladesh Tri-Nation Series]] and also in a group match between [[Sunrisers Hyderabad]] and [[Kings XI Punjab]] in the [[2018 Indian Premier League]] . For failing to report those approaches made to him by the bookmakers, he was found guilty of breaching the ICC ''Anti-Corruption Code 2.4.4'' and was handed a two-year ban, one year being suspended. He is supposed to be able to resume international cricket on 29 October 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cricbuzz.com/cricket-news/110552/shakib-al-hasan-icc-bcb-ban-banned-suspended-bangladesh-cricket-team |title=ICC bans Shakib Al Hasan for two years |work=Cricbuzz|date=29 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==== Players strike ====\nShakib also led a players' strike which existed for a brief period of time from 21 October 2019 to 23 October 2019 demanding for higher salaries especially in domestic first class cricket system and issues related to proposal of Bangladesh Premier League to adopt the franchise method.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/50136104|title=Bangladesh Cricket Board calls players' strike a conspiracy|access-date=31 October 2019|work=[[BBC]]}}</ref> He along with fellow players reportedly addressed the pay dispute issue to the media and even threatened to boycott the [[Bangladeshi cricket team in India in 2019\u201320|tour of India]] and the rest of international cricket season until their demands were to be fulfilled.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/10/bangladesh-cricketers-strike-pay-demands-191021114726557.html|title=Bangladesh cricketers go on strike seeking demands|access-date=31 October 2019|work=[[Al Jazeera]]}}</ref> However the issue was sorted out as the BCB accepted to fulfill the demand of the players by offering salary increments.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/27909061/bangladesh-players-go-strike|title=Full coverage: Player revolt in Bangladesh cricket|access-date=31 October 2019|work=Cricinfo}}</ref> During the time when he was leading the players' strike, he was also accused for breaching the agreement with BCB by signing a sponsorship deal as an ambassador for an undisclosed amount with a leading telecommunication operator called [[Grameenphone]] which is also a former national team sponsor.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geosuper.tv/latest/3141-bangladesh-to-take-captain-to-court-over|title=Bangladesh to take Shakib to court over breaching the agreement|access-date=31 October 2019|work=[[Geo Super]]}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nShakib studied for a [[English major|BA in English]] at [[American International University-Bangladesh]] (AIUB).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aiub.edu/aiub-inter-dept-twenty20-cricket-tournament-2009|title=AIUB Inter Dept. Twenty20 Cricket Tournament 2009|publisher=AIUB|accessdate=23 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nHe married Umme Ahmed Shishir, a [[Bangladeshi American]] in December 2012.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh/content/story/596892.html |title=\nShakib ties knot with US-based girl |first=Mohammad |last=Isam |work=ESPNcricinfo |date=12 December 2012 |accessdate=12 December 2012}}</ref><ref>{{citation |url=http://bdnews24.com/details.php?id=238050&cid=26 |title=\nShakib starts 'new innings' |first= |last= |work=[[Bdnews24.com]] |date=12 December 2012 |accessdate=12 December 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Demotix\">{{citation |url=http://www.demotix.com/news/1673040/cricketer-sakib-al-hasan-marries-bangladesh |title= Cricketer Shakib Al Hasan marries |first=Anisul |last=Islam |work=[[Demotix]] |date=12 December 2012 |accessdate=12 December 2012}}</ref> The couple met each other in 2011 while Shakib was playing [[county cricket]] for [[Worcestershire County Cricket Club|Worcestershire]] in England.<ref name=\"Demotix\" /> They had their first daughter Alayna Aubrey Hasan  in 8 November 2015. In August 2018 he became a [[Lawful permanent residents (United States)|green card holder]] which allows him to live and work in the US. <!-- Despite what the headline in the ref says a green card doesn't mean that one automatically becomes a citizen. See the Lawful permanent residents (United States) article. --><ref>{{citation|url=https://newsbeezer.com/bangladesh/shakib-is-now-a-us-citizen-got-greencard/|title=Shakib is now a US citizen, got greencard!|work=NewsBeezer|accessdate=3 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Records and achievements==\n{{see also|List of international cricket five-wicket hauls by Shakib Al Hasan|Five-wicket haul#List of bowlers who have taken five-wicket hauls in all three international formats}}\n\n* Best partnership record for any wicket for a Bangladeshi pair in ODIs, with Mahmadullah (224).<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/fow/highest_partnerships_by_wicket.html?class=2;id=25;type=team|title=Cricket Records/ Bangladesh/ One-Day Internationals/ Highest partnerships by wicket|work=Cricinfo|access-date=30 August 2017}}</ref> (This is also the highest ever 5th wicket runs stand in the history of [[ICC Champions Trophy]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/fow/highest_partnerships_by_wicket.html?id=44;type=trophy|title=Cricket Records/ ICC Champions Trophy/ Highest partnerships by wicket|work=Cricinfo|access-date=30 August 2017}}</ref>)\n* Most wickets taken in [[Twenty20|T20 cricket]] on a single ground (76 at [[Sher-e-Bangla National Cricket Stadium|Shere Bangla National Stadium]], [[Mirpur Model Thana|Mirpur]])<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/records/305216.html|title=Records/ Twenty20 matches/ Bowling records/ Most wickets on a single ground|work=Cricinfo|access-date=10 June 2017}}</ref>\n* Fourth bowler in Test cricket history to pick up 5-wickets hauls against all Test playing nations (after [[Dale Steyn]], [[Muttiah Muralitharan]] and [[Rangana Herath]])<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cricket.com.au/news/shakib-al-hasan-five-wicket-haul-bangladesh-australia-every-test-playing-nation-herath-murali-steyn/2017-08-28|title=Shakib joins legends with record five |work=Cricket.com.au |accessdate=28 August 2017}}</ref>\n* Third all-rounder in the history of international cricket to reach 10,000 runs and take 500 wickets, fastest to do so<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kumar |first1=Ram |title=Stats: Shakib Al Hasan fastest to register 10,000 runs and 500 wickets in international cricket history |url=https://www.sportskeeda.com/cricket/stats-shakib-al-hasan-fastest-to-register-10-000-runs-and-500-wickets-in-international-cricket-history |accessdate=16 June 2018 |agency=sportskeeda |date=7 June 2018}}</ref>\n* First spin bowler, and third player overall (with [[Wasim Akram]] and [[Waqar Younis|Waqar Yonis]] grabbing 100+ each at [[Sharjah Cricket Stadium|Sharjah]] stadium), to grab 100+ ODI wickets at a single ground. (112 at  [[Sher-e-Bangla National Cricket Stadium|Sher-e-Bangla National Stadium]])<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/records/283947.html|title=Records {{!}} One-Day Internationals {{!}} Bowling records {{!}} Most wickets on a single ground {{!}} ESPNcricinfo|work=Cricinfo|access-date=2018-08-13}}</ref>\n* In 2017 [[Bangladeshi cricket team in New Zealand in 2016\u201317#1st Test|in the 1st Test between Bangladesh and New Zealand]], he became only Seventh batsman to score a double century and got a duck in a test when he scored 217 and 0.<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/18542322/double-duck-tail-end-highs|title=Double and a duck|work=ESPNCricinfo}}</ref>\n* Only The Third all-rounder in the World to score a century and take a 10 Wicket-haul in a match after Sir [[Ian Botham]] and [[Imran Khan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sportskeeda.com/cricket/all-rounders-who-scored-a-century-and-picked-10-wickets-in-the-same-test|title=3 all-rounders who scored a century and picked 10 wickets in the same Test|author=Depak Panda|work=[[Sportskeeda]]|accessdate=22 November 2014}}</ref>\n* Only all-rounder in the cricket history to be ranked #1 Alrounder In all three formats.\n* Fastest all-rounder to score 3000 Test Runs and take 200 Test wicket (54 Test) surpassing [[Ian Botham]] who took 55 test matches to reach the milestone.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://zeenews.india.com/cricket/shakib-al-hasan-becomes-fastest-to-reach-3000-runs-200-wickets-in-tests-2158203.html|title=Shakib Al Hasan becomes fastest to reach 3000 runs; 200 wickets in Tests|work=[[Zee News]]|accessdate=23 November 2018}}</ref>\n* Fastest all-rounder to score 5000 ODI Runs and take 200 ODI wickets.{{Citation needed|date=June 2019}}\n* First Bangladeshi Bowler to take 500 international wickets.{{Citation needed|date=June 2019}}\n* Second Bangladeshi Batsmen to score 10,000 International Runs.{{Citation needed|date=June 2019}} \n* Most Test (203*) and T20I (85*) wicket taker for  Bangladesh.\n* Shakib leads the table of scoring most runs on a single ground (3980 runs in 120 innings)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/records/284230.html|title=Records/ Test, ODI, T20I/ Most runs on a single ground|work=ESPNCricinfo}}</ref> and most wickets on a single ground (190 wickets in 110 matches) combining all formats.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/records/283945.html|title=Records/ Test, ODI, T20I/ Most wickets on a single ground|work=ESPNCricinfo}}</ref>\n* In December 2018 in the [[West Indian cricket team in Bangladesh in 2018\u201319#2nd T20I|2nd T20I against West Indies]], Shakib become the eighth cricketer to take at least one five wicket-haul in all three formats.{{efn|other seven players being [[Tim Southee]], [[Lasith Malinga]], [[Ajantha Mendis]], [[Bhuvneshwar Kumar]], [[Umar Gul]], [[Imran Tahir]] and [[Kuldeep Yadav]]}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newsnation.in/sports-news/cricket-news/shakib-al-hasan-five-wicket-haul-world-record-bangladesh-vs-west-indies-mirpur-t20i-article-209507.html |title=Shakib Al Hasan enters elite list after five-wicket haul... |work=News Nation |accessdate=20 December 2018}}</ref>\n* Best bowling figure by a captain (5/20) in a T20I match and the only captain to pick up a five-fer in T20Is.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/records/283935.html|title=T20I Bowling Records/ Best figures in a innings by a captain|work=ESPNCricinfo}}</ref>\n* In the first match of [[2019 Cricket World Cup group stage#Bangladesh vs South Africa|against South Africa in 2019 World Cup]], he became become the second Bangladeshi bowler to bag 250 ODI wickets and the fastest and the fifth player to score 5000 runs and to take 250 wickets in ODIs in just 199 matches. (Others cricketer being [[Abdul Razzak]], [[Sanath Jayasuriya]], [[Jacques Kallis]] and [[Shahid Afridi]])<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.timesnownews.com/sports/cricket/article/icc-world-cup-2019-shakib-al-hasan-scripts-massive-world-record-becomes-fastest-to-take-250-wickets-and-score-5000-runs-in-odis/430073| title=Shakib Al Hasan scripts massive world record, becomes fastest to take 250 wickets and score 5000 runs in ODIs| work=Times Now|date=2 June 2019}}</ref>\n*Shakib is one of only three cricketers with 4,000 runs and 300 wickets in T20s. He achieved this milestone in 260 matches, faster that the other two who achieved the mark, [[Shahid Afridi]] (283) and [[Dwayne Bravo]] (292).\n*Shakib is the fastest to score 11,000 runs and to get 500 wickets.\n* In [[2019 Cricket World Cup]], Shakib became quickest All-rounder, in terms of innings, to achieve the double of 6,000 runs and 250 wickets in ODIs and overall fourth cricketer to achieve the double.{{efn|others three cricketers are [[Sanath Jayasuriya]], [[Jacques Kallis]] and [[Shahid Afridi]].}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sportstar.thehindu.com/cricket/icc-cricket-world-cup/news/shakib-al-hasan-records-best-allrounder-6000-runs-wickets-jacques-kallis/article28022408.ece|title=World Cup 2019: Shakib Al Hasan slams century, topples records|work=Sportstar|publisher=The Hindu|date=17 June 2019}}</ref>\n* In [[2019 Cricket World Cup]] group match [[2019 Cricket World Cup group stage#Afghanistan vs Bangladesh|against Afghanistan]], Shakib achieved several milestones.\n** Shakib became first Bangladeshi player to score 1,000 runs in World Cup and also the first from Bangladesh to pick up a five wicket haul in World Cup.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/cricket/icc-world-cup-2019-bangladesh-vs-afghanistan-shakib-al-hasan-scripts-unique-world-cup-history-for-bangladesh/story-7oR0TQYDSpW7We3JRIc8mN.html |title=ICC\u2009World Cup 2019, Bangladesh vs Afghanistan:\u2009Shakib Al Hasan scripts unique World Cup history for Bangladesh |work=Hindustan Times |accessdate=24 June 2019}}</ref>\n** He became the only cricketer to score 1,000 runs and pick up 30 wickets in World Cup alongside the only one to score 600 runs and pick up 10 wickets in a single tournament of World Cup.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.prothomalo.com/sports/article/1600972/|title=\n\u09b0\u09c7\u0995\u09b0\u09cd\u09a1\u099f\u09bf\u09b0 \u0995\u09a5\u09be \u09ae\u09be\u09a5\u09be\u09af\u09bc \u099b\u09bf\u09b2 \u09b8\u09be\u0995\u09bf\u09ac\u09c7\u09b0 |work=Prothom Alo|date=25 June 2019|language=bn}}</ref>\n** He became the second cricketer after [[Yuvraj Singh]] to score a 50 and pick up a 5 wicket haul in World Cup match.<ref name=\"Indian Express\"/>\n* In [[2019 Cricket World Cup|2019 World Cup]] group match [[2019 Cricket World Cup group stage#Bangladesh vs India|against India]], Shakib became first ever cricketer to score 500 runs and pick up 10 wickets in a single tournament of World Cup.<ref name=\"The Hindu\"/>\n* In [[2019 Cricket World Cup|2019 World Cup]] group match [[2019 Cricket World Cup group stage#Pakistan vs Bangladesh|against Pakistan]], Shakib equalled [[Sachin Tendulkar]]'s record of making the [[List of Cricket World Cup records#One tournament|most 50+ runs in a single World Cup tournament]] (7).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/sports/cricket-world-cup-2019/story/shakib-al-hasan-breaks-sachin-tendulkar-world-cup-record-1563193-2019-07-05 |title=Shakib Al Hasan breaks Sachin Tendulkar' World Cup record|work=India Today|date=5 July 2019}}</ref> and also became the first Bangladeshi and third player in the world to score more than 600 runs in a single World Cup.\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* {{Cricinfo|ref=ci/content/player/56143.html}}\n* [https://www.cricbuzz.com/profiles/544/shakib-al-hasan  Shakib Al Hasan Profile] on [[Cricbuzz]]\n\n{{s-start-collapsible|header={{S-sports}}}}\n{{succession box|\n before=[[Mashrafe Mortaza]]|\n title=[[Bangladeshi national cricket captains|Bangladesh national cricket captain]]|\n years=2009\u20132010 |\n after= [[Mashrafe Mortaza]]\n}}\n{{succession box|\n before=[[Mashrafe Mortaza]]|\n title=[[Bangladeshi national cricket captains|Bangladesh national cricket captain]]|\n years=2010\u20132011 |\n after= [[Mushfiqur Rahim]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Current national cricket captains}}\n{{Navboxes colour\n|title= Captaincy\n|bg= #006838\n|fg=red\n|bordercolor=red\n|list1=\n{{Bangladeshi Test cricket captains}}\n{{Bangladesh ODI cricket captains}}\n{{Bangladesh T20I cricket captains}}\n}}\n{{Navboxes colour\n|title= Bangladesh squads\n|bg= #006838\n|fg= red\n|bordercolor=red\n|list1=\n{{Bangladesh Squad 2007 Cricket World Cup}}\n{{Bangladesh Squad 2011 Cricket World Cup}}\n{{Bangladesh Squad 2015 Cricket World Cup}}\n{{Bangladesh Squad 2019 Cricket World Cup}}\n}}\n{{Dhaka Dynamites squad}}\n{{Sunrisers Hyderabad Squad}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Shakib al Hasan}}\n[[Category:1987 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Bangladeshi cricketers]]\n[[Category:Bangladesh Test cricketers]]\n[[Category:Bangladesh One Day International cricketers]]\n[[Category:Bangladesh Twenty20 International cricketers]]\n[[Category:Bengali people]]\n[[Category:Kolkata Knight Riders cricketers]]\n[[Category:Sunrisers Hyderabad cricketers]]\n[[Category:Khulna Division cricketers]]\n[[Category:Worcestershire cricketers]]\n[[Category:Leicestershire cricketers]]\n[[Category:Cricketers at the 2007 Cricket World Cup]]\n[[Category:Cricketers at the 2011 Cricket World Cup]]\n[[Category:Cricketers at the 2015 Cricket World Cup]]\n[[Category:Dhaka Dynamites cricketers]]\n[[Category:Khulna Royal Bengals cricketers]]\n[[Category:Melbourne Renegades cricketers]]\n[[Category:Barbados Tridents cricketers]]\n[[Category:Adelaide Strikers cricketers]]\n[[Category:People from Khulna]]\n[[Category:Asian Games medalists in cricket]]\n[[Category:Cricketers at the 2014 Asian Games]]\n[[Category:Asian Games bronze medalists for Bangladesh]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2014 Asian Games]]\n[[Category:Asian Games competitors for Bangladesh]]\n[[Category:Karachi Kings cricketers]]\n[[Category:Peshawar Zalmi cricketers]]\n[[Category:Bangladesh Test cricket captains]]\n[[Category:Jamaica Tallawahs cricketers]]\n[[Category:Legends of Rupganj cricketers]]\n[[Category:Kala Bagan Krira Chakra cricketers]]\n[[Category:Prime Bank Cricket Club cricketers]]\n[[Category:Abahani Limited cricketers]]\n[[Category:Rangpur Riders cricketers]]\n[[Category:Bangladesh under-19 cricketers]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Bangladesh National Sports Award]]\n[[Category:People from Magura District]]\n[[Category:Cricketers at the 2019 Cricket World Cup]]\n", "text_old": "{{Fanpov|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2013}} \n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2013}}\n{{short description|Bangladeshi cricketer}}\n{{Infobox cricketer\n| name = Shakib-Al-Hasan\n| image = Shakib Al Hasan (4) (cropped).jpg\n| caption = Shakib in 2018\n| fullname = Shakib Al Hasan\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1987|3|24|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Magura District]], [[Bangladesh]]\n| heightm = 1.75\n| batting = Left-handed\n| bowling = [[Slow left-arm orthodox]]\n| role = [[All-rounder]]\n| country = Bangladesh\n| international = true\n| internationalspan = 2006\u2013present\n| testdebutdate = 18 May\n| testdebutyear = 2007\n| testdebutagainst = India\n| testcap = 46\n| lasttestdate = 5 September\n| lasttestyear = 2019\n| lasttestagainst = Afghanistan\n| odidebutdate = 6 August\n| odidebutyear = 2006\n| odidebutagainst = Zimbabwe\n| odicap = 82\n| lastodidate = 5 July\n| lastodiyear = 2019\n| lastodiagainst = Pakistan\n| odishirt = 75\n| T20Idebutdate = 28 November\n| T20Idebutyear = 2006\n| T20Idebutagainst = Zimbabwe\n| T20Icap = 11\n| lastT20Ifor = Bangladesh\n| lastT20Iagainst = Afghanistan\n| lastT20Idate = 21 September\n| lastT20Iyear = 2019\n| club1 = [[Khulna Division cricket team|Khulna Division]]\n| year1 = 2004\u20132019\n| club2 = [[Worcestershire County Cricket Club|Worcestershire]]\n| year2 = 2010\u20132011\n| club3 = [[Kolkata Knight Riders]]\n| year3 = 2011\u20132017\n| clubnumber3 = 75\n| club4 = [[Khulna Royal Bengals]]\n| year4 = 2012\n| club5 = [[Uthura Rudras]]\n| year5 = 2012\n| club6 = [[Dhaka Gladiators]]\n| year6 = 2013\n| club7 = [[Leicestershire County Cricket Club|Leicestershire]]\n| year7 = 2013\n| club8 = [[Barbados Tridents]]\n| year8 = 2013, 2018\u20132019\n| clubnumber8 = 75\n| club9 = [[Adelaide Strikers]]\n| year9 = 2014\n| clubnumber9 = 75\n| club10 = [[Melbourne Renegades]]\n| year10 = 2015\n| clubnumber10 = 75\n| club11 = [[Rangpur Riders]]\n| year11 = 2015\n| club12 = [[Karachi Kings]]\n| year12 = 2016\n| clubnumber12 = 75\n| club13 = [[Jamaica Tallawahs]]\n| year13 = 2016\u20132017\n| clubnumber13 = 75\n| club14 = [[Dhaka Dynamites]]\n| year14 = 2016\u20132019\n| clubnumber14 = 75\n| club15 = [[Peshawar Zalmi]]\n| year15 = 2017\u20132018\n| clubnumber15 = 77\n| club16 = [[Sunrisers Hyderabad]]\n| year16 = 2018\u20132019\n| clubnumber16 = 75\n| columns = 4\n| column1 = [[Test cricket|Test]]\n| column2 = [[One Day International|ODI]]\n| column3 = [[Twenty20 International cricket|T20I]]\n| column4 = [[First-class cricket|FC]]\n| matches1 = 56\n| matches2 = 206\n| matches3 = 76\n| matches4 = 92\n| runs1 = 3,862\n| runs2 = 6,323\n| runs3 = 1,567\n| runs4 = 5,777\n| bat avg1 = 39.40\n| bat avg2 = 37.86\n| bat avg3 = 23.74\n| bat avg4 = 37.27\n| 100s/50s1 = 5/24\n| 100s/50s2 = 9/47\n| 100s/50s3 = 0/9\n| 100s/50s4 = 8/34\n| top score1 = 217\n| top score2 = 134[[not out|*]]\n| top score3 = 84\n| top score4 = 217\n| deliveries1 = 13,020\n| deliveries2 = 10,517\n| deliveries3 = 1,667\n| deliveries4 = 19,170\n| wickets1 = 210\n| wickets2 = 260\n| wickets3 = 92\n| wickets4 = 310\n| bowl avg1 = 31.12\n| bowl avg2 = 30.21\n| bowl avg3 = 20.58\n| bowl avg4 = 30.03\n| fivefor1 = 18\n| fivefor2 = 2\n| fivefor3 = 1\n| fivefor4 = 23\n| tenfor1 = 2\n| tenfor2 = 0\n| tenfor3 = 0\n| tenfor4 = 2\n| best bowling1 = 7/36\n| best bowling2 = 5/29\n| best bowling3 = 5/20\n| best bowling4 = 7/32\n| catches/stumpings1 = 24/\u2013\n| catches/stumpings2 = 50/\u2013\n| catches/stumpings3 = 19/\u2013\n| catches/stumpings4 = 47/\u2013\n| source = http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh/content/player/56143.html ESPNcricinfo\n| date = 21 September \n| year = 2019\n}}\n'''Shakib Al Hasan''' ({{lang-bn|\u09b8\u09be\u0995\u09bf\u09ac \u0986\u09b2 \u09b9\u09be\u09b8\u09be\u09a8}}; born 24 March 1987) is a Bangladeshi international [[cricket]]er who has played all three formats of the game. Internationally, Shakib has been recognised as one of the greatest all-rounders of all time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://iccrankings.cricket.com.pk/allrounder/|title=All Rounder Rankings|publisher=|accessdate=27 October 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricket.com.au/news/feature/shakib-al-hasan-bangaldesh-worlds-number-one-allrounder/2015-01-17|title=Bangladesh's finest pursues greatness|publisher=|accessdate=27 October 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/education/story/bangladeshi-player-shakib-al-hasan-named-best-all-rounder-in-all-formats-by-international-cricket-council/1/447455.html|title=Bangladeshi Player Shakib Al Hasan named best all-rounder in all formats by ICC: Some interesting facts about the cricketer : Sports Arena|publisher=|accessdate=27 October 2016}}</ref> He was ranked as one of the world's most famous athletes by [[ESPN.com|ESPN]] WORLD FAME 100 in 2019.<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.espn.com/espn/feature/story/_/id/26113613/espn-world-fame-100-2019#shakib-al-hasan |title=Shakib in the list of ESPN WORLD FAME 100 in 2019 |publisher=ESPN|accessdate=13 March 2019}}</ref>\nHis aggressive left-handed batting style in the [[batting order (cricket)|middle order]], controlled [[Left-arm orthodox spin|slow left-arm orthodox]] bowling, and athletic fielding has helped him win trophies in top leagues across the world.<ref>{{cricinfo|id=56143|accessdate=25 September 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/18515383/curious-case-shakib-al-hasan|title=The curious case of Shakib Al Hasan|work=ESPNcricinfo|access-date=2018-07-13}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, Shakib became the first and only cricketer in history to be ranked the 'No.1 all-rounder' by [[International Cricket Council|ICC]] in its [[ICC Player Rankings|Player Rankings]] in all three formats of the game (Test, Twenty20 and One Day Internationals).<ref>{{citation|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/sports/cricket/story/shakib-al-hasan-ranked-best-testodi-and-t20-all-rounder-in-icc-player-rankings-259782-2015-06-26|title=Shakib ranked number one all-rounder in all three formats  |publisher=India Today |accessdate=26 June 2019}}</ref> He is currently ranked no.1 in odis and no.2 in tests and t-20s. On 13 January 2017, he registered the highest individual score (217) by a Bangladeshi batsman in Tests.<ref>{{Cite web |first=Alagappan |last=Muthu|date=12 January 2017|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/new-zealand-v-bangladesh-2016-17/content/story/1077214.html |title=Mominul, Tamim sparkle on rain-hit day |website=ESPNcricinfo |access-date=25 September 2017}}</ref> In November 2018, he became the first bowler for Bangladesh to [[List of Bangladesh Test cricket records#Most Wickets|take 200 wickets in Tests]].<ref name=\"SAH200\">{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/25359369/shakib-al-hasan-becomes-quickest-3000-runs-200-wickets-double |title=Shakib becomes the quickest to 3000 runs-200 wickets double |work=ESPN Cricinfo |accessdate=24 November 2018}}</ref> In June 2019, Shakib became the fastest player to score 6,000 runs and take 250 wickets in ODIs in just 199 matches.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bdcrictime.com/shakib-al-hasan-fastest-to-reach-6000-runs-and-250-wickets-in-odis/ |title=Shakib Al Hasan fastest to reach 6000 runs and 250 wickets in ODIs |work=BDCricTime |accessdate=28 June 2019}}</ref> He is the highest run scorer as well as the highest wicket taker for Bangladesh in ICC ODI World Cups. He is also the only cricketer to score 1000 runs and to take 30 wickets in World Cup. At the [[2019 Cricket World Cup]], Shakib became the first cricketer to score 600{{nbsp}}runs and take 10{{nbsp}}wickets in a single World Cup.\n\nOn 29 October 2019, the [[International Cricket Council]] (ICC) banned Shakib from all cricket for two years, with one year suspended, after breaching the ICC's Anti-Corruption Code.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.icc-cricket.com/media-releases/1473892 |title=Shakib Al Hasan banned after accepting three charges under ICC Anti-Corruption Code |work=International Cricket Council |accessdate=29 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Early years and youth cricket==\nBorn in [[Magura District|Magura]], [[Khulna Division|Khulna]], Shakib started playing cricket at an early age. According to ''[[Prothom Alo]]'' sports editor Utpal Shuvro, Shakib \"was fairly proficient at cricket and was often hired to play for different villages and teams\".<ref name=\"From Magura to No. 1\">{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/magazine/content/story/389383.html |title=From Magura to No. 1 |first=Utpal |last=Shuvro |work=ESPNcricinfo |date=6 February 2009 |accessdate=31 October 2010}}</ref> In one of those matches, Shakib impressed an umpire who arranged for him to practice with the Islampur Para Club, a team in the Magura Cricket League. During the practice session, Shakib batted aggressively and bowled fast, as he usually did, but also chose to experiment with spin bowling which proved to be not so effective. He was picked to play for Islampur and took a wicket with his first ball; it was his first delivery with a proper cricket ball, having previously played with a [[tape ball|taped tennis ball]].{{Citation needed|date=August 2019}} He spent six months training at [[Bangladesh Krira Shiksha Pratisthan]],<ref name=\"From Magura to No. 1\"/> a government-run sports institute.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.bkspbd.org/why_bksp.html |title=About BKSP |publisher=Bangladesh Krira Shikkha Protishtan |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100130201357/http://www.bkspbd.org/why_bksp.html |archive-date=30 January 2010 |accessdate=23 February 2011}}</ref> and in 2004, at the age of 17, was drafted by [[Khulna Division cricket team|Khulna]] to play in the National Domestic League.\n\nShakib first represented Bangladesh at the U-19 level, debuting in August 2006 against [[Zimbabwe national cricket team|Zimbabwe]] at [[Harare Sports Club]]. He played an important part in Bangladesh's victory, where he scored 30 runs and bowled out [[Elton Chigumbura]] to get his first ODI wicket.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/249207.html|work=ESPNcricinfo|title=Scorecard: Bangladesh tour of Zimbabwe, 5th ODI: Zimbabwe v Bangladesh at Harare, 6 August 2006}}</ref> In 2005, during the final of a tri-nation tournament involving England and Sri Lanka's Under-19 teams, Shakib scored an 86-ball century and took three wickets to lead his team to victory.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh/content/story/229488.html |title=Saqibul Hasan blasts Bangladesh to victory|work=[[ESPNcricinfo]] |date=13 December 2005 |accessdate=7 November 2009}}</ref> Between 2005 and 2006, Shakib played 18&nbsp;youth One Day Internationals; he scored 563&nbsp;runs at an [[Batting average (cricket)|average]] of 35.18, and took 22&nbsp;wickets at an [[bowling average|average]] of 20.18.<ref>{{citation |url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/73/73152/73152.html |title=Shakib Al Hasan |work=CricketArchive|url-access=subscription |accessdate=7 November 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Domestic and T20 franchise cricket==\nDomestically Shakib has represented Khulna since 2004, and in 2010 spent several months playing for [[Worcestershire County Cricket Club|Worcestershire]] in England, becoming the first Bangladeshi player to represent an [[County cricket|English county cricket]] team. For the [[2011 Indian Premier League]], Shakib was contracted by [[Kolkata Knight Riders]]. Shakib was released by KKR and was picked up by [[Sunrisers Hyderabad]] in the [[List of 2018 Indian Premier League personnel changes|2018 IPL personnel changes]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thedailystar.net/sports/bangladesh-cricket/shakib-al-hasan-gaining-confidence-each-sunrisers-hyderabad-session-1558471|title=Shakib al hasan gaining confidence each sunrisershyderabad session|website=dailystar.net}}</ref> In the [[2012 Bangladesh Premier League|first season of Bangladesh Premier League]], he captained [[Khulna Royal Bengals]], and in the [[2013 Bangladesh Premier League|second season]] he led [[Dhaka Gladiators]] to the tournament title. In the [[2015 Bangladesh Premier League|2015 season]] he played for [[Rangpur Riders]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thedailystar.net/sports/icons-find-teams-bpl-161047|title=BPL: Shakib to lead Rangpur, Mushfiq Sylhet, Tamim Ctg|work=The Daily Star}}</ref> and from [[2016 Bangladesh Premier League|2016 season]] he is playing for [[Dhaka Dynamites]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://m.bdnews24.com/en/detail/cricket/1248843|title=Dhaka Dynamites' Shakib wants to win BPL 2016|website=bdnews24.com}}</ref> Shakib represented [[Uthura Rudras]] in the [[2012 Sri Lanka Premier League]]. Shakib also played for [[Barbados Tridents]] in the [[2013 Caribbean Premier League]]. He played for [[Jamaica Tallawahs]] in both the [[2016 Caribbean Premier League|2016]] and [[2017 Caribbean Premier League|2017 season]] before returning to [[Barbados Tridents|Barbados]] for [[2018 Caribbean Premier League]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thedailystar.net/sports/cricket/shakibs-jamaica-conquer-cpl-1266748|title=Shakib's Jamaica conquer CPL|work=The Daily Star}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thedailystar.net/sports/bangladesh-cricket/shakib-al-hasan-replaced-steve-smith-barbados-tridents-1610815?amp|title=Shakib Al Hasan replaced by Steve Smith|work=The Daily Star}}</ref> He played for [[Adelaide Strikers]] in [[2014\u201315 Big Bash League season|2014]] replacing the injured [[Johan Botha (cricketer)|Johan Botha]], thus becoming the first Bangladeshi to play in the [[Big Bash League]].<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/big-bash-league-2013/content/story/706569.html |title=Shakib joins Adelaide Strikers|work=ESPNcricinfo |date=3 January 2014 |accessdate=3 January 2014}}</ref> For [[2015\u201316 Big Bash League|2015 season]] he was picked up by [[Melbourne Renegades]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thedailystar.net/shakib-to-play-for-melbourne-renegades-56888|title=Shakib to play for Melbourne Renegades}}</ref> For [[2016 Pakistan Super League]] he was picked up by [[Karachi Kings]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.banglanews24.com/sports/article/48146/Shakib-to-play-with-Karachi-Kings|title=Shakib to play with Karachi|website=banglanews24.com}}</ref> and in [[2017 Pakistan Super League|2017 season]] and  he played for [[Peshawar Zalmi]]<ref name=zalmi>{{cite web|url=https://www.dhakatribune.com/sport/cricket/2017/10/07/peshawar-retain-shakib-release-tamim-quetta-keep-mahmudullah|title=Peshawar retain Shakib, release Tamim as Quetta keep Mahmudullah|work=Dhaka Tribune}}</ref> He was supposed to play for the [[2018 Pakistan Super League|2018 season]] also but was injured at that time<ref name=zalmi /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thedailystar.net/sports/bangladesh-cricket/shakib-out-psl-1538398|title=Shakib Out of PSL|work=The Daily Star}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2019, he was selected to play for the Brampton Wolves franchise team in the [[2019 Global T20 Canada]] tournament.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.canadacricket.com/?p=12755 |title=Global T20 draft streamed live |work=Canada Cricket Online |accessdate=20 June 2019}}</ref> Shakib again played for Barbados in the [[2019 Caribbean Premier League|2019]] season.<ref>{{cite news\n| author =\n| title =Litton Das and Shakib Al Hasan fly to Caribbean to join in CPL\n| quote =\n| newspaper =bdcrictime.com\n| date =\n| pages =\n| url =https://www.bdcrictime.com/litton-das-and-shakib-al-hasan-fly-to-caribbean-to-join-in-cpl/amp/\n| accessdate =  \n}}</ref> He was released by the Sunrisers Hyderabad ahead of the [[List of 2020 Indian Premier League personnel changes|2020 IPL auction]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/28087425/where-do-eight-franchises-stand-2020-auction |title=Where do the eight franchises stand before the 2020 auction? |work=ESPN Cricinfo |accessdate=15 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\n===Debut years===\nShakib made his [[One Day International]] (ODI) debut against [[Zimbabwe cricket team|Zimbabwe]] on 6 August 2006, where he scored 30 runs and bowled out [[Elton Chigumbura]] to get his first ODI wicket.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/249207.html|work=ESPNcricinfo|title=Scorecard: Bangladesh tour of Zimbabwe, 5th ODI: Zimbabwe v Bangladesh at Harare, 6 August 2006}}</ref> He made his Test debut the following 6 May against [[India national cricket team|India]]. From January 2009 to April 2011 and again from March 2012, Shakib was ranked first amongst ODI all-rounders by the [[International Cricket Council|ICC]]. In December 2011, he became the world's top-ranked Test all-rounder. In December 2014 Shakib became the world's top ranked Twenty 20 all-rounder. He is currently the only all-rounder to be ranked in the top 3 of [[ICC Player Rankings]] across every format of international cricket.<ref name=\"Reliance ICC\">{{cite web | url=http://www.relianceiccrankings.com/| title=Reliance ICC Rankings | publisher=Reliance ICC | accessdate=25 October 2013}}</ref> In 2008, Shakib took at that time the best bowling figures by a Bangladesh player in Tests, 7&nbsp;wickets for 36&nbsp;runs, against [[New Zealand national cricket team|New Zealand]]. To date he is [[Bangladesh]]'s highest wicket taker in Test Matches.\n\nShakib was appointed Bangladesh's [[Captain (cricket)|vice-captain]] in June 2009. During Bangladesh's tour of the West Indies the following month, the captain [[Mashrafe Mortaza]] was injured and Shakib took over the captaincy. He was 22&nbsp;years old at the time. Initially a temporary position, Shakib's success against the [[West Indies]], securing his side's first overseas series win, ensured his retention of captaincy even after Mort recovered. Shakib was named ''[[The Wisden Cricketer]]'s'' \"Test Player of the Year\" in November 2009. In July 2010, he stepped down from the ODI captaincy to concentrate on his personal performance. Mortaza took over until he became injured again and Shakib was asked to resume leadership. This lasted until he was relieved of captaincy in September 2011 due to a poor World Cup campaign.\n\nIn 2015 after batting in the first match at [[2015 Cricket World Cup]], Hasan had a total of 4,040 runs in ODI matches and became the first Bangladeshi cricketer to score 4,000 runs in ODIs.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://bdnews24.com/cricket/2015/02/18/shakib-al-hasan-first-bangladesh-player-to-score-4000-odi-runs | title=Shakib Al Hasan first Bangladesh player to score 4,000 ODI runs | work=[[Bdnews24.com]] | date=18 February 2015 | accessdate=18 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Breakthrough (2006\u20132008)===\nShakib was included in Bangladesh's senior squad to tour Zimbabwe in February 2006. Along with [[Farhad Reza]] and [[Mushfiqur Rahim]], Shakib was one of the three uncapped players to be included in the squad.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/zimvbdesh/content/story/253971.html |title=Whatmore: 'Bangladesh are favourites'|work=ESPNcricinfo |date=20 July 2006 |accessdate=7 November 2009}}</ref> Shakib and Reza were described as \"very good cricketers in all departments of the game\", and Faruq Ahmed&nbsp;\u2013 the chief selector&nbsp;\u2013 said that Bangladesh had \"high hopes from them and it's time for them to perform at the international level\".<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/kenyavbdesh/content/story/252258.html |title=Bangladesh name young allrounders |work=ESPNcricinfo |date=3 July 2006 |accessdate=7 November 2009}}</ref> Shakib made his ODI debut on the tour on 6 August; his maiden wicket was that of all-rounder [[Elton Chigumbura]], and he finished with bowling figures of 1/39. He also scored 30&nbsp;not&nbsp;out while [[Shahriar Nafees]] scored his maiden ODI century to help Bangladesh win by eight&nbsp;wickets. It was the final match in the series, which Zimbabwe won 3\u20132.<ref>{{citation |url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/98/98929.html |title=o2398 a17537: Zimbabwe v Bangladesh, Bangladesh in Kenya and Zimbabwe 2006 (5th ODI) |work=CricketArchive|url-access=subscription|accessdate=9 November 2010}}</ref> In September 2006, Shakib was one of three players to be granted a rookie contract with the [[Bangladesh Cricket Board]] (BCB), along with Farhad Reza and [[Mehrab Hossain, Jr.|Mehrab Hossain Jr]]. This increased the number of players with central contracts and under the control of the BCB from 20 to 23.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh/content/story/260387.html |title=Mahmud named Bangladesh team manager|work=ESPNcricinfo |date=23 September 2006 |accessdate=7 November 2009}}</ref>\n\nThe [[West Indies]] hosted the [[2007 Cricket World Cup]] in March and April; Shakib was included in the 15-man squad led by [[Habibul Bashar]].<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh/content/story/280197.html |title=Mashud left out of Bangladesh squad |work=ESPNcricinfo|date=13 February 2007 |accessdate=9 November 2010}}</ref> Bangladesh made it to the second stage of the competition and finished seventh.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wc2007/engine/series/125929.html?view=pointstable |title=ICC World Cup 2006/07 / Points table |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=9 November 2010}}</ref> Along the way the team caused an upset by beating [[India national cricket team|India]] to help knock them out of the tournament. With [[Tamim Iqbal]] in just his fifth ODI and Mushfiqur Rahim, Shakib was one of three Bangladesh batsmen in the match to score a half century to help the team reach its target of 192 to win.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wc2007/content/story/285701.html |title=Brilliant Bangladesh stun India |first=Siddhartha |last=Vaidyanathan |work=ESPNcricinfo |date=17 March 2007 |accessdate=9 November 2010}}</ref> Later in the tournament, Shakib scored another half-century although Bangladesh were defeated by England on that very occasion.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wc2007/content/story/290076.html |title=Saqibul stands tall but can't stop the fall |first=Dileep |last=Premachandran |work=ESPNcricinfo |date=11 April 2008 |accessdate=9 November 2010}}</ref> With 202&nbsp;runs from nine&nbsp;matches at an average of 28.85<ref>{{cite web |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/wc2007/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=2403;type=tournament |title=ICC World Cup, 2006/07 / Records / Most wickets |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=9 November 2010}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Shakib fielding, 23 January, 2009, Dhaka SBNS.jpg|thumb|right|220px|Shakib in the 3rd and the final ODI against Zimbabwe in January 2009 in [[Sher-e-Bangla National Stadium]], which Bangladesh won with Shakib's individual unbeaten 33 runs off 60 balls<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bdeshvzim/engine/match/378759.html|title=3rd ODI: Bangladesh v Zimbabwe at Dhaka, Jan 23, 2009 \u2013 Cricket Scorecard \u2013 ESPN Cricinfo|publisher=|accessdate=27 October 2016}}</ref>]]\nLater that year, in May, India [[Indian cricket team in Bangladesh in 2007|toured Bangladesh]] for two Tests and three ODIs. On 18 May, Shakib made his Test debut against India. He batted once, scoring 27&nbsp;runs, and bowled 13&nbsp;overs without taking a wicket as the match ended in a draw.<ref>{{citation |url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/116/116634.html |title=f50076 t1832: Bangladesh v India India in Bangladesh 2007 (1st Test) |work=CricketArchive|url-access=subscription|accessdate=9 November 2010}}</ref> India won the Test series 1\u20130 and the ODI series 3\u20130. After the tour, [[Dav Whatmore]] resigned from his position as Bangladesh coach,<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/story/291550.html |title=Whatmore quits as Bangladesh coach|work=ESPNcricinfo |date=20 April 2007 |accessdate=9 November 2010}}</ref> and batsman [[Mohammad Ashraful]] replaced Habibul Bashar as captain.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh/content/story/296705.html |title=Ashraful named Bangladesh captain |work=ESPNcricinfo|date=2 June 2007 |accessdate=9 November 2010}}</ref> In September 2007, South Africa hosted the [[2007 ICC World Twenty20|ICC World Twenty20]]. Victory against West Indies in the first round was enough to ensure Bangladesh's progression to the second round, although it was the only one of their five matches they won. In the match against West Indies, Shakib took 4/34; it was the first time a Bangladesh player had taken more than three wickets in an International Twenty20 match (T20I).<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/twenty20wc/content/story/310815.html |title=Ashraful slams his way to fastest fifty in Bangladesh win |work=ESPNcricinfo |first1=HR |last1=Gopalakrishna |first2=Mathew |last2=Varghese |date=13 September 2007 |accessdate=9 November 2010}}</ref> Shakib was part of another piece of T20I history when in a match against Australia in the tournament he became one of three victims of the first T20I hat-trick. [[Brett Lee]] took Shakib's wicket, followed by those of Mortaza's and [[Alok Kapali]] to help Australia to a nine-wicket win.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/twenty20wc/content/story/311208.html |title=Hayden and Lee power Australian win |first=Sriram |last=Veera |work=ESPNcricinfo |date=16 September 2007 |accessdate=26 December 2010}}</ref> In October that year, it was announced that [[Jamie Siddons]]&nbsp;\u2013 Australia's assistant coach&nbsp;\u2013 would take over the role of Bangladesh coach;<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh/content/story/317465.html |title=Siddons accepts Bangladesh job |work=ESPNcricinfo|date=28 October 2007 |accessdate=9 November 2010}}</ref> Siddons asserted that the previous set-up had focused on short-term goals and that he was planning to improve Bangladesh over the long term and keep together a core squad of talented players to gain experience at international level.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/nzvbdesh/content/story/331087.html |title='My vision is long-term' \u2013 Siddons |work=ESPNcricinfo|date=15 January 2008 |accessdate=9 November 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Bangladeshi cricket team in New Zealand in 2007\u201308|December 2007 and January 2008]], Bangladesh toured New Zealand for two Tests and three ODIs. Although he did not play the first Test, Shakib was selected over [[Enamul Haque Jr]] for the second due to his better batting ability.<ref name=\"NZ January 2008\">{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/nzvbdesh/content/story/330795.html |title=New Zealand coast to innings victory |last=Binoy |first=George |work=ESPNcricinfo |date=14 January 2008 |accessdate=9 November 2010}}</ref> It was Shakib's fourth Test, and until that point he had gone wicketless. His first wicket was that of New Zealand's [[Craig Cumming]].<ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/player/56143.html?class=1;template=results;type=bowling;view=match |title=Statistics / Statsguru / Shakib Al Hasan / Test matches |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=9 November 2010}}</ref><ref>{{citation |url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/124/124203.html |title=f50566 t1861: New Zealand v Bangladesh, Bangladesh in New Zealand 2007/08 (2nd Test) |work=CricketArchive|url-access=subscription|accessdate=9 November 2010}}</ref> New Zealand won by an innings and 137&nbsp;runs and took the series 2\u20130.<ref name=\"NZ January 2008\"/> New Zealand also completed a clean sweep in the ODIs which preceded the Tests, winning 3\u20130.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/nzvbdesh/content/story/328292.html |title=Vettori and McCullum thrash Bangladesh |work=ESPNcricinfo |first=Jamie |last=Alter |date=30 December 2007 |accessdate=9 November 2010}}</ref> Shakib played in all three ODIs scoring 31&nbsp;runs at an average of 10.33,<ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/batting/most_runs_career.html?id=3308;type=series |title=Records / Bangladesh in New Zealand ODI Series, 2007/08 / Most runs |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=9 November 2010}}</ref> and taking 3&nbsp;wickets at an average of 42.33.<ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=3308;type=series |title=Records / Bangladesh in New Zealand ODI Series, 2007/08 / Most wickets |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=9 November 2010}}</ref> Over [[South African cricket team in Bangladesh in 2007\u201308|February and March 2008 South Africa toured Bangladesh]], playing two Tests and three ODIs. South Africa won both Tests.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bdeshvrsa/engine/match/323948.html |title=South Africa in Bangladesh Test Series \u2013 2nd Test Bangladesh v South Africa: Test no. 1865 |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=9 November 2010}}</ref> Shakib played in both Bangladesh's defeats, taking just one wicket while conceding 122&nbsp;runs,<ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=3677;type=series |title=Records / South Africa in Bangladesh Test Series, 2007/08 / Most wickets |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=9 November 2010}}</ref> and scoring 75&nbsp;runs.<ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/batting/most_runs_career.html?id=3677;type=series |title=Records / South Africa in Bangladesh Test Series, 2007/08 / Most runs |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=9 November 2010}}</ref> South Africa won the subsequent ODI series 3\u20130.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bdeshvrsa/content/story/342381.html |title=South Africa No.1 after clean sweep |first=Kanishkaa |last=Balachandran |work=ESPNcricinfo |date=14 March 2008 |accessdate=9 November 2010}}</ref> Shakib passed 1,000 ODI runs in the series; he passed the landmark in his 39th ODI with a batting average of 35.37.<ref name=\"ODI cumulative batting average\">{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/player/56143.html?class=2;template=results;type=batting;view=cumulative |title=Statistics / Statsguru / Shakib Al Hasan / ODI matches cumulative batting average |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=9 November 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Bangladesh's leading all-rounder (2008\u20132019)===\nBefore [[New Zealand cricket team in Bangladesh in 2008\u201309|New Zealand's tour of Bangladesh in October 2008]], Shakib was considered more of a batsman than a bowler, despite being an all-rounder. Though he usually batted down the order at number seven in Tests, he had mostly batted in the top five in ODIs. In a departure from Shakib's usual role Jamie Siddons, the coach, stated that Shakib would play the Test series against New Zealand as a specialist bowler. The move immediately paid off, and he took 7/37 in New Zealand's first innings in the opening Test. They were the best bowling figures by a Bangladesh player in Tests.<ref name=\"From Magura to No. 1\"/> Bangladesh lost the series 2\u20130, but Shakib finished as Bangladesh's leading wicket-taker in the series with 10&nbsp;wickets at 17.80.<ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=4494;type=series |title=Records / New Zealand in Bangladesh Test Series, 2008/09 / Most wickets |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=9 November 2010}}</ref> His spell was nominated to be the Best Test Bowling Performance of 2008 by ESPNCricinfo.<ref>http://www.espncricinfo.com/awards2008/content/story/385017.html</ref>\nBangladesh won the opening match of the ODI series against New Zealand&nbsp;\u2013 securing their first ever ODI win over them<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bdeshvnz/content/story/373126.html |title=Bangladesh maul sorry New Zealand|work=ESPNcricinfo |date=9 October 2008 |accessdate=11 November 2010}}</ref>&nbsp;\u2013 although they eventually lost the series 2\u20131.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bdeshvnz/engine/series/361750.html |title=New Zealand tour of Bangladesh 2008/09 / Results |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=11 November 2010}}</ref> Shakib finished with five&nbsp;wickets from three matches, making him Bangladesh's second-highest wicket-taker for the series behind Mashrafe Mortaza (7);<ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=4493;type=series |title=Records / New Zealand in Bangladesh ODI Series, 2008/09 / Most wickets |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=11 November 2010}}</ref> however Shakib scored just 16&nbsp;runs in the series.<ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/batting/most_runs_career.html?id=4493;type=series |title=Records / New Zealand in Bangladesh ODI Series, 2008/09 / Most runs |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=11 November 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe following month, Bangladesh toured [[Bangladeshi cricket team in South Africa in 2008\u201309|South Africa]] for two Tests, three ODIs, and a T20I. While Bangladesh lost all their matches against South Africa except for an abandoned ODI,<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/rsavbdesh/engine/series/350336.html |title=Bangladesh tour of South Africa 2008/09 / Results |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=11 November 2010}}</ref> Shakib continued to build on the good bowling form he had found against New Zealand. On the first day of the opening Test, Shakib went wicketless; on the advice of Mohammad Salauddin, Bangladesh's assistant coach, he gave the ball [[Flight (cricket)|flight]] on the second day and went on to take five wickets. He took another five-wicket haul in the second Test, again as Bangladesh lost to South Africa.<ref name=\"From Magura to No. 1\"/> Along with South Africa's [[Makhaya Ntini]], Shakib was the series' leading wicket-taker with 11 at an average of 20.81.<ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=4291;type=series |title=Records / Bangladesh in South Africa Test Series, 2008/09 / Most wickets |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=11 November 2010}}</ref> Shakib's performance against South Africa in a losing cause prompted former Australian [[Leg spin|leg spin bowler]] [[Kerry O'Keeffe]] to describe him as the \"world's best finger spinner at the moment\".<ref name=\"From Magura to No. 1\"/> Sri Lanka [[Sri Lankan cricket team in Bangladesh in 2008\u201309|toured Bangladesh in December 2008 and January 2009]] for two Tests and a Tri-nation tournament including Zimbabwe. Sri Lanka won both Tests and the tournament final,<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bdeshvsl/engine/series/378736.html |title=Sri Lanka tour of Bangladesh 2008/09 / Results |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=11 November 2010}}</ref> although Shakib turned in a man of the match performance, scoring 92&nbsp;not&nbsp;out, in the second ODI against Sri Lanka helped Bangladesh to their only victory against them on the tour.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/tri-bdesh/content/story/386385.html |title=Shakib powers Bangladesh to final|work=ESPNcricinfo |date=14 January 2009 |accessdate=11 November 2010}}</ref> In the first match of the Test series, Shakib took another five-wicket haul as his team again was defeated.<ref name=\"From Magura to No. 1\"/>\n\nOn 22 January 2009 Shakib was ranked first amongst ODI all-rounders by the ICC.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci-icc/content/story/387457.html |title=Shakib takes top spot among ODI allrounders |work=ESPNcricinfo|date=22 January 2010 |accessdate=9 November 2010}}</ref> Although he was part of the auction of players held the following month for the [[2009 Indian Premier League]], Shakib was not chosen by any of the eight teams and no bids were made for him. This was despite being rated as the world's highest ranked ODI all-rounder at the time. His teammate Mashrafe Mortaza, who was bought in the auction, said \"I would have been a lot happier if Shakib had got a team because he truly deserved it for his sensational form with the bat and ball\".<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ipl2009/content/story/389524.html |title=Proud Mortaza credits hard work|date=6 February 2009 |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=7 February 2009}}</ref>\n\n===Captaincy and Vice-captaincy (2009\u20132011)===\n[[File:Shakib al hasan 3.jpg|thumb|left|Shakib was appointed Bangladesh's vice-captain in June 2009.]]\nAt the beginning of 2009, there was speculation over Mohammad Ashraful's position as captain after a succession of defeats for Bangladesh and continuous poor form for Ashraful. Shakib was considered a possible successor by the [[Bangladesh Cricket Board]] (BCB). However, the BCB was cautious of over-burdening the all-rounder and decided against the move. Other candidates were discounted, and Ashraful remained as captain.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh/content/story/389739.html |title=Ashraful to continue as Bangladesh captain|work=ESPNcricinfo |date=8 February 2009 |accessdate=6 March 2009}}</ref> Later in 2009, Ashraful's captaincy was again under scrutiny after Bangladesh exited the [[2009 ICC World Twenty20]] in the first round following losses to Ireland and India. When [[Mashrafe Mortaza]] replaced Mohammad Ashraful in June 2009, Shakib was appointed vice-captain, filling the position vacated by Mortaza.<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wivbdesh2009/content/current/story/410237.html|title=Mashrafe named Bangladesh captain|date=23 June 2009|work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=8 July 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn July\u2013August 2009, [[Bangladeshi cricket team in West Indies in 2009|Bangladesh toured the West Indies]]. When Mortaza injured his knee in the first Test, he was unable to take to the field on the final day and Shakib took over as captain. He and [[Mahmudullah]] led Bangladesh's bowling attack, sharing 13&nbsp;wickets in the match and securing a historic win for Bangladesh.\nIt was Bangladesh's first against the West [[Indies]], their first overseas Test victory, and only their second Test win.<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wivbdesh2009/content/story/414146.html|title=Shakib, Mahmudullah make up for Mortaza's absence|date=13 July 2009|work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=18 July 2009}}</ref><ref>{{citation|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/247/247186.html|title=f51408 t1923 West Indies v Bangladesh: Bangladesh in West Indies 2009 (1st Test)|work=CricketArchive|url-access=subscription|accessdate=18 July 2009}}</ref> The West Indies side was very inexperienced due to the fallout of a dispute between the [[West Indies Cricket Board]] and the West Indies Players' Association over pay. The first XI had made themselves unavailable for selection and a new squad had to be chosen. Seven West Indies players made their Test debut in the match and the side was captained by [[Floyd Reifer]] who had played the last of his four Tests ten years earlier.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wivbdesh2009/content/story/413237.html |title=West Indies name replacement squad |work=ESPNcricinfo|date=8 July 2009 |accessdate=18 July 2009}}</ref> Shakib was fined 10% of his match fee for excessive appealing; bowler [[Shahadat Hossain]] was also fined and batsman [[Imrul Kayes]] was reprimanded for the same reason.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wivbdesh2009/content/story/414425.html |title=Shakib and Shahadat fined for excessive appealing |work=ESPNcricinfo |date=14 July 2009 |accessdate=19 June 2009}}</ref>\n\n====West Indies====\nIn Mortaza's absence through injury, Shakib led Bangladesh for the remainder of the tour.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wivbdesh2009/content/current/story/414664.html |title=History beckons for Bangladesh |work=ESPNcricinfo |first=Jamie|last=Alter |date=16 July 2009 |accessdate=18 July 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"step aside\">{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wivbdesh2009/content/story/416880.html |title=Mortaza happy to step aside for Shakib |work=ESPNcricinfo|date=30 July 2009 |accessdate=1 August 2009}}.</ref> Aged 22&nbsp;years and 115&nbsp;days at the start of the second Test, Shakib became Bangladesh's youngest captain and fifth youngest in the history of Test cricket.<ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/records/283416.html |title=Records / Test matches / Individual records (captains, players, umpires) / Youngest captains |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=23 November 2010}}</ref> Under Shakib's leadership Bangladesh went on to win the second Test, and in the process secured their first overseas series win.<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wivbdesh2009/content/current/story/415358.html |title=Raqibul and Shakib inspire first overseas series win |last=Veera |first=Sriram |work=ESPNcricinfo |date=20 July 2009 |accessdate=21 July 2009}}</ref> Individually Shakib performed well, earning both the player-of-the-match and player-of-the-series awards, scoring 16 and 96&nbsp;not&nbsp;out with the bat and taking 3/59 and 5/70 with the ball.<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wivbdesh2009/engine/current/match/401072.html|title=Scorecard: West Indies v Bangladesh, 2nd Test, 17\u201320 July 2009|work=ESPNcricinfo|accessdate=21 July 2009}}</ref> He scored 159&nbsp;runs in the series at an average of 53.00 and was Bangladesh's second highest run-scorer for the series;<ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/batting/most_runs_career.html?id=5037;type=series |title=Records / Bangladesh in West Indies Test Series, 2009 /  Most runs |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=1 August 2009}}</ref> his haul of 13&nbsp;wickets at an average of 18.76 from both matches meant Shakib was the equal highest wicket-taker for the series along with West Indies fast bowler [[Kemar Roach]].<ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=5037;type=series |title=Records / Bangladesh in West Indies Test Series, 2009 /  Most wickets |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=1 August 2009}}</ref> After winning the Test series 2\u20130, Bangladesh proceeded to whitewash the ODI series, winning 3\u20130. The West Indies' dispute remained unsolved for the whole of Bangladesh's tour and the West Indies continued to field an inexperienced side.<ref name=\"step aside\"/> Shakib collected two half centuries in the ODI series, averaging 45.00, and was the third highest run-scorer in the series;<ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/batting/most_runs_career.html?id=5036;type=series |title=Records / Bangladesh in West Indies ODI Series, 2009 /  Most runs |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=1 August 2009}}</ref> he also took 2&nbsp;wickets at an average of 48.00.<ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=5036;type=series |title=Records / Bangladesh in West Indies ODI Series, 2009 /  Most wickets |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=1 August 2009}}</ref> For his performance in the ODIs, Shakib was named the man of the series.<ref>{{citation |url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Seasons/WI/2009_WI_Bangladesh_in_West_Indies_2009.html |title=Bangladesh in West Indies 2009 |work=CricketArchive |url-access=subscription |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121026120022/http://www.cricketarchive.com/Archive/Seasons/WI/2009_WI_Bangladesh_in_West_Indies_2009.html |archive-date=26 October 2012 |accessdate=1 August 2009}}</ref>\n\n====Zimbabwe====\nShakib was appointed captain for Bangladesh's [[Bangladeshi cricket team in Zimbabwe in 2009|tour of Zimbabwe in August 2009]] as Mortaza was still injured.<ref name=\"step aside\"/> In the second ODI of the five match series in Zimbabwe in August 2009, Shakib scored 104 off only 64 balls before being run-out&nbsp;\u2013 his third ODI century&nbsp;\u2013 to help his team to their highest score in ODIs and lead Bangladesh to a 2\u20130 lead in the series.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/zimvbdesh2009/content/story/418910.html |title=Shakib scripts convincing win |author=Sriram Veera |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=11 August 2009}}</ref> He finished the series with 170&nbsp;runs from five&nbsp;matches at an average of 42.50&nbsp;\u2013 fifth highest run-scorer<ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/batting/most_runs_career.html?id=5129;type=series |title=Records / Bangladesh in Zimbabwe ODI Series, 2009 / Most runs |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=3 September 2009}}</ref>&nbsp;\u2013 and 6&nbsp;wickets an average of 39.66, fourth highest wicket-taker in the series.<ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=5129;type=series |title=Records / Bangladesh in Zimbabwe ODI Series, 2009 / Most wickets |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=3 September 2009}}</ref> Following his team's 4\u20131 victory in the ODI series against Zimbabwe, Shakib travelled to Australia to undergo medical treatment for acute groin pain. He had been experiencing pain since the end of the West Indies tour, but he had decided to play through the pain and lead Bangladesh in Zimbabwe.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh/content/story/422343.html |title=Shakib to undergo treatment in Australia|work=ESPNcricinfo |date=27 August 2009 |accessdate=3 September 2009}}</ref> Although he did not win, Shakib was nominated Cricketer of the Year and Test Player of the Year in the 2009 [[ICC Awards]]; he was the only Bangladesh player to be nominated in either category that year.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci-icc/content/current/story/422973.html |title=Dhoni, Dilshan pick up maximum nominations|work=ESPNcricinfo |date=2 September 2009 |accessdate=3 September 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite media release|url=http://icc-cricket.yahoo.net/events_and_awards/lg_icc_awards/newsdetails.php?newsId=1310_1254417540 |title=Mitchell Johnson takes top honours at glittering ICC Awards night |date=2 October 2009 |publisher=International Cricket Council |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110807055221/http://icc-cricket.yahoo.net/events_and_awards/lg_icc_awards/newsdetails.php?newsId=1310_1254417540 |archive-date=7 August 2011 |accessdate=9 November 2010}}</ref>\n\nShakib's success meant that it was not a given that Mortaza would replace him as captain once fit,<ref name=\"step aside\"/> but it was announced in September 2009 that Mortaza would return as captain for Bangladesh's home [[Zimbabwe cricket team in Bangladesh in 2009|ODI series against Zimbabwe the following month]] and Shakib would return to the role of vice-captain.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bdeshvzim09/content/current/story/424272.html |title=Mortaza appointed captain for Zimbabwe series |work=ESPNcricinfo|date=9 September 2009 |accessdate=9 September 2009}}</ref> However, Mortaza failed to return from arthroscopic surgery on both knees in time for the series, and Shakib was again named captain.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bdeshvzim09/content/story/430712.html |title=Injured Mortaza out of Zimbabwe ODIs |work=ESPNcricinfo|date=22 October 2009 |accessdate=1 November 2009}}</ref> After losing the opening match&nbsp;\u2013 in which Shakib criticised the performance of Bangladesh's batsmen including himself<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bdeshvzim09/content/story/431572.html |title=We can still win this 4\u20131&nbsp;\u2013 Shakib |work=ESPNcricinfo|date=27 October 2009 |accessdate=1 November 2009}}</ref>&nbsp;\u2013 Bangladesh went on to win the series 4\u20131.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bdeshvzim09/engine/series/422622.html |title=Zimbabwe tour of Bangladesh 2009/10 / Results |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=11 November 2010}}</ref> In the second match of the series, Shakib passed 2,000&nbsp;runs in ODIs.<ref name=\"ODI cumulative batting average\"/> In November 2009, Shakib was named ''[[The Wisden Cricketer]]'s'' \"Test Player of the Year\".<ref name=\"Test player of the year\">{{citation |url=http://wisdencricketer.com/item.php?parent_id=3&child_id=0&item_id=599 |title=Remember The Name |work=The Wisden Cricketer online |author=Rabeed Imam |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091012075533/http://wisdencricketer.com/item.php?parent_id=3&child_id=0&item_id=599 |archive-date=12 October 2009 |accessdate=11 October 2009}}</ref>\n\n====England and the Asia Cup====\n[[File:Shakib al hasan 4.jpg|thumb|upright|Shakib in the field against England during the second ODI, shortly after relinquishing the captaincy]]\nOver February and March 2010 [[English cricket team in Bangladesh in 2009\u201310|England toured Bangladesh]] for two Tests and three ODIs. England won all of their matches against Bangladesh.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bdeshveng2010/engine/series/426373.html |title=England tour of Bangladesh 2009/10 / Results |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=11 November 2010}}</ref> Shakib was Bangladesh's leading wicket-taker in both the Test and ODI series (9 wickets in Tests and 5 in ODIs).<ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=5510;type=series |title=Records / England in Bangladesh Test Series, 2009/10 / Most wickets |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=11 November 2010}}</ref><ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=5509;type=series |title=Records / England in Bangladesh ODI Series, 2009/10 / Most wickets |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=11 November 2010}}</ref> In the second Test, Shakib scored 49 and 96, and took 4/124 from 66&nbsp;overs. Both Tests went to the final day and Shakib expressed the opinion that the experience had exhausted his side.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bdeshveng2010/content/story/453368.html |title=Bangladesh ran out of steam&nbsp;\u2013 Shakib |last=Miller |first=Andrew |work=ESPNcricinfo |date=24 March 2010 |accessdate=11 November 2010}}</ref> The match was also a source of controversy after incorrect umpiring decisions on the third day went against Bangladesh, prompting Shakib to blame the lack of a [[Umpire Decision Review System|referral system]] for some of the team's misfortune.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bdeshveng2010/content/story/453049.html |title=Shakib blames board for lack of review system |last=Miller |first=Andrew |work=ESPNcricinfo |date=22 March 2010 |accessdate=11 November 2010}}</ref> In turn, Bangladesh [[Bangladeshi cricket team in England in 2010|toured England in May and July]] the same year. They again lost the Test series 2\u20130.<ref name=\"England 2010 results\">{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england-v-bangladesh-2010/engine/series/426339.html |title=Bangladesh tour of England, Ireland and Scotland 2010 / Results |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=11 November 2010}}</ref> Shakib finished as his team's leading wicket-taker with eight wickets,<ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/england-v-bangladesh-2010/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=5504;type=series |title=Bangladesh in England Test Series, 2010 / Records / Most wickets |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=11 November 2010}}</ref> although he only scored 52&nbsp;runs.<ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/england-v-bangladesh-2010/engine/records/batting/most_runs_career.html?id=5504;type=series |title=Bangladesh in England Test Series, 2010 / Records / Most runs |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=11 November 2010}}</ref> Before the ODI series, Bangladesh left England for Sri Lanka, which was hosting the [[2010 Asia Cup]] in June. Bangladesh lost all three of their matches.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/asia2010/engine/series/424694.html |title=Asia Cup 2010 / Results |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=11 November 2010}}</ref> With five wickets, Shakib was Bangladesh's lead wicket-taker with [[Shafiul Islam]] (5 each).<ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/asia2010/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=5477;type=tournament |title=Asia Cup, 2010 / Records / Most wickets |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=11 November 2010}}</ref>\n\nAs he was struggling to cope with the captaincy and his role as an all-rounder, Shakib gave up the captaincy in July 2010 to focus on his own performance. Mashrafe Mortaza returned to take charge in ODIs. Coach Jamie Siddons explained that \"Shakib was the main person behind the decision, he decided it was a bit much for him. His form was down with the bat and he needed a rest.\"<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england-v-bangladesh-2010/content/current/story/466199.html |title=Shakib is an ideal captain&nbsp;\u2013 Siddons |work=ESPNcricinfo |last=McGlashan |first=Andrew |date=5 July 2010 |accessdate=9 November 2010}}</ref> Bangladesh returned to England for the ODI half of their tour. Bangladesh lost the series 2\u20131,<ref name=\"England 2010 results\"/> but their victory in the second match was the first time Bangladesh had beaten England in international cricket.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england-v-bangladesh-2010/content/story/466798.html |title=Bangladesh seal historic victory |last=McGlashan |first=Andrew |work=ESPNcricinfo |date=10 July 2010 |accessdate=11 November 2010}}</ref> While in Europe, Bangladesh were scheduled to play two ODIs against Ireland, and one each against Scotland and Netherlands. The match against Scotland was abandoned and Bangladesh lost one match to each of Ireland and the Netherlands.<ref name=\"England 2010 results\"/>\n\nHaving signed a contract in November 2009,<ref name=\"Shakib for Worcestershire\">{{citation |url=http://www.worcesternews.co.uk/sport/wccc/4744603.Worcestershire_in_swoop_for_Shakib_as_overseas_player/ |title=Worcestershire in swoop for Shakib as overseas player |work=Worcester News |publisher=[[Newsquest|Newsquest Media Group]] |last=Reeves |first=Michael |date=18 November 2009 |accessdate=11 November 2010}}</ref> Shakib joined up with [[Worcestershire County Cricket Club]], playing the second division of the [[County Championship]], in July 2010. He was the first Bangladeshi to represent a county side.<ref name=\"Shakib for Worcestershire\"/> While playing for Worcestershire he took his best first-class bowling figures of 7/32 against [[Middlesex County Cricket Club|Middlesex]]. In eight first-class matches he scored 358&nbsp;runs at 25.57 (with one score over 50)<ref>{{citation |url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/73/73152/f_Batting_by_Team.html |title=First-class batting and fielding for each team by Shakib Al Hasan |work=CricketArchive|url-access=subscription|accessdate=11 November 2010}}</ref> and took 35&nbsp;wickets at 22.37,<ref>{{citation |url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/73/73152/f_Bowling_by_Team.html |title=First-class bowling for each team by Shakib Al Hasan |work=CricketArchive|url-access=subscription|accessdate=11 November 2010}}</ref> as Worcestershire secured promotion to the first division at the end of the season.<ref>{{citation |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/counties/9006380.stm |title=Worcestershire win promotion with victory over Sussex |publisher=[[BBC Sport]] |date=16 September 2010 |accessdate=11 November 2010}}</ref> Shakib also played five one-day matches for Worcestershie, scoring 187 at an average of 37.40 (including two half-centuries)<ref>{{citation |url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/73/73152/a_Batting_by_Team.html |title=ListA batting and fielding for each team by Shakib Al Hasan |work=CricketArchive|url-access=subscription|accessdate=11 November 2010}}</ref> and taking 9&nbsp;wickets at 17.77.<ref>{{citation |url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/73/73152/a_Bowling_by_Team.html |title=ListA bowling for each team by Shakib Al Hasan |work=CricketArchive|url-access=subscription|accessdate=11 November 2010}}</ref>\n\nFor his performances in 2009, he was named in the World Test XI by the ICC<ref>http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci-icc/content/story/427665.html</ref>\n\n====New Zealand and Zimbabwe====\nIn October 2010, [[New Zealand cricket team in Bangladesh in 2010\u201311|New Zealand went to Bangladesh]] for five ODIs. In the first match of the series Mortaza injured his ankle and was forced to leave the field; Shakib took over, and under his leadership Bangladesh secured a nine-run victory, during which Shakib took four wickets and scored 58. Once it emerged that Mortaza would be unable to play in the rest of the series, Shakib was made captain for the remaining matches.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh-v-new-zealand-2010/content/story/480285.html |title=Mortaza ruled out due to injury |work=ESPNcricinfo|date=6 October 2010 |accessdate=11 November 2010}}</ref> In the fourth match, Shakib scored a century and took three wickets to help his team win by nine runs.<ref name=\"NZ 4th ODI 2010\">{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh-v-new-zealand-2010/content/story/481617.html |title=All-round Shakib inspires Bangladesh to historic win |work=ESPNcricinfo |first=Andrew |last=Fernando |date=14 October 2010 |accessdate=11 November 2010}}</ref> Bangladesh went on to win the series 4\u20130,<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh-v-new-zealand-2010/content/story/482305.html |title=Bangladesh reap rewards of hard work |first=Mohammad |last=Isam |work=ESPNcricinfo |date=18 October 2010 |accessdate=11 November 2010}}</ref> their first series victory against a full strength ICC Full Member nation.<ref name=\"NZ 4th ODI 2010\"/> Shakib finished the series as the player with most runs and wickets on either side: 213&nbsp;runs<ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/batting/most_runs_career.html?id=6168;type=series |title=Records / New Zealand in Bangladesh ODI Series, 2010/11 / Most runs |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=11 November 2010}}</ref> and 11&nbsp;wickets.<ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=6168;type=series |title=Records / New Zealand in Bangladesh ODI Series, 2010/11 / Most wickets |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=11 November 2010}}</ref>\n\nAlthough Mortaza returned from injury in time for Zimbabwe's tour of Bangladesh in December, Shakib was retained as captain for the five-match ODI series.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh-v-zimbabwe-2010/content/current/story/489535.html |title=Shakib retained as captain for Zimbabwe series |work=ESPNcricinfo|date=28 November 2010 |accessdate=29 November 2010}}</ref> Following his side's defeat in the opening ODI, Shakib stated that he \"was not prepared to take the job and I am also not satisfied with my role as a captain\".<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh-v-zimbabwe-2010/content/story/490108.html |title='I was not prepared for captaincy'&nbsp;\u2013 Shakib Al Hasan|work=ESPNcricinfo |date=2 December 2010 |accessdate=2 December 2010}}</ref> Bangladesh went on to win the next three complete matches, with one called off due to rain, to beat Zimbabwe 3\u20131.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh-v-zimbabwe-2010/content/current/story/491571.html |title=Shakib praises Bangladesh recovery|work=ESPNcricinfo |date=12 December 2010 |accessdate=12 December 2010}}</ref> Shakib was Bangladesh's second-highest run-scorer and wicket taker for the series with 156&nbsp;runs, including two half centuries, and nine&nbsp;wickets.<ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/batting/most_runs_career.html?id=6321;type=series |title=Records / Zimbabwe in Bangladesh ODI Series, 2010/11 / Most runs |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=12 December 2010}}</ref><ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=6321;type=series |title=Records / Zimbabwe in Bangladesh ODI Series, 2010/11 / Most wickets |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=12 December 2010}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"float: right; margin-left: 1em; width: 40%; font-size: 90%;\" cellspacing=\"5\"\n|-\n!colspan=\"6\"|'''Shakib's record as captain'''\n|-\n!Format \u2193 || Matches || Won || Lost || Drawn/NR\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| Test <ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh/engine/records/individual/list_captains.html?class=1;id=25;type=team|work=ESPNcricinfo|title=List of Bangladesh test captains}}</ref>\n|| 13 || 3 {{efn|Mortaza began the first Test against the West Indies in 2009 as captain, the win is not counted as being part of Shakib's term in charge}} || 10 || 0\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ODI <ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh/engine/records/individual/most_matches_as_captain.html?class=2;id=25;type=team|title=Bangladesh captains' playing record in ODI matches|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> \n|| 50 || 23 || 26 || 1\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| T20I <ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh/engine/records/individual/most_matches_as_captain.html?class=3;id=25;type=team |title=Bangladesh captains' playing record in International Twenty20 matches |work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> \n|| 17 || 4 || 13 ||\n|-\n|colspan=5; align=center|Last updated on: 23 December 2018 \n|}\n\nIn February to March April 2011, Bangladesh co-hosted the [[2011 Cricket World Cup|World Cup]] with India and Sri Lanka. West Indies dismissed Bangladesh for 58&nbsp;runs, the team's lowest score in ODIs and a record low for a Full Member at the World Cup.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/icc_cricket_worldcup2011/content/story/504517.html |title='Team devastated by performance'&nbsp;\u2013 Siddons |work=ESPNcricinfo |first=Sidharth |last=Monga |date=6 March 2011 |accessdate=6 March 2011}}</ref> Shakib's house was stoned by angry fans in the aftermath,<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/icc_cricket_worldcup2011/content/story/504533.html |title=Shakib, Siddons hit back at criticism from former players |work=ESPNcricinfo |first=Sidharth |last=Monga |date=6 March 2011 |accessdate=6 March 2011}}</ref> as was the West Indies team bus as it left the ground.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/icc_cricket_worldcup2011/content/story/504279.html |title=West Indies team bus stoned in Dhaka |first=Sidharth |last=Monga |work=ESPNcricinfo |date=4 March 2011 |accessdate=6 March 2011}}</ref> Bangladesh registered wins against England, Ireland and the Netherlands, but defeats by West Indies, India and South Africa meant they did not progress beyond the first round of the tournament.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/icc_cricket_worldcup2011/content/story/506964.html |title=Abject Bangladesh surrender meekly |first=Abhishek |last=Purohit |work=ESPNcricinfo |date=19 March 2011 |accessdate=20 March 2011}}</ref> With 8&nbsp;wickets at an average of 27.87, Shakib was Bangladesh's lead wicket-taker in the tournament,<ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/icc_cricket_worldcup2011/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=4857;type=tournament |title=ICC Cricket World Cup, 2010/11 / Records / Most wickets |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=20 March 2011}}</ref> and his 142&nbsp;runs from 6&nbsp;innings made him the team's third highest run-scorer.<ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/icc_cricket_worldcup2011/engine/records/batting/most_runs_career.html?id=4857;type=tournament |title=ICC Cricket World Cup, 2010/11 / Records / Most runs |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=20 March 2011}}</ref>\n\n'''After World Cup'''\n\nShortly after the World Cup, [[Australian cricket team in Bangladesh in 2011|Australia toured Bangladesh]] for three ODIs. In the first match of the series, Shakib scored 51 to pass 3,000&nbsp;runs in ODIs.<ref name=\"ODI cumulative batting average\"/> Bangladesh lost the series 3\u20130,<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh-v-australia-2011/content/story/510859.html |title=Hussey hundred sets up Australia's clean-sweep |first=Brydon |last=Coverdale |work=ESPNcricinfo |date=13 April 2011 |accessdate=18 April 2011}}</ref> Shakib scored 69&nbsp;runs in three matches<ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/batting/most_runs_career.html?id=6486;type=series |title=Records / Australia in Bangladesh ODI Series, 2011 / Most runs |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=18 April 2011}}</ref> and took just one wicket whilst conceding 117&nbsp;runs.<ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=6486;type=series |title=Records / Australia in Bangladesh ODI Series, 2011 / Most wickets |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=18 April 2011}}</ref> [[Shane Watson]]'s performances in the series meant he was ranked first amongst ODI all-rounders, claiming the position from Shakib.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci-icc/content/story/511114.html |title=Watson rises to top spot in ICC rankings|work=ESPNcricinfo |date=15 April 2011 |accessdate=18 April 2011}}</ref> For the [[2011 Indian Premier League]], held in April and May, Shakib was contracted by [[Kolkata Knight Riders]] for US$425,000.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/indian-premier-league-2011/content/story/495911.html |title=Ryder, Kartik, Kaif go in re-bidding|work=ESPNcricinfo |date=6 January 2011 |accessdate=8 January 2011}}</ref> He made his debut in the tournament on 15 April in a match against [[Rajasthan Royals]]. He claimed two wickets in the match, first that of [[Amit Paunikar]] and then [[Shane Watson]], but did not get the chance to bat as his team only lost a wicket, winning by 9 wickets.<ref>{{citation |url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/333/333574.html |title=tt2137 ipl188 Rajasthan Royals v Kolkata Knight Riders: Indian Premier League 2011 |work=CricketArchive |url-access=subscription |accessdate=18 April 2011}}</ref> KKR were knocked out in the semi-finals of the competition;<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/indian-premier-league-2011/content/story/517231.html |title=A cut above the rest |first=Nitin |last=Sundar |work=ESPNcricinfo |date=30 May 2011 |accessdate=31 May 2011}}</ref> Shakib played in seven matches, taking 11&nbsp;wickets at an average of 15.90 and finished as KKR's third-highest wicket-taker.<ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/indian-premier-league-2011/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=5969;type=tournament |title=Indian Premier League, 2011 / Records / Most wickets |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=31 May 2011}}</ref> After the IPL, Shakib returned to Worcestershire for seven weeks. He played a single County Championship match as his time with the team coincided with the [[2011 Friends Life t20]],<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/county-cricket-2011/content/current/story/498143.html |title=Shakib rejoins Worcestershire for 2011|work=ESPNcricinfo |date=6 January 2011 |accessdate=8 January 2011}}</ref><ref>{{citation |url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/73/73152/First-Class_Matches.html |title=First-class matches played by Shakib Al Hasan |work=CricketArchive|url-access=subscription|accessdate=23 July 2011}}</ref> but in that match he took seven wickets and passed 3,000&nbsp;runs in first-class cricket.<ref>{{citation |url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/316/316169.html |title=f53262 Worcestershire v Hampshire: LV County Championship 2011 (Division 1) |work=CricketArchive|url-access=subscription|accessdate=23 July 2011}}</ref> Worcestershire finished fifth out of nine teams in their group for the t20 competition, failing to qualify for the quarter-finals.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/series/491208.html |title=Friends Life t20 2011 |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=23 July 2011}}</ref> From 12&nbsp;matches Shakib took 19&nbsp;wickets, finishing as the club's leading wicket-taker, equal with seam bowler [[Gareth Andrew]].<ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=6381;type=tournament |title=Records / Friends Life t20, 2011 / Most wickets |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=23 July 2011}}</ref>\n\nWhen Bangladesh toured Zimbabwe in [[Bangladeshi cricket team in Zimbabwe in 2011|August 2011]] they were expected to win the one-off Test, which was Zimbabwe's first in five years, and the five-match ODI series. As it transpired Bangladesh lost the ODI series 3\u20132 and the Test. Shakib and his vice-captain, Tamim Iqbal, were sacked with a BCB official citing unsatisfactory leadership.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh/content/current/story/531274.html |title=Shakib and Tamim stripped of leadership roles |work=ESPNcricinfo |date=5 September 2011 |accessdate=5 September 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Post-captaincy (2011\u20132017)===\nBangladesh's first series under new leadership was against the West Indies in [[West Indian cricket team in Bangladesh in 2011\u201312|October 2011]]. Relieved of the captaincy, Shakib was Bangladesh's leading wicket-taker in both the ODI and Test series,<ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=6863;type=series |title=Records / West Indies in Bangladesh ODI Series, 2011/12 / Most wickets |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=21 December 2011}}</ref><ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=6864;type=series |title=Records / West Indies in Bangladesh Test Series, 2011/12 / Most wickets |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=21 December 2011}}</ref> His bowling was backed up by 168&nbsp;runs in the two Tests (of the Bangladesh players, only Tamim Iqbal scored more),<ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/batting/most_runs_career.html?id=6864;type=series |title=Records / West Indies in Bangladesh Test Series, 2011/12 / Most runs |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=21 December 2011}}</ref> and 79 from two innings in the ODIs.<ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/batting/most_runs_career.html?id=6863;type=series |title=Records / West Indies in Bangladesh ODI Series, 2011/12 / Most runs |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=21 December 2011}}</ref> Bangladesh lost both series.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/series/531420.html |title=West Indies tour of Bangladesh 2011/12 / Results |work=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=21 December 2011}}</ref> Following this, Shakib was Bangladesh's top run-scorer and wicket-taker in the [[Pakistani cricket team in Bangladesh in 2011\u201312|home Test series]] against Pakistan in December 2011.<ref>{{citation|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=6957;type=series|title=Pakistan in Bangladesh Test Series, 2011/12: Most wickets|work=[[ESPNcricinfo]]|accessdate=21 December 2011}}</ref><ref>{{citation|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/batting/most_runs_career.html?id=6957;type=series|title=Pakistan in Bangladesh Test Series, 2011/12: Most runs|work=[[ESPNcricinfo]]|accessdate=21 December 2011}}</ref> In the second Test of the series, he became Bangladesh's first player to score a century (his highest score, 144) and take five wickets in an innings in the same Test.<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh-v-pakistan-2011/content/story/546223.html|title=Pakistan in charge despite Shakib's six-for|last=Ravindran|first=Siddarth|date=20 December 2011|work=ESPNcricinfo|accessdate=21 December 2011}}</ref> After the series he moved to first place in the ICC's ranking of Test all-rounders.<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh/content/current/story/546592.html|title=Shakib becomes No. 1 Test allrounder|date=22 December 2011|work=ESPNcricinfo|accessdate=27 December 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Bangladesh Cricket Board]] founded the six-team [[Bangladesh Premier League]] in 2012, a twenty20 tournament to be held in February that year. The BCB made Shakib the 'icon player' for [[Khulna Royal Bengals]].<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh/content/story/547222.html |title=Bangladesh Premier League to begin on February 9 |first=Tariq |last=Engineer |work=[[ESPNcricinfo]] |date=28 December 2011 |accessdate=5 March 2012}}</ref> Under his captaincy, Shakib's team progressed to the semi-finals of the competition where they were beaten by [[Dhaka Gladiators]].<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh-premier-league-2012/content/story/555618.html |title=Dhaka make final despite Shakib |work=[[ESPNcricinfo]] |date=28 February 2012 |accessdate=5 March 2012}}</ref> In ten matches he scored 280&nbsp;runs and took 15&nbsp;wickets, which make him KRB's leading wicket-taker, and was named Man of the Tournament.<ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh-premier-league-2012/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=7188;type=tournament |title=Bangladesh Premier League, 2011/12 / Records / Most wickets |work=[[ESPNcricinfo]] |accessdate=5 March 2012}}</ref><ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh-premier-league-2012/content/story/555925.html |title=The BPL XI |first=Mohammad |last=Isam |work=ESPNcricinfo |date=1 March 2012 |accessdate=5 March 2012}}</ref>\n\nSoon after the BPL finished, Bangladesh hosted the [[2012 Asia Cup]] featuring India, Pakistan, and Sri Lanka. In four matches Shakib scored 237&nbsp;runs including three half-centuries and took six wickets. Bangladesh progressed to the final of the tournament for the first time where they lost to Pakistan by two runs. Shakib's performance saw him named Player of the Tournament and reclaim the number&nbsp;1 ODI all-rounder ranking from Australia's Shane Watson.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/asia-cup-2012/content/story/558027.html |title=Team effort takes Bangladesh to historic final |first=Kanishkaa |last=Balachandran |work=ESPNcricinfo |date=20 March 2012 |accessdate=29 March 2012}}</ref><ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/asia-cup-2012/content/story/558267.html |title=Pakistan prevail over gutsy Bangladesh |first=Abhishek |last=Purohit |work=ESPNcricinfo |date=22 March 2012 |accessdate=29 March 2012}}</ref><ref>{{citation |url=http://icc-cricket.yahoo.net/newsdetails.php?newsId=19717_1332781920 |title=Shakib returns as No.1 ranked all-rounder in ODIs |date=26 March 2012 |publisher=International Cricket Council |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120618034148/http://icc-cricket.yahoo.net/newsdetails.php?newsId=19717_1332781920 |archive-date=18 June 2012 |accessdate=29 March 2012}}</ref> The [[2012 Indian Premier League]] was held in April and May; Shakib played in eight of KKR's 18 matches and won two-man of the match awards as the team won the competition for the first time.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh/content/story/566769.html |title=Shakib happy with IPL outcome |work=ESPNcricinfo |date=30 May 2012 |accessdate=7 July 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[West Indian cricket team in Bangladesh in 2012\u201313|home series against West Indies in late 2012]], he became the 2nd Bangladeshi to both take 100 Test wickets, making him the leading wicket-taker in Tests for Bangladesh, and to complete the 1000 run / 100 wicket double.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh-v-west-indies-2012/content/story/592795.html |title=A high and low for Shakib Al Hasan |first=Kanishkaa |last=Balachandran |work=ESPNcricinfo |date=24 November 2012 |accessdate=11 December 2012}}</ref> However, he got ruled out of the ODI and T20 series due to a shin injury.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh-v-west-indies-2012/content/story/594591.html |title=Shakib out of rest of West Indies ODIs |first=Mohammad |last=Isam |work=ESPNcricinfo |date=1 December 2012 |accessdate=11 December 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[2013 Bangladesh Premier League player auction|auction of the BPL 2]], Shakib was brought by defending champions [[Dhaka Gladiators]] for $365,000, the most expensive player in the tournament.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh/content/story/597888.html |title=Shakib the top pick at BPL auction |first=Mohammad |last=Isam |work=ESPNcricinfo |date=20 December 2012 |accessdate=27 February 2013}}</ref> He led his team to victory, getting 329 runs and 15 wickets in 12 matches, emerging as the Man of the Tournament for consecutive second time in the BPL.\n<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh-premier-league-2013/content/story/605655.html |title=The BPL XI |first=Mohammad |last=Isam |work=ESPNcricinfo |date=20 February 2013 |accessdate=27 February 2013}}</ref>\n\nShakib got ruled out of the [[Bangladeshi cricket team in Sri Lanka in 2012\u201313|Sri Lanka tour]] in March due to a calf muscle injury. He had a successful operation on the right leg at a private hospital in [[Sydney]], [[Australia]]. He would be on rest for one month since his operation<ref>{{citation |url=http://bdnews24.com/cricket/2013/02/26/shakibs-surgery-successful |title=Shakib's surgery successful |first=Mohammad |last=Isam |work=bdnews24.com |date=26 February 2013 |accessdate=27 February 2013}}</ref>\n\nShakib signed for [[Leicestershire County Cricket Club]] as their second overseas club, joining Australian [[Joe Burns (cricketer)|Joe Burns]] for their [[2013 Friends Life t20|Twenty 20]] campaign.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/cricket/21975899 | title=Shakib Al Hasan joins for FL t20 | date=29 March 2013 |work=BBC Sport|publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation| accessdate=28 September 2013}}</ref> Shakib played in all 10 of Leicestershire's games.\n\nIn the [[2013 Caribbean Premier League]], Shakib played for [[Barbados Tridents]]. On 3 August 2013 against [[Trinidad & Tobago Red Steel]] Shakib recorded the second best bowling figure in T20 cricket dismissing six batsmen to finish with figures of 6 for 6 from his four overs at Kensington Oval.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/caribbean-premier-league-2013/content/story/658685.html | title=Barbados Tridents v Trinidad & Tobago Red Steel, CPL 2013, Bridgetown Shakib's six overwhelms Trinidad in low-scorer |work=ESPNcricinfo| date=3 August 2013 | accessdate=17 August 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn his debut match at the [[2013\u201314 Big Bash League season]], Shakib scored 41 runs off 29 balls and took 2 wickets for 21 runs in his 4 overs for [[Adelaide Strikers]], although being unable to prevent his team from losing.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/big-bash-league-2013/engine/current/match/654061.html |work=ESPNcricinfo| title=Adelaide Strikers vs Sidney Sixers | date=5 January 2014 | accessdate=5 January 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[2014 Indian Premier League]], he was retained by Kolkata Knight Riders for a fee of INR 2.80 [[crore]]. In the competition he scored 227 runs in 11 innings at a strike rate of 149.34; his best being a 60 off 38 balls. He also achieved 11 wickets in 13 matches at an economy of 6.68 and an average of 30.36. His all-round performance was instrumental in Kolkata Knight Riders' title win. For his performances in 2014, he was named as 12th man in the [[2014 Indian Premier League#2014 Cricinfo IPL XI|Cricinfo IPL XI]] .\n\nIn 2nd Test match of [[Zimbabwean cricket team in Bangladesh in 2014\u201315|Zimbabwe tour of Bangladesh 2014]] Shakib became only the third player in Test history after [[Ian Botham]] (1980) and [[Imran Khan]] (1983) to score a hundred and take 10 wickets in the same match.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/story/797145.html | title=Shakib joins Imran, Botham | date=7 November 2014 | accessdate=7 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 December 2014, it was announced that Shakib would be joining the [[Melbourne Renegades]] for the final 4 games of the [[2014\u201315 Big Bash League season]], replacing [[Andre Russell]], who would be leaving to join the [[West Indies cricket team|West Indies]] in their [[West Indian cricket team in South Africa in 2014\u201315|tour of South Africa]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cricket.com.au/news/shakib-al-hasan-joins-melbourne-renegades-big-bash-league/2014-12-24|title=Bangladesh hero Shakib joins Renegades|work=cricket.com.au|accessdate=15 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bigbash.com.au/news-and-videos/2014/12/24/shakib-al-hasan-joins-melbourne-renegades|title=Shakib joins the Renegades|work=bigbash.com.au|accessdate=15 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.melbournerenegades.com.au/news/2014/12/24/renegades-sign-shakib|title=Renegades sign Shakib Al Hasan|work=melbournerenegades.com.au|accessdate=15 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, Shakib helped Bangladesh to their most successful year in cricket. Following their success in the [[2015 Cricket World Cup]], he also helped the team to a white wash of Pakistan and series win against India and South Africa. On 15 July, he took his 200th wicket of his ODI career by taking wicket of [[Hashim Amla]] in the final ODI of the series. He also became the 8th and youngest ODI cricketer to take 200 wickets and score 4000 runs.\n\n===New era of Test & T20I captaincy (2017\u20132019)===\nAfter the retirement of [[Mashrafe Mortaza]] in 2017, Shakib was appointed as the T20I captain of the team for the second time. Later [[Mushfiqur Rahim]] was also removed from Test captaincy and Hasan was again appointed as Test captain. However, during [[2017-18 Bangladesh Tri-Nation Series]] he injured his finger and was rested for few days and in his absence [[Mahmudullah]] captained the side in the [[Sri Lankan cricket team in Bangladesh in 2017-18|Home series against Sri Lanka]] and [[2018 Nidahas Trophy]]. His first tour was against Pakistan in July 2017.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cricketcountry.com/news/shakib-al-hasan-appointed-bangladeshs-t20i-captain-598395 |title=Shakib Al Hasan appointed Bangladesh's T20I captain |publisher=Cricket Country |accessdate=22 April 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thedailystar.net/sports/shakib-officially-t20-captain-1394791 |title=Shakib officially T20 captain |work=The Daily Star |accessdate=22 April 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 August 2017, Al Hasan became the 4th bowler in Test history to record a 5-wicket haul against all Test Playing nations (except Afghanistan and Ireland, who have only just granted Test status earlier that year.) when he grabbed 5 wickets against Australia in his first encounter with the team. He also scored a half-century in the first innings. In the second innings, he only scored 8 runs with the bat, but he grabbed another 5 wickets to secure his first 10-wicket haul and the win.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cricket.com.au/news/shakib-al-hasan-five-wicket-haul-bangladesh-australia-every-test-playing-nation-herath-murali-steyn/2017-08-28|title=Shakib joins legends with record five|work=cricket.com.au|access-date=28 August 2017|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://live.cricket.com.au/#/2032/41972|title=Live & Official Cricket Scores {{!}} cricket.com.au|website=live.cricket.com.au|access-date=30 August 2017}}</ref> However, after the series, Al Hasan opted to take a break from Test to focus on limited-overs games.\n\nIn April 2018, he was one of ten cricketers to be awarded a central contract by the [[Bangladesh Cricket Board]] (BCB) ahead of the 2018 season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/23229414/bcb-cuts-contracts-list-2018-ten |title=BCB cuts contracts list for 2018 to ten |work=ESPN Cricinfo |accessdate=18 April 2018}}</ref> Later the same month, he was named in the [[World XI (cricket)|Rest of the World XI]] squad for the [[West Indies v ICC World XI in England in 2018|one-off T20I]] against the [[West Indies national cricket team|West Indies]], played at [[Lord's]] on 31 May 2018,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.icc-cricket.com/media-releases/670194 |title=Rashid, Tamim and Shakib confirmed for ICC World XI team to play the Windies at Lord's |work=International Cricket Council |accessdate=23 April 2018}}</ref> but later withdrew from squad due to personal reason.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.icc-cricket.com/media-releases/691274|title=Sandeep Lamichhane added to the ICC World XI for 31 May T20I against the Windies at Lord's|accessdate=16 May 2018|work=International Cricket Council}}</ref> On 24 May, he became the second T20 player to take 300 wickets and score 4000 runs in the format.<ref>{{cite web|title=Super Shakib joins elite list of T20 greats|url=https://www.cricket.com.au/news/shakib-al-hasan-t20-allrounder-4000-runs-300-wickets-double/2018-04-25|website=cricket.com.au|publisher=Cricket Australia|accessdate=25 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2018, he was named in the squad for the [[Dhaka Dynamites]] team, following the draft for the [[2018\u201319 Bangladesh Premier League]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tigercricket.com.bd/2018/10/29/full-players-list-of-the-teams-following-players-draft-of-bpl-t20-2018-19/ |title=Full players list of the teams following Players Draft of BPL T20 2018\u201319 |work=Bangladesh Cricket Board |accessdate=29 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2018, in the series [[West Indian cricket team in Bangladesh in 2018\u201319|against the West Indies]], he became the first bowler for Bangladesh to [[List of Bangladesh Test cricket records#Most Wickets|take 200 wickets in Tests]].<ref name=\"SAH200\"/> In the same match, he also became the fastest cricketer, in terms of matches, to score 3,000 runs and take 200 wickets in Tests, doing so in his 54th match.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thedailystar.net/sports/bangladesh-cricket/news/shakib-becomes-fastest-200-wicket-3000-run-double-1664536 |title=Shakib becomes fastest to 200-wicket, 3,000-run double |work=The Daily Star (Bangladesh) |accessdate=24 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2019:Cricket World Cup and beyond===\nIn April 2019, he was named as the vice-captain of [[2019 Cricket World Cup squads#Bangladesh|Bangladesh's squad]] for the [[2019 Cricket World Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/26535028/bangladesh-pick-odi-newbie-abu-jayed-world-cup |title=Bangladesh pick ODI newbie Abu Jayed for World Cup |work=ESPN Cricinfo |accessdate=16 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.icc-cricket.com/news/1180213 |title=Shakib, Jayed, Hossain in Bangladesh squad for World Cup |work=International Cricket Council |accessdate=16 April 2019}}</ref> In the first innings of  Bangladesh's opening match in the World Cup, against [[South Africa national cricket team|South Africa]], he and [[Mushfiqur Rahim]] scored 142 runs for the third wicket, the highest partnership for any wicket for Bangladesh in a World Cup match.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.republicworld.com/sports-news/cricket-news/world-cup-2019-what-a-lovely-batting-tigers-rave-netizens-as-shakib-al-hasan-and-mushfiqur-rahims-record-breaking-partnership-sets-bangladesh-up-for-a-big-total-against-south-africa |title=World Cup 2019: \u2018What A Lovely Batting Tigers\u2019, Rave Netizens As Shakib Al Hasan And Mushfiqur Rahim\u2019s Record-breaking Partnership Sets Bangladesh Up For A Big Total Against South Africa |work=Republic World |accessdate=2 June 2019}}</ref> Bangladesh went on to score their [[List of Bangladesh One Day International cricket records#Highest Innings Totals|highest total in an ODI match]], finishing on 330/6 from their 50 overs.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://in.reuters.com/article/cricket-worldcup-zaf-bgd/cricket-record-partnership-spurs-bangladesh-to-score-their-highest-odi-total-idINL8N2390HF |title=Cricket-Record partnership spurs Bangladesh to score their highest ODI total |work=Reuters |accessdate=2 June 2019}}</ref> In the second innings, he took the wicket of [[Aiden Markram]] as  his 250th wicket in ODIs, to become the fastest cricketer to take 250 wickets and score 5,000 runs in ODIs, in terms of number of matches (199).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thedailystar.net/icc-cricket-world-cup-2019/news/shakib-fastest-5k-runs-250-wickets-double-1752502 |title=Shakib fastest to 5k runs, 250 wickets double |work=The Daily Star (Bangladesh) |accessdate=2 June 2019}}</ref> Bangladesh went on to win the match by 21 runs with Shakib named as player of the match. In that match he also became the first cricketer to score a fifty in the first match of Bangladesh in each World Cup since [[2007 Cricket World Cup|2007]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/8039/game/1144487/bangladesh-vs-south-africa-5th-match-icc-cricket-world-cup-2019 |title=5th match, ICC Cricket World Cup at London, Jun 2 2019 |work=ESPN Cricinfo |accessdate=2 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn Bangladesh's next match in the tournament, against [[New Zealand national cricket team|New Zealand]], Shakib played in his 200th ODI.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thedailystar.net/icc-cricket-world-cup-2019/bangladesh-vs-new-zealand-interesting-facts-1753495 |title=Interesting facts ahead of Tigers' game against New Zealand |work=The Daily Star (Bangladesh) |accessdate=5 June 2019}}</ref> On 17 June 2019, in the match against the [[West Indies cricket team|West Indies]], Shakib became the second batsman for Bangladesh to [[List of Bangladesh One Day International cricket records#Most Career Runs|score 6,000 runs in ODIs]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dhakatribune.com/sport/cricket/2019/06/17/shakib-gets-past-6-000-odi-runs |title=Shakib gets past 6,000 ODI runs |work=Dhaka Tribune |accessdate=17 June 2019}}</ref> For his unbeaten 124 he was awarded man of the match.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/sports/cricket-world-cup-2019/story/west-indies-vs-bangladesh-world-cup-2019-report-shakib-al-hasan-hundred-liton-das-1550840-2019-06-17|title= World Cup 2019: Shakib, Liton gun down 322 in record chase as Bangladesh crush West Indies|work= India Today |accessdate=17 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 June 2019, in the match against [[Afghanistan national cricket team|Afghanistan]], where he was again named man of the match, Shakib became the first batsman for Bangladesh to score 1,000 runs in the Cricket World Cup,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/cricket/icc-world-cup-2019-bangladesh-vs-afghanistan-shakib-al-hasan-scripts-unique-world-cup-history-for-bangladesh/story-7oR0TQYDSpW7We3JRIc8mN.html |title=ICC\u2009World Cup 2019, Bangladesh vs Afghanistan:\u2009Shakib Al Hasan scripts unique World Cup history for Bangladesh |work=Hindustan Times |accessdate=24 June 2019}}</ref> and the first bowler for Bangladesh to take a [[five-wicket haul]] in a World Cup match.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/sports/cricket-world-cup-2019/story/bangladesh-vs-afghanistan-world-cup-2019-match-report-shakib-al-hasan-mushfiqur-rahim-1555443-2019-06-24 |title=World Cup 2019: Bangladesh ride on all-round Shakib Al Hasan to inflict 7th-straight defeat on Afghanistan |work=India Today |accessdate=24 June 2019}}</ref> He also became the second cricketer, after [[Yuvraj Singh]], to score 50 runs and take five wickets in the same match at a World Cup.<ref name=\"Indian Express\">{{cite web|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/sports/cricket-world-cup/shakib-al-hasan-yuvraj-singhs-world-cup-record-5797784/ |title=Shakib al Hasan matches Yuvraj Singh\u2019s World Cup record for best all-round performance |work=Indian Express |accessdate=24 June 2019}}</ref> On 2 July 2019, in the match against [[India national cricket team|India]], Shakib became the first cricketer in the World Cup to score 500 runs and take 10 wickets in a single tournament.<ref name=\"The Hindu\">{{cite news |last1=Sportstar |first1=Team |title=Shakib Al Hasan first to 500 runs and 10 wickets in single World Cup |url=https://sportstar.thehindu.com/cricket/icc-cricket-world-cup/news/shakib-al-hasan-world-cup-2019-records-batting-bowling-allrounder-new-zealand-scott-styris/article28263851.ece |accessdate=2 July 2019 |work=[[Sportstar]] |publisher=[[The Hindu]] |date=2 July 2019}}</ref> He finished the tournament as the leading run-scorer for Bangladesh, with 606 runs in eight matches.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/averages/batting_bowling_by_team.html?id=12357;team=25;type=tournament |title=ICC Cricket World Cup, 2019 - Bangladesh: Batting and bowling averages |work=ESPN Cricinfo |accessdate=5 July 2019}}</ref> and surpassed [[Sachin Tendulkar]]'s record for the most runs in the group stage of a World Cup.<ref name=\"hasan\">{{cite web |title=Shakib Al Hasan breaks Sachin Tendulkar' World Cup record |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/sports/cricket-world-cup-2019/story/shakib-al-hasan-breaks-sachin-tendulkar-world-cup-record-1563193-2019-07-05 |first=Saurabh|last=Kumar|website=India Today |date=5 July 2019|accessdate=6 July 2019}}</ref> He was named in the 'Team of the Tournament' by the ICC and ESPNCricinfo.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.icc-cricket.com/news/1278701/featured|title=CWC19: Team of the Tournament |work=ICC |accessdate=25 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/27210608/starc-archer-ferguson-bumrah-espncricinfo-2019-world-cup-xi |title= Starc, Archer, Ferguson, Bumrah in ESPNcricinfo's 2019 World Cup XI|work=ESPNCricinfo |accessdate=25 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2019, during the [[2019\u201320 Bangladesh Tri-Nation Series]], Shakib took his 350th wicket in international cricket, in the final group match against [[Afghanistan national cricket team|Afghanistan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.icc-cricket.com/news/1353055 |title=All-round Shakib gives Bangladesh momentum heading into tri-series final |work=International Cricket Council |accessdate=21 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Disciplinary issues==\nIn October 2010, Shakib was on 92 in the fourth ODI against [[New Zealand cricket team|New Zealand]], when there was movement near the sightscreen, which the umpires failed to stop.<ref name=\"Discipline\">{{Cite news|title= A punishment that should have come earlier|url= http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh/content/story/721459.html|work= [[ESPNcricinfo]]|date= 22 February 2014|accessdate=23 February 2014}}</ref> After a few minutes Shakib, Bangladesh captain at the time, ran towards the sightscreen, hurled abuse and threatened to hit the offender with his bat.<ref name=\"Discipline\" /> He was later warned by the match referee.<ref name=\"Discipline\" />\n\nIn March 2011, during the world cup match against [[West Indies cricket team|West Indies]], several people in the [[Sher-e-Bangla National Cricket Stadium]] grandstand complained Shakib had reacted too strongly when he was booed.<ref name=\"Discipline\" /> The offending picture was spread over the internet and published in several newspapers. Within days of that incident, Shakib blasted former national cricketers in his ''[[Prothom Alo]]'' column.<ref name=\"Discipline\" />\n\nIn February 2014, Shakib was fined BDT 300,000 and was handed with a three-ODI ban, because he had made an indecent gesture towards his crotch in the dressing room live on broadcast, during the second ODI against [[Sri Lanka cricket team|Sri Lanka]].<ref>{{Cite news|title= Shakib suspended for three ODIs|url= http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh/content/story/721171.html|work= [[ESPNcricinfo]]|date= 21 February 2014|accessdate=23 February 2014}}</ref> Shakib later made a public apology statement through his official [[Facebook]] page.<ref>{{Cite news|title= Shakib offers an apology|url= http://bdnews24.com/cricket/2014/02/22/shakib-offers-an-apology|publisher= [[bdnews24.com]]|date= 22 February 2014|accessdate=23 February 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2014, Shakib was allegedly involved in a brawl between him and a spectator, who was allegedly harassing Shakib's wife in the grand stand of Sher-e-Bangla National Cricket Stadium, during the first ODI against [[India cricket team|India]].<ref>{{Cite news|title= BCB to investigate alleged altercation between Shakib, spectator|url= http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh-v-india-2014/content/story/752783.html|work= ESPNcricinfo|date= 15 June 2014|accessdate=8 July 2014}}</ref> Shakib violated rules by \"leaving the team dressing room during the course of an international match\".<ref>{{Cite news|title= Shakib attends BCB hearing over alleged altercation|url= http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh/content/story/754361.html|work= ESPNcricinfo|date= 21 June 2014|accessdate=8 July 2014}}</ref> Shakib later filed a case the following day regarding the incident.<ref>{{Cite news|title= Man held for \u2018harassing\u2019 Shakib's wife|url= http://bdnews24.com/bangladesh/2014/06/19/man-held-for-harassing-shakibs-wife|work= [[bdnews24.com]]|date= 19 June 2014|accessdate=8 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nDuring the 6th T20I match which was a controversial tense clash between Sri Lanka and Bangladesh as a part of the [[2018 Nidahas Trophy]], he argued the poor umpiring errors for not signalling a \"no ball\" delivery when [[Isuru Udana]] bowled 2 short pitched bouncer deliveries to [[Mustafizur Rahman]] in the last over of the match, where Bangladesh needed 12 runs to victory off the six balls.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/22803467/shakib-nurul-fined-breaching-code-conduct|title=Shakib, Nurul fined for breaching code of conduct|work=ESPNcricinfo|access-date=17 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cricbuzz.com/cricket-news/101036/shakib-al-hasan-nurul-hasan-nidahas-trophy-fined-25-percent-for-altercation|title=Shakib, Nurul fined for breaching ICC code of conduct|work=Cricbuzz|access-date=17 March 2018|language=en}}</ref> Fellow cricketer, [[Mahmudullah]] who was on the non-striker's end when Mustafizur Rahman was batting, demanded a no-ball delivery from the on-field umpires. Shakib later threatened to leave the field and recalled the batsmen from the field as a result of the umpiring errors. Reserve Bangladeshi cricketer, [[Nurul Hasan (cricketer)|Nurul Hasan]] was also suspected to have breached the code of conduct for exchanging war of words with Sri Lankan skipper, [[Thisara Perera]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thedailystar.net/sports/bangladesh-cricket/hot-rivalry-what-cost-1549450|title=A hot rivalry, but at what cost?|date=2018-03-17|work=The Daily Star|access-date=17 March 2018|language=en}}</ref> It was also revealed that Shakib exchanged arguments with Sri Lankan commentator [[Russell Arnold]]. The [[International Cricket Council]] later imposed a 25 percent fine and issued a demerit point to both Shakib and [[Nurul Hasan (cricketer)|Nurul Hasan]] for their unruly behaviour on the field by breaching the code of ethics.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/cricket/india-sri-lanka-bangladesh-tri-series/shakib-al-hasan-nurul-hasan-docked-25-percent-match-fee/articleshow/63344033.cms|title=Shakib Al Hasan, Nurul Hasan docked 25 percent match fee \u2013 Times of India|work=The Times of India|access-date=17 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.firstpost.com/firstcricket/sports-news/nidahas-trophy-2018-shakib-al-hasan-fined-handed-demerit-point-nurul-hasan-penalised-for-breaching-iccs-code-of-conduct-4394401.html|title=Nidahas Trophy 2018: Shakib Al Hasan fined, handed demerit point; Nurul Hasan penalised for breaching ICC's code of conduct- Firstcricket News, Firstpost|website=FirstCricket|language=en-US|access-date=17 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://zeenews.india.com/cricket/shakib-al-hasan-nurul-hasan-receive-punishment-for-breaching-icc-code-of-conduct-2090760.html|title=Shakib Al Hasan, Nurul Hasan receive punishment for breaching ICC Code of Conduct|date=2018-03-17|work=Zee News|access-date=2018-03-17|language=en}}</ref>\n\n===International ban===\nOn 7 July 2014, Shakib was banned for eight months from all forms of cricket for what the [[Bangladesh Cricket Board]] described as a \"severe attitude problem\".<ref name=\"Banned\">{{cite web | url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh/content/story/758155.html | title=Shakib Al Hasan suspended for six months by BCB | work=ESPNcricinfo| date=7 July 2014 | accessdate=8 July 2014}}</ref> Shakib missed Bangladesh's [[Bangladesh cricket team in West Indies in 2014|tour of the West Indies]]; he was also prohibited to participate in foreign tournaments until 31 December 2015.<ref name=\"Banned\"/> Controversy arose when Shakib left to play for the [[Barbados Tridents]] of the [[Caribbean Premier League]], allegedly without informing board officials and without obtaining a [[No Objection Certificate]] from the board, a claim he has denied.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh/content/story/757945.html | title='I never said I would quit' \u2013 Shakib| work=ESPNcricinfo| date=6 July 2014 | accessdate=8 July 2014}}</ref> Shakib found himself embroiled in further controversy after a dispute with coach [[Chandika Hathurusingha]] led to rumours of him threatening to retire from Test and One Day cricket.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh/content/story/757629.html | title=Shakib threatens to quit international cricket| work=ESPNcricinfo| date=5 July 2014 | accessdate=8 July 2014}}</ref> The BCB has ended the restriction on no-objection certificates being issued to Bangladesh all-rounder Shakib Al Hasan, leaving him free to participate in overseas tournaments. BCB reduced his ban by three a half months on 26 August 2014 letting him play for Bangladesh from 15 September 2014.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh/content/story/807379.html | title=Shakib's NOC restriction lifted| work=ESPNcricinfo| date=4 December 2014 | accessdate=4 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nShakib was initially selected to lead the team in the [[Bangladeshi cricket team in India in 2019\u201320|T20I and Test series against India]], but on 29 October 2019, Shakib was suspended for one year and banned from all forms of cricket for two years by the [[International Cricket Council]] for breaching the ICC-Anti Corruption Code. Shakib was supposedly contacted by bookmakers while playing in the [[2018 Bangladesh Tri-Nation Series]] and also in a group match between [[Sunrisers Hyderabad]] and [[Kings XI Punjab]] in the [[2018 Indian Premier League]] . For failing to report those approaches made to him by the bookmakers, he was found guilty of breaching the ICC ''Anti-Corruption Code 2.4.4'' and was handed a two-year ban, one year being suspended. He is supposed to be able to resume international cricket on 29 October 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cricbuzz.com/cricket-news/110552/shakib-al-hasan-icc-bcb-ban-banned-suspended-bangladesh-cricket-team |title=ICC bans Shakib Al Hasan for two years |work=Cricbuzz|date=29 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==== Players strike ====\nShakib also led a players' strike which existed for a brief period of time from 21 October 2019 to 23 October 2019 demanding for higher salaries especially in domestic first class cricket system and issues related to proposal of Bangladesh Premier League to adopt the franchise method.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/50136104|title=Bangladesh Cricket Board calls players' strike a conspiracy|access-date=31 October 2019|work=[[BBC]]}}</ref> He along with fellow players reportedly addressed the pay dispute issue to the media and even threatened to boycott the [[Bangladeshi cricket team in India in 2019\u201320|tour of India]] and the rest of international cricket season until their demands were to be fulfilled.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/10/bangladesh-cricketers-strike-pay-demands-191021114726557.html|title=Bangladesh cricketers go on strike seeking demands|access-date=31 October 2019|work=[[Al Jazeera]]}}</ref> However the issue was sorted out as the BCB accepted to fulfill the demand of the players by offering salary increments.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/27909061/bangladesh-players-go-strike|title=Full coverage: Player revolt in Bangladesh cricket|access-date=31 October 2019|work=Cricinfo}}</ref> During the time when he was leading the players' strike, he was also accused for breaching the agreement with BCB by signing a sponsorship deal as an ambassador for an undisclosed amount with a leading telecommunication operator called [[Grameenphone]] which is also a former national team sponsor.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geosuper.tv/latest/3141-bangladesh-to-take-captain-to-court-over|title=Bangladesh to take Shakib to court over breaching the agreement|access-date=31 October 2019|work=[[Geo Super]]}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nShakib studied for a [[English major|BA in English]] at [[American International University-Bangladesh]] (AIUB).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aiub.edu/aiub-inter-dept-twenty20-cricket-tournament-2009|title=AIUB Inter Dept. Twenty20 Cricket Tournament 2009|publisher=AIUB|accessdate=23 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nHe married Umme Ahmed Shishir, a [[Bangladeshi American]] in December 2012.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh/content/story/596892.html |title=\nShakib ties knot with US-based girl |first=Mohammad |last=Isam |work=ESPNcricinfo |date=12 December 2012 |accessdate=12 December 2012}}</ref><ref>{{citation |url=http://bdnews24.com/details.php?id=238050&cid=26 |title=\nShakib starts 'new innings' |first= |last= |work=[[Bdnews24.com]] |date=12 December 2012 |accessdate=12 December 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Demotix\">{{citation |url=http://www.demotix.com/news/1673040/cricketer-sakib-al-hasan-marries-bangladesh |title= Cricketer Shakib Al Hasan marries |first=Anisul |last=Islam |work=[[Demotix]] |date=12 December 2012 |accessdate=12 December 2012}}</ref> The couple met each other in 2011 while Shakib was playing [[county cricket]] for [[Worcestershire County Cricket Club|Worcestershire]] in England.<ref name=\"Demotix\" /> They had their first daughter Alayna Aubrey Hasan  in 8 November 2015. In August 2018 he became a [[Lawful permanent residents (United States)|green card holder]] which allows him to live and work in the US. <!-- Despite what the headline in the ref says a green card doesn't mean that one automatically becomes a citizen. See the Lawful permanent residents (United States) article. --><ref>{{citation|url=https://newsbeezer.com/bangladesh/shakib-is-now-a-us-citizen-got-greencard/|title=Shakib is now a US citizen, got greencard!|work=NewsBeezer|accessdate=3 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Records and achievements==\n{{see also|List of international cricket five-wicket hauls by Shakib Al Hasan|Five-wicket haul#List of bowlers who have taken five-wicket hauls in all three international formats}}\n\n* Best partnership record for any wicket for a Bangladeshi pair in ODIs, with Mahmadullah (224).<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/fow/highest_partnerships_by_wicket.html?class=2;id=25;type=team|title=Cricket Records/ Bangladesh/ One-Day Internationals/ Highest partnerships by wicket|work=Cricinfo|access-date=30 August 2017}}</ref> (This is also the highest ever 5th wicket runs stand in the history of [[ICC Champions Trophy]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/fow/highest_partnerships_by_wicket.html?id=44;type=trophy|title=Cricket Records/ ICC Champions Trophy/ Highest partnerships by wicket|work=Cricinfo|access-date=30 August 2017}}</ref>)\n* Most wickets taken in [[Twenty20|T20 cricket]] on a single ground (76 at [[Sher-e-Bangla National Cricket Stadium|Shere Bangla National Stadium]], [[Mirpur Model Thana|Mirpur]])<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/records/305216.html|title=Records/ Twenty20 matches/ Bowling records/ Most wickets on a single ground|work=Cricinfo|access-date=10 June 2017}}</ref>\n* Fourth bowler in Test cricket history to pick up 5-wickets hauls against all Test playing nations (after [[Dale Steyn]], [[Muttiah Muralitharan]] and [[Rangana Herath]])<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cricket.com.au/news/shakib-al-hasan-five-wicket-haul-bangladesh-australia-every-test-playing-nation-herath-murali-steyn/2017-08-28|title=Shakib joins legends with record five |work=Cricket.com.au |accessdate=28 August 2017}}</ref>\n* Third all-rounder in the history of international cricket to reach 10,000 runs and take 500 wickets, fastest to do so<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kumar |first1=Ram |title=Stats: Shakib Al Hasan fastest to register 10,000 runs and 500 wickets in international cricket history |url=https://www.sportskeeda.com/cricket/stats-shakib-al-hasan-fastest-to-register-10-000-runs-and-500-wickets-in-international-cricket-history |accessdate=16 June 2018 |agency=sportskeeda |date=7 June 2018}}</ref>\n* First spin bowler, and third player overall (with [[Wasim Akram]] and [[Waqar Younis|Waqar Yonis]] grabbing 100+ each at [[Sharjah Cricket Stadium|Sharjah]] stadium), to grab 100+ ODI wickets at a single ground. (112 at  [[Sher-e-Bangla National Cricket Stadium|Sher-e-Bangla National Stadium]])<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/records/283947.html|title=Records {{!}} One-Day Internationals {{!}} Bowling records {{!}} Most wickets on a single ground {{!}} ESPNcricinfo|work=Cricinfo|access-date=2018-08-13}}</ref>\n* In 2017 [[Bangladeshi cricket team in New Zealand in 2016\u201317#1st Test|in the 1st Test between Bangladesh and New Zealand]], he became only Seventh batsman to score a double century and got a duck in a test when he scored 217 and 0.<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/18542322/double-duck-tail-end-highs|title=Double and a duck|work=ESPNCricinfo}}</ref>\n* Only The Third all-rounder in the World to score a century and take a 10 Wicket-haul in a match after Sir [[Ian Botham]] and [[Imran Khan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sportskeeda.com/cricket/all-rounders-who-scored-a-century-and-picked-10-wickets-in-the-same-test|title=3 all-rounders who scored a century and picked 10 wickets in the same Test|author=Depak Panda|work=[[Sportskeeda]]|accessdate=22 November 2014}}</ref>\n* Only all-rounder in the cricket history to be ranked #1 Alrounder In all three formats.\n* Fastest all-rounder to score 3000 Test Runs and take 200 Test wicket (54 Test) surpassing [[Ian Botham]] who took 55 test matches to reach the milestone.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://zeenews.india.com/cricket/shakib-al-hasan-becomes-fastest-to-reach-3000-runs-200-wickets-in-tests-2158203.html|title=Shakib Al Hasan becomes fastest to reach 3000 runs; 200 wickets in Tests|work=[[Zee News]]|accessdate=23 November 2018}}</ref>\n* Fastest all-rounder to score 5000 ODI Runs and take 200 ODI wickets.{{Citation needed|date=June 2019}}\n* First Bangladeshi Bowler to take 500 international wickets.{{Citation needed|date=June 2019}}\n* Second Bangladeshi Batsmen to score 10,000 International Runs.{{Citation needed|date=June 2019}} \n* Most Test (203*) and T20I (85*) wicket taker for  Bangladesh.\n* Shakib leads the table of scoring most runs on a single ground (3980 runs in 120 innings)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/records/284230.html|title=Records/ Test, ODI, T20I/ Most runs on a single ground|work=ESPNCricinfo}}</ref> and most wickets on a single ground (190 wickets in 110 matches) combining all formats.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/records/283945.html|title=Records/ Test, ODI, T20I/ Most wickets on a single ground|work=ESPNCricinfo}}</ref>\n* In December 2018 in the [[West Indian cricket team in Bangladesh in 2018\u201319#2nd T20I|2nd T20I against West Indies]], Shakib become the eighth cricketer to take at least one five wicket-haul in all three formats.{{efn|other seven players being [[Tim Southee]], [[Lasith Malinga]], [[Ajantha Mendis]], [[Bhuvneshwar Kumar]], [[Umar Gul]], [[Imran Tahir]] and [[Kuldeep Yadav]]}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newsnation.in/sports-news/cricket-news/shakib-al-hasan-five-wicket-haul-world-record-bangladesh-vs-west-indies-mirpur-t20i-article-209507.html |title=Shakib Al Hasan enters elite list after five-wicket haul... |work=News Nation |accessdate=20 December 2018}}</ref>\n* Best bowling figure by a captain (5/20) in a T20I match and the only captain to pick up a five-fer in T20Is.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/records/283935.html|title=T20I Bowling Records/ Best figures in a innings by a captain|work=ESPNCricinfo}}</ref>\n* In the first match of [[2019 Cricket World Cup group stage#Bangladesh vs South Africa|against South Africa in 2019 World Cup]], he became become the second Bangladeshi bowler to bag 250 ODI wickets and the fastest and the fifth player to score 5000 runs and to take 250 wickets in ODIs in just 199 matches. (Others cricketer being [[Abdul Razzak]], [[Sanath Jayasuriya]], [[Jacques Kallis]] and [[Shahid Afridi]])<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.timesnownews.com/sports/cricket/article/icc-world-cup-2019-shakib-al-hasan-scripts-massive-world-record-becomes-fastest-to-take-250-wickets-and-score-5000-runs-in-odis/430073| title=Shakib Al Hasan scripts massive world record, becomes fastest to take 250 wickets and score 5000 runs in ODIs| work=Times Now|date=2 June 2019}}</ref>\n*Shakib is one of only three cricketers with 4,000 runs and 300 wickets in T20s. He achieved this milestone in 260 matches, faster that the other two who achieved the mark, [[Shahid Afridi]] (283) and [[Dwayne Bravo]] (292).\n*Shakib is the fastest to score 11,000 runs and to get 500 wickets.\n* In [[2019 Cricket World Cup]], Shakib became quickest All-rounder, in terms of innings, to achieve the double of 6,000 runs and 250 wickets in ODIs and overall fourth cricketer to achieve the double.{{efn|others three cricketers are [[Sanath Jayasuriya]], [[Jacques Kallis]] and [[Shahid Afridi]].}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sportstar.thehindu.com/cricket/icc-cricket-world-cup/news/shakib-al-hasan-records-best-allrounder-6000-runs-wickets-jacques-kallis/article28022408.ece|title=World Cup 2019: Shakib Al Hasan slams century, topples records|work=Sportstar|publisher=The Hindu|date=17 June 2019}}</ref>\n* In [[2019 Cricket World Cup]] group match [[2019 Cricket World Cup group stage#Afghanistan vs Bangladesh|against Afghanistan]], Shakib achieved several milestones.\n** Shakib became first Bangladeshi player to score 1,000 runs in World Cup and also the first from Bangladesh to pick up a five wicket haul in World Cup.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/cricket/icc-world-cup-2019-bangladesh-vs-afghanistan-shakib-al-hasan-scripts-unique-world-cup-history-for-bangladesh/story-7oR0TQYDSpW7We3JRIc8mN.html |title=ICC\u2009World Cup 2019, Bangladesh vs Afghanistan:\u2009Shakib Al Hasan scripts unique World Cup history for Bangladesh |work=Hindustan Times |accessdate=24 June 2019}}</ref>\n** He became the only cricketer to score 1,000 runs and pick up 30 wickets in World Cup alongside the only one to score 600 runs and pick up 10 wickets in a single tournament of World Cup.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.prothomalo.com/sports/article/1600972/|title=\n\u09b0\u09c7\u0995\u09b0\u09cd\u09a1\u099f\u09bf\u09b0 \u0995\u09a5\u09be \u09ae\u09be\u09a5\u09be\u09af\u09bc \u099b\u09bf\u09b2 \u09b8\u09be\u0995\u09bf\u09ac\u09c7\u09b0 |work=Prothom Alo|date=25 June 2019|language=bn}}</ref>\n** He became the second cricketer after [[Yuvraj Singh]] to score a 50 and pick up a 5 wicket haul in World Cup match.<ref name=\"Indian Express\"/>\n* In [[2019 Cricket World Cup|2019 World Cup]] group match [[2019 Cricket World Cup group stage#Bangladesh vs India|against India]], Shakib became first ever cricketer to score 500 runs and pick up 10 wickets in a single tournament of World Cup.<ref name=\"The Hindu\"/>\n* In [[2019 Cricket World Cup|2019 World Cup]] group match [[2019 Cricket World Cup group stage#Pakistan vs Bangladesh|against Pakistan]], Shakib equalled [[Sachin Tendulkar]]'s record of making the [[List of Cricket World Cup records#One tournament|most 50+ runs in a single World Cup tournament]] (7).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/sports/cricket-world-cup-2019/story/shakib-al-hasan-breaks-sachin-tendulkar-world-cup-record-1563193-2019-07-05 |title=Shakib Al Hasan breaks Sachin Tendulkar' World Cup record|work=India Today|date=5 July 2019}}</ref> and also became the first Bangladeshi and third player in the world to score more than 600 runs in a single World Cup.\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* {{Cricinfo|ref=ci/content/player/56143.html}}\n* [https://www.cricbuzz.com/profiles/544/shakib-al-hasan  Shakib Al Hasan Profile] on [[Cricbuzz]]\n\n{{s-start-collapsible|header={{S-sports}}}}\n{{succession box|\n before=[[Mashrafe Mortaza]]|\n title=[[Bangladeshi national cricket captains|Bangladesh national cricket captain]]|\n years=2009\u20132010 |\n after= [[Mashrafe Mortaza]]\n}}\n{{succession box|\n before=[[Mashrafe Mortaza]]|\n title=[[Bangladeshi national cricket captains|Bangladesh national cricket captain]]|\n years=2010\u20132011 |\n after= [[Mushfiqur Rahim]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Current national cricket captains}}\n{{Navboxes colour\n|title= Captaincy\n|bg= #006838\n|fg=red\n|bordercolor=red\n|list1=\n{{Bangladeshi Test cricket captains}}\n{{Bangladesh ODI cricket captains}}\n{{Bangladesh T20I cricket captains}}\n}}\n{{Navboxes colour\n|title= Bangladesh squads\n|bg= #006838\n|fg= red\n|bordercolor=red\n|list1=\n{{Bangladesh Squad 2007 Cricket World Cup}}\n{{Bangladesh Squad 2011 Cricket World Cup}}\n{{Bangladesh Squad 2015 Cricket World Cup}}\n{{Bangladesh Squad 2019 Cricket World Cup}}\n}}\n{{Dhaka Dynamites squad}}\n{{Sunrisers Hyderabad Squad}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Shakib al Hasan}}\n[[Category:1987 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Bangladeshi cricketers]]\n[[Category:Bangladesh Test cricketers]]\n[[Category:Bangladesh One Day International cricketers]]\n[[Category:Bangladesh Twenty20 International cricketers]]\n[[Category:Bengali people]]\n[[Category:Kolkata Knight Riders cricketers]]\n[[Category:Sunrisers Hyderabad cricketers]]\n[[Category:Khulna Division cricketers]]\n[[Category:Worcestershire cricketers]]\n[[Category:Leicestershire cricketers]]\n[[Category:Cricketers at the 2007 Cricket World Cup]]\n[[Category:Cricketers at the 2011 Cricket World Cup]]\n[[Category:Cricketers at the 2015 Cricket World Cup]]\n[[Category:Dhaka Dynamites cricketers]]\n[[Category:Khulna Royal Bengals cricketers]]\n[[Category:Melbourne Renegades cricketers]]\n[[Category:Barbados Tridents cricketers]]\n[[Category:Adelaide Strikers cricketers]]\n[[Category:People from Khulna]]\n[[Category:Asian Games medalists in cricket]]\n[[Category:Cricketers at the 2014 Asian Games]]\n[[Category:Asian Games bronze medalists for Bangladesh]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2014 Asian Games]]\n[[Category:Asian Games competitors for Bangladesh]]\n[[Category:Karachi Kings cricketers]]\n[[Category:Peshawar Zalmi cricketers]]\n[[Category:Bangladesh Test cricket captains]]\n[[Category:Jamaica Tallawahs cricketers]]\n[[Category:Legends of Rupganj cricketers]]\n[[Category:Kala Bagan Krira Chakra cricketers]]\n[[Category:Prime Bank Cricket Club cricketers]]\n[[Category:Abahani Limited cricketers]]\n[[Category:Rangpur Riders cricketers]]\n[[Category:Bangladesh under-19 cricketers]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Bangladesh National Sports Award]]\n[[Category:People from Magura District]]\n[